Numerical Solutions and System of Linear Equations
Others - Trigonometry and Applications of Trigonometry
Summation of Series - Method of Difference

Integration of Rational Functions by using Partial Fractions
Using Probability Table (Standard Results of P(A'), P(AUB) and P(A|B))
Poisson Approximation to the Binomial Distribution

fields.content: By means of the substitution \[y = 8^{x}\], or otherwise, find the exact values of $$x$$ which satisfy the equation \[64^{x} - 5(8^{x}) + 4 = 0\].

A smooth curve passes through the points $$(1, 2)$$, $$(1.5, 2.8)$$, $$(2, 3.4)$$, $$(2.5, 3.8)$$ and $$(3, 3.6)$$ as shown in the diagram. Use the trapezium rule with four intervals to find an approximate value for the area of the region between the curve, the x-axis and the lines $$x = 1$$ and $$x = 3$$. State with a reason, whether this approximate value is greater than or less than the true area of the region.

img;;The diagram shows a cube with each side of length 1 unit. The base ABCD lies in a horizontal plane, the edges AE, BF, CG and DH are vertical, and EFGH is the top of the cube. Calculate the size of the angle which the diagonal BH makes with the base ABCD, giving your answer to the nearest degree.
The points A, B and C have position vectors given respectively by;\[a = 2i + 3j + 4k\], \[b = 5i - 2j + k\], \[c = 3i + 5j + 2k\].;Calculate angle ABC, giving your answer to the nearest degree.
By completing the square, find the greatest and least values, as \[\Theta\] varies, of \[\cos ^{2} - \cos \Theta + 6\].
Solve the inequality \[|1 + x| < 3\].;Hence write down the solution of \[-4 < |1 + x| < 3\].
Given that \[6x^{3} + cx^{2} - 29x + d\] is divisible by both \[2x - 1\] and \[x + 3\], find the value of c and the value of d.

Given that $$x$$ is sufficiently small for \[x^{3}\] and higher powers of $$x$$ to be neglected, and that \[\cos x - 4\sin x = 6x\], show that a quadratic equation for $$x$$ is \[x^{2} + 20x - 2 = 0\].;Hence find an approximate value for $$x$$, giving your answer correct to 3 significant figures.
Find the general solution, in radians, of the equation \[7\sin^{2}x - \cos^{2}x = 1\].

The number 105 840 can be expressed in prime factors as \[2^{4} \times 3^{3} \times 5^{1} \times 7^{2}\].;Excluding 1 and 105 840, how many positive integers are factors of 105 840? [Hint: one factor of 105 840 is 90, which can be expressed as \[2^{1} \times 3^{2} \times 5^{1} \times 7^{0}\]].

Express \[5\sin\theta + 12\cos\theta\] in the form \[R\sin(\theta + \alpha)\], where \[R\] is positive and \[\alpha\] is acute, giving the value of \[\alpha\] to the nearest \[0.1^\circ\].;Hence solve the equation \[6\sec\theta - 5\tan\theta = 12\], for values of \[\theta\] lying between \[0^\circ\] and \[360^\circ\], giving your answers to the nearest  \[0.1^\circ\].

In this question, you may use the result \[\frac{\mathrm{d} }{\mathrm{d} x} (\sec x) = \sec x \tan x\].;It is given that \[y = \ln (\sec x)\].;(i) Prove that \[\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\mathrm{d} x^{2}} = \sec^{2}x\].;(ii) Find Maclaurin's series for y in ascending powers of x, up to and including the term in \[x^{4}\].

(a) A sector containing an angle of \[\frac{1}{4}\pi\] radians is cut from a circular piece of paper of radius r, as shown in Fig. 1. The straight edges of the paper which remains are then brought together, without overlapping, to form a cone, as shown in Fig. 2. The semi-vertical angle of this cone is denoted by \[\theta\]. Calculate the size of this semi-vertical angle, giving your answer in radians, correct to 3 significant figures.;(b) The point D on the side BC of triangle ABC is such that \[BD = \frac{2}{3} BC\]. Angle \[ABD = 60^\circ\], AB = c, BC = a, AC = b and AD = x (see Fig. 3).;(i) By considering triangle ABD, prove that \[9x^{2} = 9c^{2} - 4a^{2} + 6ax\].;(ii) By considering also triangle ACD, deduce that \[x = \frac{a^{2} + 3b^{2} - 3c^{2}}{3a}\].

(a) A piece of wire of length 8 cm is cut into two pieces, one of length x cm, the other of length (8 - x) cm. The piece of length x cm is bent to form a circle with circumference x cm. The other piece is bent to form a square with perimeter (8 - x) cm. Show that, as x varies, the sum of the areas enclosed by these two pieces of wire is a minimum when the radius of the circle is \[\frac{4}{4 + \pi}\] cm.;(b) A spherical balloon is being inflated in such a way that its volume is increasing at a constant rate of \[150cm^{3}s^{-1}\]. At time t seconds, the radius of the balloon is r cm.;(i) Find \[\frac{\mathrm{d} r}{\mathrm{d} t}\] when r = 50.;(ii) Find the rate of increase of the surface area of the balloon when its radius is 50cm.;[The formulae for the volume and surface area of a sphere are \[V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^{3}\], \[A = 4\pi r^{2}\].]

A bank has an account for investors. Interest is added to the account at the end of each year at a fixed rate of 5% of the amount in the account at the beginning of that year. A man and a woman both invest money.;(a) The man decides to invest $$x$$ at the beginning of one year and then a further $$x$$ at the beginning of the second and each subsequent year. He also decides that he will not draw any money out of the account, but just leave it, and any interest, to build up.;(i) How much will there be in the account at the end of 1 year, including the interest?;(ii) Show that, at the end of n years, when the interest for the last year has been added, he will have a total of \[\$ 21(1.05^{n} - 1)x\] in his account.;(iii) After how many complete years will he have, for the first time, at least $$12x$$ in his account?;(b) The woman decides that, to assist her in her everyday expenses, she will withdraw the interest as soon as it has been added. She invests $$y$$ at the beginning of each year. Show that, at the end of n years, she will have received a total of \[\$ \frac {1}{40} n(n + 1)y\] in interest.

O is the origin and A is the point on the curve \[y = \tan x\] where \[x = \frac {1}{4} \pi\]. Show that the area of the region enclosed by the chord OA and the arc OA of the curve is \[\frac {1}{8} \pi - \ln \sqrt{2}\].;(b) A portion of the curve \[ay = x^{2}\], where a is a positive constant, is rotated about the vertical axis Oy to form the curved surface of an open bowl. The bowl has a horizontal circular base of radius r and a horizontal circular rim of radius 3r. Prove that the depth of the bowl is \[\frac {8r^{2}}{a}\]. ;Find the volume of the bowl in terms of r and a.;Given that the volume of the bowl is \[\frac {1}{10} \pi a^{3}\], find the depth of the bowl in terms of a only.

(i) Express \[f(x) = \frac {3x + 5}{(x + 1)(x + 2)(x + 3)}\] in partial fractions.;(ii) Given that x is sufficiently small for \[x^{3}\] and higher powers of x to be neglected, show that \[f(x) \approx \frac {5}{6} - \frac {37}{36}x + \frac {227}{216}x^{2}\].;(iii) Use the quadratic approximation in (ii) to estimate the value of \[\int_{0}^{0.1} f(x)dx\].;(iv) Prove, by induction or otherwise, that \[\sum_{r=1}^{n} \frac {3r + 5}{(r+1)(r+2)(r+3)} = \frac {7}{6} - \frac {3n + 7}{(n+2)(n+3)}\].

Find;(i) \[\int \frac {1}{1 + \cos 2x} dx\],;(ii) \[\int x^{2} e^{3x} dx\],;(iii)\[\int_{0}^{2} \frac {x^{2}}{1 + x^{6}} dx\], by using the substitution \[y = x^{3}\], giving your answer correct to 3 decimal places.

(a) Given that \[x^{2} - 2xy + 2y^{2} = 4\], find an expression for \[\frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x}\] in terms of x and y. Find the coordinates of each point on the curve \[x^{2} - 2xy + 2y^{2} = 4\] at which the tangent is parallel to the x-axis.;(b) A curve is defined by the parametric equations \[x = t^{2}, y = t^{3}\]. Show that the equation of the tangent to the curve at the point \[P(p^{2}, p^{3})\] is \[2y - 3px + p^{3} = 0\]. Show that there is just one point on the curve at which the tangent passes through the point (-3, -5), and determine the coordinates of this point.
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics

In this question give each of your answers either as an exact fraction in its lowest terms or as a decimal corrects to 3 places.;There are 36 people at a gathering of two families. There are 25 people with the name Lee and 11 people with the name Chan. Of the 25 people named Lee, 4 are single men, 5 are single women and there are 8 married couples. Of the 11 people named Chan, 2 are single men, 3 are single women and there are 3 married couples. Two people are chosen at random from the gathering. ;(i) Show that the probability that they both have the name Lee is  .;(ii) Find the probability that they are married to each other.;(iii) Find the probability that they both have the name Lee, given that they are married to each other.;(iv) Find the probability that they are a man and a woman with the same name.;(v) Find the probability that they are married to each other, given that they are a man and a woman with the same name;

In a large population the proportion having blood group A is 35%. Specimens of blood from the first five people attending a clinic are to be tested. It can be assumed that these five people are a random sample from the population. The random variable X denotes the number of people in the sample who are found to have blood group A.;(i) Show that  , correct to 3 decimal places.;(ii) Three such samples of five people are taken. Find;(a) The probability that each of these three samples has more than two people with blood group A;(b) The probability that one of these three samples has exactly one person with blood group A, another has exactly two people with blood group A, and the remaining sample has more than two people with blood group A.;One hundred such samples of five people are taken. Using a suitable approximation, find the probability that the number of these samples that contain two or fewer people with blood group A will be at least 70.;

1.8, and the corresponding figure for "Xanadu" sets is 2.7. Sales take place independently at random times.;(i) Find the probability that exactly 2 "Kubla" sets are sold in a given week. [1];(ii) Find the probability that exactly 4 "Kubla" sets are sold in a given two-week period. [2];(iii) Find the probability that total number of television sets sold in a given week is at least 4. [4];(b) The random variable X has a Poisson distribution with mean ?. Denoting  by P(X = r) by $${{p}_{r}}$$ show that;       $$\frac{{p}_{r+1}}{{p}_{r}} = \frac{\lambda}{r+1}$$  [3];Deduce that $${{p}_{r+1}}$$ > $${{p}_{r}}$$  when  r < $$\lambda + 1$$ .      [1];Deduce the values of r for which $${{p}_{r}}$$ is greatest in the cases;(i) $$\lambda$$ = 12.3;(ii) $$\lambda$$ = 15

The random variable X has probability density function f given by;f(x) = $$\frac{3}{32} \left( 4 - {x}^{2}\right)$$  -2 <= x =< 2 ;f(x) = 0 otherwise;Show that Var(X) = $$\frac{4}{5}$$;The random variable Y is defined by Y = aX + b, where a and b are positive constants. It is given that E(Y) = 50 and Var(Y) = 80. Find a and b.;A random sample consists of 160 independent observations of Y. Find an approximate value for the probability that the sample mean lies between 49.0 and 50.5.;

A horticulturist takes a random sample of 80 bean seeds of a particular variety, and sows them under standard laboratory conditions. The number of the seeds that germinate is 64. Find an approximate 90% confidence interval for the probability that a randomly chosen bean seed of the particular variety will germinate under the same conditions.;The total crop weight, x kg, of each of the 64 plants is measured, with the following summarized results: $$\sum x$$ = 3003.4;$$\sum x^{2}$$ = 1615.96  . Find unbiased estimates of the population mean and variance of crop weight per plant.;The horticulturist wishes to test the hypothesis that the mean crop weight per plant is 5kg, against the alternative hypothesis that the mean crop weight per plant is less than 5kg. Carry out the test at the 10% level of significance. ; Find the largest level of significance at which the test would result in rejection of the null hypothesis.;

The diagram (not drawn to scale) shows a sketch of the curve C with polar equation \[r = a(1 + 6\cos \theta), -\beta \leq \theta \leq \beta\], where a is a positive constant and \[\cos \beta = - \frac {1}{6}\]. Cartesian axes are taken at the pole O, with Ox along the initial line, and Oy along the line \[\theta = \frac {1}{2} \pi\].;Express y in terms of \[\theta\] and hence show that the maximum value of y on C is \[(\frac {5}{3} \sqrt{5})a\].;Express x in terms of \[\cos \theta\] and, by completing the square or otherwise, show that the minimum value of x on C is \[- \frac {1}{24}a\].;\[A = a^{2}\int_{0}^{\frac {1}{2} \pi} (19 + 12\cos \theta + 18 \cos 2\theta)d \theta\].;Hence find A.

The diagram shows a sketch of the graph of y = f(x). On separate diagrams sketch the graphs of;(i) \[y = |f(x)|\],;(ii) \[y^{2} = -f(x)\].;(b) A graph has equation \[y = \frac {8}{(3x - 2)(x + 2)}\].;Find the coordinates of the stationary point of the graph.;State the equations of all the asymptotes and hence sketch the graph.

On a single diagram sketch the graphs of \[y = \pi \sin x\] and \[y = \pi - x\], for \[-3\pi \leq x\leq 3\pi\], and hence state the number of real roots of the equation \[\pi \sin x = \pi - x\].;The smallest positive root is denoted by \[\alpha\] and the largest positive root is denoted by \[\beta\].;(i) Express \[\beta\] in terms of \[\alpha\].;(ii) Find an approximate value for \[\beta\] by using linear interpolation on the interval \[\frac {3}{2}\pi \leq x \leq 2\pi\].;(iii) Taking \[\frac {1}{4} \pi\] as a first approximation to \[\alpha\], apply the Newton-Raphson process once to find a second approximation to  \[\alpha\], giving three decimal places in your answer.;Giving a reason, determine whether \[\alpha\] is greater or less than this second approximation.

(a) Find the general solution of the differential equation \[\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} y}{\mathrm{d} x^{2}} + 2 \frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x} + 5y = 13 + 20y\].;(b) On a single Argand diagram sketch the loci given by;(i) \[|z - 3| = 4\],;(ii) \[|z - 3 - 3i| = |z|\].;Hence, or otherwise, find the exact values of all the complex numbers z that satisfy both (i) and (ii).

The plane \[\prod \] passes through the origin O and is perpendicular to 2i + 2j + k. The line L has cartesian equation \[\frac {x - 4}{1} = \frac {y - 8}{3} = \frac {z - 4}{2}\].;The points A and B have position vectors i + 2j - 3k and 3i + 5j + 2k respectively.;(i) State a cartesian equation for \[\prod \].;(ii) The point C on L has position vector c, where c.k = 0. Find c, and hence state an alternative equation for L of the form \[\frac {x - p}{1} = \frac {y - q}{m} = \frac {z}{n}\], giving numerical values for p, q, l, m and n.;(iii) Find the exact value of the length of the perpendicular from A to L.;(iv) Find, in either order, the exact value of the length of the projection of \[\overrightarrow{AB}\] onto;(a) the normal to  \[\prod \],;(b) the plane  \[\prod \].
The polynomial $$4{x}^{3} - 20{x}^{2} + 13x + 12$$  is denoted by f(x). Show that (x - 4) is a factor of f(x).;Hence, or otherwise, find all the solutions of f(x) = 0.;
A and B are two points on a circle with centre O and radius 5cm. Given that the length of the minor arc AB is 4cm, calculate the area of the sector AOB.;
The first term of a geometric progression is 10 and its sum to infinity is 15. Find the third term of the progression.;

Given that $$y = {e}^{x} \cos x $$, prove that $$\frac{d^2 y}{d x^2} = - 2 {e}^{x} \sin x $$, and hence find $$\frac{d^3 y}{d x^3}$$.;;Obtain Maclaurin's series for $${e}^{x} \cos x $$  up to and including the term in $${x}^{3}$$.;
The function f is defined by;f : $$x \mapsto 9 - {x}^{2},  x \in $$ R;Find the exact solutions of the equation ff(x) = 0.;
In this question, a "word' is defined to be any set of letters in a row, whether or not it makes sense. Find how many different "words" can be made using all 8 letters of the word SYLLABUS.;

A spherical balloon is being inflated and, at the instant when its radius is 3m, its surface area is increasing at the rate of 2 $${m}^{2}{s}^{- 1}$$. Find the rate of increase, at the same instant, of;(i) the radius,;(ii) the volume.;;[The formulae for the surface area and volume of a sphere are A = $$4\pi {r}^{2}$$  and V = $$\frac{4}{3}\pi{r}^{3}$$.];
Prove by induction that;$$\sum\limits_{r=1}^{n} r( r + 4 ) = \frac{1}{6}n( n + 1 )( 2n + 13 )$$;

Express $$2\sin t + ( 2\sqrt{3} )\cos t $$ in the form $$R\sin ( t + \alpha )$$, where 0 < $$\alpha$$ < $$\frac{1}{2}\pi$$.;What is the least value of $$\frac{1}{10 + 2\sin t + ( 2\sqrt{3} )\cos t}$$ as t varies?;
Given that the equation $$\cos \theta + \frac{31}{8}\theta = 0$$ has a root close to zero, use a quadratic approximation for $$\cos \theta$$ to estimate this root.;

Use the trapezium rule with 4 intervals, each of width 0.4, to find an approximate value for $$\int^{1.6}_0 x e^{x^2} \mathrm{d} x$$, giving your answer correct to 2 decimal places.;Calculate the exact value of $$\int^{1.6}_0 x e^{x^2} \mathrm{d} x$$, giving your answer in terms of e.

Express $$f( x ) = \frac{7 - 3x - {x}^{2}}{{( 1 - x )}^2 ( 2 + x )}$$ in partial fractions.;Hence or otherwise prove that, if $${x}^{3}$$ and higher powers of x may be neglected, then $$f( x ) = \frac{1}{8}( 28 + 30x + 41 {x}^{2} )$$.;

Relative to a fixed origin O, the points A, B and C have position vectors given respectively by a = 2i + 3j - k, b = 5i - 2j + 3k, c = 4i + j - 2k. Find;(i) the length of AB, correct to 3 significant figures,;(ii) angle BAC, correct to the nearest degree,;(iii) the area of triangle ABC, correct to 3 significant figures.;Show that, for all values of the parameter t, the point P with position vector p = (2 + 3t)i + (3 - 5t)j + (-1 + 4t)k lies on the line through A and B. Find p such that OP is perpendicular to AB.;

In this question, give your answers for lengths correct to 3 significant figures and for angles correct to the nearest degree.;(a) In triangle ABC, AB = 9cm, AC = 10cm and angle ACB = $${60}^{0}$$. Find;(i) the two possible values of angle BAC,;(ii) the two possible lengths of BC.;;(b) Show that the equation $$2\sin x \cos x + 4 {\cos}^2 x = 1$$ may be written in the form $${\ tan}^2 x - 2\tan x - 3 = 0$$.;Hence find the general solution for x.;

(a) Given that x is real, prove that $$x^2 - 4x + 9$$  is always positive. Solve the inequality $$\frac{x^3 + 2 x^2 + x + 14}{x^2 + 5} > x + 1$$.;(b) Sketch, on separate diagrams, the graphs of;(i) y = |x - 1|,;(ii)y = |x - 1| + |x - 3|.;Hence or otherwise find the least value of |x - 1| + |x - 2| + |x - 3|, justifying your answer.;

The equation of a curve C is $$x^3 + xy + 2 y^3 = k$$, where k is a constant. Find  $$\frac{dy}{dx}$$ in terms of x and y.;It is given that C has a tangent which is parallel to the y-axis. Show that the y-coordinate of the point of contact of the tangent with C must satisfy $$216 {y}^{6} + 4 {y}^{3} + k = 0$$.;Hence show that  $$k \leq \frac{1}{54}$$.;Find the possible values of k in the case where the line x = -6 is a tangent to C.;It is given instead that C has a tangent which is parallel to the x-axis. Show that $$k \leq \frac{1}{54}$$ in this case also.;

The curve C is given parametrically by the equations $$x = 2 + t \text{ , } y = 1 - {t}^{2}$$.;Show that the normal at the point with parameter t has equation $$x - 2ty = 2 {t}^{3} - t + 2.$$;The normal at the point T, where t = 2, cuts C again at the point P, where t = p. Show that $$4{p}^{2} + p - 18 = 0$$ and hence deduce the coordinates of P.;Find the cartesian equation of C and hence sketch C.;;

(a) Given that $$x + 2 = A (2x + 2) + B$$ for all values of x, find the constants A and B. Hence or otherwise find $$\int \frac{x + 2}{x^2 + 2x + 5} dx$$.;(b) If  $$x = 4 {\cos}^2 \theta + 7 {\sin}^2 \theta$$, show that $$7 - x = 3 {\cos}^2 \theta$$, and find a similar expression for $$x - 4$$. By using the substitution $$x= 4 {\cos}^2 \theta + 7 {\sin}^2 \theta$$, evaluate $$\int^7_4 \frac{1}{\sqrt{{ ( x - 4 ) ( 7 - x ) }}} dx$$.;

(i) Find, correct to 3 significant figures, the coordinates of the turning point of the curve $$y = x + 3\sin x$$ for which $$0 \leq x \leq \pi$$. Hence sketch the curve for $$0 \leq x \leq \pi$$.;(ii) Find, in terms of $$\pi$$,;(a) $$\int^{\pi}_0 {\sin }^2 x dx$$,;(b) $$\int^{\pi}_0 x \sin x d x$$.;(iii) The region bounded by the curve $$y = x + 3 \sin x$$, the x-axis and the line $$x = \pi$$ is rotated through $$2\pi$$ radians about the x-axis. Find the volume of the solid of revolution so formed, giving your answer in terms of $$\pi$$ .;
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics
Particle Mechanics

A Personal Identification Number (PIN) consists of 4 digits in order, each of which is one of the digits 0,1,2,?,9. Susie has difficulty remembering her PIN. She tries to remember her PIN and writes down what she thinks it is. The probability that the first digit is correct is 0.8 and the probability that the second digit is correct is 0.86. The probability that the first two digits are both correct is 0.72. Find;(i) the probability that the second digit is correct given that the first digit is correct,;(ii) the probability that the first digit is correct and the second digit is incorrect,;(iii) the probability that the first digit is incorrect and the second digit is correct,;(iv) the probability that the second digit is incorrect given that the first digit is incorrect.;The probability that all four digits are correct is 0.7. On 12 separate occasions Susie writes down independently what she thinks is her PIN. Find the probability that the number of occasions on which all four digits are correct is less than 10. ;

A computer can give independent observations of a random variable X with probability distribution given by $$P(X=0) = \frac{3}{4}$$ and $$P(X=2) = \frac{1}{4}$$. It is programmed to output a value for the random variable Y defined by $$Y = {X}_{1}+ {X}_{2}$$, where $${X}_{1}$$ and $${X}_{2}$$ are independent observations of X. Tabulate the probability distribution of Y, and show that E(Y) = 1.;;The random variable T is defined by $$T= Y^2$$. Find E(T) and show that Var(T) = $$\frac{63}{4}$$.;;The computer is programmed to produce a large number n of independent values for T and to calculate the mean M of these values. Fine the smallest value of n such that P(M<3) > 0.99.;;

The continuous random variable X is such that:;img;Show that P(X>1) = 8/27.;Find the probability density function of X, and hence find E(X).;108 independent observations are taken of X.;(i) The number of observations greater that 2 is denoted by N. Using a suitable approximation, find $$P(3 < N < 6)$$;(ii) The number of observations greater than 1 is denoted by R. Using a suitable approximation, find $$P(24 < R < 40)$$.;

The random variable X has a normal distribution with mean 3 and variance 4. The random variable S is the sum of 100 independent observations of X, and the random variable T is the sum of a further 300 independent observations of X. Giving your answers to 3 places of decimals, find;(i) P(S > 310);(ii) P(3S > 50+T);The random variable N is the sum of n independent observations of X. State the approximate value of P(N > 3.5n) as n becomes very large, justifying your answer.;;

A coin is chosen at random from a population of recently produced coins. The discrete random variable X is the age, in years, of the coin. The population mean of X is denoted by $$\hat{\mu}$$, the population standard deviation is denoted by $$\hat{\sigma}$$, and the population proportion for which X-1is denoted by p. A random sample of 120 independent observations of X was taken and the results can be summarized as follows.;img;;(i) Calculate unbiased estimates of $$\hat{\mu}$$, $$\hat{\sigma^2}$$ and $$\hat{p}$$.;(ii) Find a symmetric 95% confidence interval for $$\mu$$.;(iii) It is desired to find a symmetric 95%confidence interval for $$\hat{\sigma^2}$$, of width 0.2, using a random sample of n coins. Estimate the smallest possible value for n.;(iv) Using a 10%significance level, test the null hypothesis p=0.4 against the alternative hypothesis p<0.4.

(a) The curve C has polar equation \[r = \frac {a}{\theta}\], for \[0 < \theta \leq 2\pi\],  where a is a positive constant. Give a reason why, if r is large, \[r\sin \theta \approx a\].Deduce the cartesian equation of the asymptote of C.;Sketch C.;Find the area of the sector bounded by C and the lines \[\theta = \frac {1}{2} \pi\] and \[\theta = \frac {3}{2} \pi\].;(b) The cartesian equation of a curve is \[3(x - 1)^2 + 4y^2 = 12\]. Show that \[-1 \leq x \leq 3\], and find the range of possible values of y.;Find the polar equation of this curve, expressing r in terms of \[\theta\].

(a) By eliminating w, or otherwise, solve the simultaneous equations \[z - w + 3i + 2, z^2 -iw + 5 - 2i = 0\].;(b) The complex number q is given by \[q = \frac {e^{i\theta}}{1 - e^{i\theta}}\], where \[0 < \theta < 2\pi\]. In either order,;(i)find the real part of q,;(ii) show that the imaginary part of q is \[\frac {1}{2} \cot (\frac {1}{2}\theta)\].

(a) Find the general solution of the differential equation \[\frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x} + 3x(y^2 + 4) = 0\], expressing y in terms of x.;(b) Find the value of the constant a such that \[y=axe^{3x}\] is a particular integral of the differential equation \[\frac{\mathrm{d}^2 y}{\mathrm{d} x^2} + \frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x} - 12y = 7e^{3x}\].;Solve the differential equation given that when x = 0, y = 3 and \[\frac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d} x} = - 4\].

Find the equations of the asymptotes of the graph \[y = \frac {3 - 2x}{x - 2}\], and sketch the graph.;On the same diagram sketch the graph of \[y = 1 - e^{-2x}\]. Show that, where the graphs intersect, \[(3x + 5)e^{2x} = x - 2\], and hence state the number of real roots of this equation. Taking x = 1.7 as a first approximation, use the Newton-Raphson method once to obtain a second approximation to one of the roots of the equation. Give 3 significant figures in your answer.;Use the method of linear interpolation once, on the interval [-0.5, -0.4], to obtain an approximation to another root of the equation. Give 3 significant figures in your answer.

Three vertical flagpoles, OF, AG, BH, stand with their bases on horizontal ground. The flagpoles have heights 10m, 14m, 18m, and their bases are O, A, B respectively, where OA = 4m and OB = 8m, and angle AOB is a right angle. Referred to an origin O, the position vectors of four non-collinear points A, B, C and D are a, b, c and d respectively. Given that a - b = d - c, show that ABCD is a parallelogram. Given also that |a - c| = |b - d|, identify the shape of the parallelogram ABCD, justifying your answer.

Deduce that f(0-x) = f(0+x);;$$\Rightarrow$$ f(x) is symmetrical about x=0;$$\begin{align};  & \therefore E\left( X \right)=0 \\ ; & E\left( {{X}^{2}} \right)=\int_{-\infty }^{\infty }{{{x}^{2}}f\left( x \right)dx} \\ ; & =\int_{-2}^{2}{\left[ {{x}^{2}}\frac{3}{32}\left( 4-{{x}^{2}} \right) \right]dx} \\ ; & =\frac{3}{32}\int_{-2}^{2}{\left[ 4{{x}^{2}}-{{x}^{4}} \right]dx} \\ ; & =\frac{3}{32}\left[ \frac{4}{3}{{x}^{3}}-\frac{1}{5}{{x}^{5}} \right]_{-2}^{2} \\ ; & =\frac{3}{32}\left[ \frac{4}{3}{{\left( 2 \right)}^{3}}-\frac{1}{5}{{\left( 2 \right)}^{5}}-\frac{4}{3}{{\left( -2 \right)}^{3}}+\frac{1}{5}{{\left( -2 \right)}^{5}} \right] \\ ; & =\frac{4}{5} \\ ; & Var\left( X \right)=E\left( {{X}^{2}} \right)-{{\left[ E\left( X \right) \right]}^{2}}=\frac{4}{5}-{{0}^{2}}=\frac{4}{5} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};  & E\left( Y \right)=E\left( aX+b \right)=aE\left( X \right)+b=0+b=b \\ ; & \therefore E\left( Y \right)=50\Rightarrow b=50 \\ ; &  \\ ; & Var\left( Y \right)=Var\left( aX+b \right)={{a}^{2}}Var\left( X \right)=\frac{4}{5}{{a}^{2}} \\ ; & \therefore Var\left( Y \right)=80\Rightarrow \frac{4}{5}{{a}^{2}}=80\Rightarrow {{a}^{2}}=100 \\ ; & \Rightarrow a=10,(a>0) \\ ;\end{align}$$;;Let n = sample size = 160;Let $$\mu =E\left( Y \right)=50$$;Let $${{\sigma }^{2}}=Var\left( Y \right)=80$$;Since n(=160) is large, Centre Limit Theorem;$$\begin{align};  & \Rightarrow \overline{Y}\tilde{\ }N\left( \mu ,{{\sigma }^{2}}/n \right) \\ ; & P\left( 49.0<\overline{Y}<50.5 \right) \\ ; & \equiv P\left( \frac{49.0-\mu }{\sigma /\sqrt{n}}<Z<\frac{50.5-\mu }{\sigma /\sqrt{n}} \right) \\ ; & =P\left( \frac{49.0-50}{\sqrt{80/160}}<Z<\frac{50.5-50}{\sqrt{80/160}} \right) \\ ; & =P\left( -1.4142<Z<0.7071 \right) \\ ; & =\phi \left( 0.707 \right)-\left[ 1-\phi \left( 1.414 \right) \right] \\ ; & =0.7601-\left[ 1-0.9213 \right] \\ ; & =0.6814=0.681 \\ ;\end{align}$$

Let n = sample size = 80;Let p = proportion of seeds that germinate;;$$\begin{align};  & \widehat{p}=\frac{64}{80}=0.8 \\ ; & \widehat{q}=1-\widehat{p}=0.2 \\ ; & {{z}_{0.05}}\sqrt{\frac{\widehat{p}\widehat{q}}{n}}=1.645\sqrt{\frac{\left( 0.8 \right)\left( 0.2 \right)}{80}}=0.07357 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;The 90% confidence interval for p is;\[\begin{align};  & \left[ \widehat{p}-{{z}_{0.05}}\sqrt{\frac{\widehat{p}\widehat{q}}{n}},\widehat{p}+{{z}_{0.05}}\sqrt{\frac{\widehat{p}\widehat{q}}{n}} \right] \\ ; & =\left[ 0.8-0.07357,0.8+0.07357 \right] \\ ; & =\left[ 0.726,0.873 \right] \\ ;\end{align}\];;Let n = sample size = 64;Let $$\mu $$ = population mean of x;Let $${{\sigma }^{2}}$$ = variance of x;$$\begin{align};  & \widehat{\mu }=\overline{x}=\frac{\sum{x}}{n}=\frac{303.4}{64}=4.741=4.74 \\ ; &  \\ ; & {{\sigma }^{2}}=\frac{1}{n-1}\left[ {{\sum{{{x}^{2}}-\left( \frac{1}{n}\sum{x} \right)}}^{2}} \right] \\ ; & =\frac{1}{63}\left[ 1615.96-\frac{1}{64}{{\left( 303.4 \right)}^{2}} \right] \\ ; & =2.8199=2.82 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;Let $${{\mu }_{0}}$$ =  assumed mean = 50;Test $${{H}_{0}}$$ : $$\mu ={{\mu }_{0}}$$ against H1: $$\mu <{{\mu }_{0}}$$ ;a 1-tailed test for less;The 10% critical value, $${{z}_{0.10}}$$ = 1.282;Reject $${{H}_{0}}$$ if z<-$${{z}_{0.10}}$$;Under $${{H}_{0}}$$ , the test statistic is;$$z=\frac{\overline{x}-{{\mu }_{0}}}{\widehat{\sigma }/\sqrt{n}}=\frac{4.74-5}{\sqrt{2.82/64}}=-1.239$$;Since $$z > - {{z}_{0.10}}$$, do not reject $${{H}_{0}}$$ and conclude that, at the 10% level of significance, there is no significant evidence that the mean crop weight is less than 5kg.;;$${{H}_{0}}$$ is rejected if  $$z < -{{z}_{a}}$$, i.e. ;$$\begin{align};  & -1.239<-{{z}_{\alpha }}\equiv {{z}_{\alpha }}<1.239 \\ ; & \Rightarrow \alpha <1-\phi \left( 1.239 \right)=1-0.8924=0.1076 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;Largest significance level for rejection = 10.8%

Let Pn denotes $$\sum\limits_{r=1}^{1}{r\left( r+4 \right)}=1\left( 1+4 \right)=5$$;;For n=1,;$$\begin{align};  & LHS=\sum\limits_{r=1}^{1}{r\left( r+4 \right)}=1\left( 1+4 \right)=5 \\ ; & RHS=\frac{1}{6}\left( 1 \right)\left( 1+1 \right)\left[ 2\left( 1 \right)+13 \right]=5=LHS \\ ;\end{align}$$;;P1 is true;Assume Pk is true for $$k\in {{Z}^{+}}$$,;i.e. $$\sum\limits_{r=1}^{k}{r\left( r+4 \right)}=\frac{1}{6}k\left( k+1 \right)\left( 2k+13 \right)$$;For n=k+1;$$\begin{align};  & RHS=\frac{1}{6}\left( k+1 \right)\left[ \left( k+1 \right)+1 \right]\left[ 2\left( k+1 \right)+13 \right] \\ ; & LHS=\sum\limits_{r=1}^{k+1}{r\left( r+4 \right)} \\ ; & =\sum\limits_{r=1}^{k}{r\left( r+4 \right)}+\left( k+1 \right)\left( k+1+4 \right) \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}k\left( k+1 \right)\left( 2k+13 \right)+\left( k+1 \right)\left( k+1+4 \right) \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}k\left( k+1 \right)\left( 2k+13 \right)+\left( k+1 \right)\left( k+5 \right) \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}\left( k+1 \right)\left[ k\left( 2k+13 \right)+6\left( k+5 \right) \right] \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}\left( k+1 \right)\left[ 2{{k}^{2}}+19k+30 \right] \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}\left( k+1 \right)\left( k+2 \right)\left( 2k+15 \right) \\ ; & =\frac{1}{6}\left( k+1 \right)\left[ \left( k+1 \right)+1 \right]\left[ 2\left( k+1 \right)+13 \right]=RHS \\ ;\end{align}$$;;Pk+1 is true if Pk is true.;Therefore, by mathematical induction, Pn is true for all $$n\in {{Z}^{+}}$$

(a);(i) $$K \cup H$$ represents the event that the card taken is either a King or a Heart.;$$P(K \cup H) = \frac{2 + 3 + 1 + 3 + 3 + 2}{30}$$;$$=\frac{14}{30} = \frac{7}{15}$$;;(ii) $$J' \cap H'$$ represents the event that the card taken is not a Jack and not a Heart.;$$P(J' \cap H') = \frac{2 + 1 + 3 + 3 + 5 + 2}{30}$$;$$=\frac{16}{30} = \frac{8}{15}$$;;(iii) Let D  = card taken is a Diamond.;$$P( D|K ) = \frac{P(D \cap K)}{P(K)}$$;$$=\frac{1}{2 + 3 + 1 + 3} = \frac{1}{9}$$;;(b);P( both cards are Jacks);$$=\frac{8}{30} . \frac{7}{29} = 0.0644 = 0.064$$;;(c);P( 3 Kings or 3 Queens or 3 Jacks);$$=\frac{9}{30}.\frac{8}{29}.\frac{7}{28} + \frac{13}{30}.\frac{12}{29}.\frac{11}{28} + \frac{8}{30}.\frac{7}{29}.\frac{6}{28}$$;$$= 0.1049 = 0.105$$ (ans)

$$F(4) = a\left[ 6({4})^{2} - 4^3\right]$$ and F(4) = 1;$$\Rightarrow a(32) = 1$$;$$\therefore a = \frac{1}{32}$$;;$$f(x) = \frac{d}{dx}\left[F(x)\right]$$;$$=\frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{1}{32}(6{x}^{2} - {x}^{3})\right]$$ for $$0 \le x \le 4$$;$$=\frac{1}{32}(12x - 3{x}^{2}) = \frac{3}{32}(4x - {x}^{2})$$;$$\therefore$$ \[ f(x) = \left\{ ;  \begin{array}{l l};    \frac{3}{32}(4x - {x}^{2}) & \quad \text{for} 0 \le x \le 4\\;    0 & \quad \text{otherwise};  \end{array} \right.\];;f(x) is symmetrical about x = 2;$$\Rightarrow E(X) = 2$$;;$$E(X^2) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}{x}^{2}f(x)dx$$;$$=\int_{0}^{4}\left[x^2.\frac{3}{32}(4x - {x}^{2})\right]dx$$;$$=\frac{3}{32}\int_{0}^{4}(4{x}^{3} - {x}^{4})dx$$;$$=\frac{3}{32}{\left[x^4 - \frac{1}{5}x^5\right]}_{0}^{4}$$;$$=\frac{3}{32}\left[4^4 - \frac{1}{5}4^5\right] - 0 = \frac{24}{5}$$;$$\therefore Var(X) = E(X^2) - {\left[E(X)\right]}^2$$;$$=\frac{24}{5} - {2}^{2} = \frac{4}{5}$$;;Let n = no. of observations = 100;Let $$\mu$$ = E(X) = 2;Let $$\sigma^2$$ = Var(X) = $$\frac{4}{5}$$;;P( S > 185);$$\equiv P\left[(\sum\limits_{i=1}^{100}X) > 185\right] = P\left[\frac{1}{100}(\sum\limits_{i=1}^{100}X) > \frac{185}{100}\right]$$;$$\equiv P(\overline{X} > 1.85)$$;;Since n ( = 100) is large, Central Limit Theorem;$$\Rightarrow \overline{X} \sim N(\mu, {\sigma}^2/n)$$ approximately;$$P(\overline{X} > 1.85)$$;$$\equiv P( Z > \frac{1.85 - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}) = P( Z > \frac{1.85 - 2}{\sqrt{\frac{4}{5}/100}})$$;$$=P( Z > - 1.6771) = \Phi (1.677)$$;$$= 0.9532 = 0.953$$ (ans)

(a);Let n = sample size = 225;Let p = average proportion of rockets that fail to burn properly = $$\frac{1}{75}$$;Let X = no. of rockets out of n that fail to burn properly;;Since n ( = 225) is large and np = 3 < 5,;$$X \sim Po(\lambda) \text{ approximately, where }\lambda = np = 3$$;P ( at most 221 burn properly);$$\equiv P( X \ge 4 )$$;$$= 1- P( X < 4 )$$;$$= 1 - \left[P( X = 1 ) + P( X = 2 ) + P( X = 3 ) + P( X = 0 )\right]$$;$$= 1 - e^{-\lambda}\left[\frac{\lambda^0}{0!} + \frac{\lambda^1}{1!} + \frac{\lambda^2}{2!} + \frac{\lambda^3}{3!}\right]$$;$$= 1 - e^{-3}\left[1 + 3 + \frac{3^2}{2!} + \frac{3^3}{3!}\right]$$;$$= 0.3528 = 0.353$$ (ans);;The distribution that should be used is the Binomial distribution, i.e. $$X \sim B( n,p )$$. ;;(b);Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$\mu$$ = mean burning time;Let $${\sigma}^2$$ = variance of the burning time;Let $${\mu}_{0}$$ = assumed $$\mu$$ = 40;;$$\hat{\mu} = \overline{x} = \frac{\sum ( x - c)}{n} + c$$;$$= \frac{-27}{50} + 40 = 39.46$$;;$${\hat{\sigma}}^2 = \frac{1}{n-1}\left[\sum ( x-c )^2 - \frac{1}{n}(\sum ( x-c))^2\right]$$;$$ = \frac{1}{49}\left[ (167) - \frac{1}{50}(-27)^2\right] = 3.1106$$;;Test $${H}_{0}$$ : $$\mu = {\mu}_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1}$$ : $$\mu \neq {\mu}_{0}$$;a 2 tailed test for difference;The 5% critical value, $${z}_{0.05} = 1.960$$;Reject $${H}_{0}$$ if $$| z | > | {z}_{0.05} |$$;Under $${H}_{0}$$, the test statistic is,;$$z = (\frac{\overline{x} - \mu}{\hat{\sigma}/\sqrt{n}}) = (\frac{39.46 - 40}{sqrt{3.1106/50}}) = - 2.165$$;;Since $$| z | > | {z}_{0.05} |$$, reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that at 5% level of significance, there is significant evidence that the mean burning time differs from 40 seconds.;If the sample size is large (generally $$\ge$$ 50 ), the Central Limit Theorem implies that regardless of the population's distribution, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed. Therefore, in the above test, it is not necessary to assume, that the burning times of 'Brilliant' fireworks have a normal distribution. (ans)

(i);$$\begin{align};  & {{\tan }^{-1}}x+{{\tan }^{-1}}y+{{\tan }^{-1}}\left( xy \right)=\frac{7}{12}\pi  \\ ; & Where \\ ; & x=1, \\ ; & {{\tan }^{-1}}\left( 1 \right)+{{\tan }^{-1}}y+{{\tan }^{-1}}\left[ \left( 1 \right)y \right]=\frac{7}{12}\pi  \\ ; & \frac{1}{4}\pi +2{{\tan }^{-1}}y=\frac{7}{12}\pi  \\ ; & 2{{\tan }^{-1}}y=\frac{7}{12}\pi -\frac{1}{4}\pi =\frac{1}{3}\pi  \\ ; & {{\tan }^{-1}}y=\frac{1}{6}\pi  \\ ; & \therefore y=\tan \frac{1}{6}\pi =\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;(ii);$$\frac{d}{dx}\left[ {{\tan }^{-1}}\left( xy \right) \right]=\frac{1}{{{\left( xy \right)}^{2}}+1}\left( x\frac{dy}{dx}+y \right)$$;;(iii);$$\begin{align};  & \frac{d}{dx}\left[ {{\tan }^{-1}}x+{{\tan }^{-1}}y+{{\tan }^{-1}}\left( xy \right) \right]=\frac{d}{dx}\left[ \frac{7}{12}\pi  \right] \\ ; & \frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}+1}+\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}+1}\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{1}{{{\left( xy \right)}^{2}}+1}\left( x\frac{dy}{dx}+y \right)=0 \\ ; & \frac{1}{{{x}^{2}}+1}+\left[ \frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}+1}+\frac{x}{{{\left( xy \right)}^{2}}+1} \right]\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{y}{{{\left( xy \right)}^{2}}+1}=0 \\ ; & When:x=1,y=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \\ ; & \Rightarrow \frac{1}{\left( 1 \right)+1}+\left[ \frac{1}{\left( \frac{1}{3} \right)+1}+\frac{\left( 1 \right)}{\left( \frac{1}{3} \right)+1} \right]\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{\left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \right)}{\left( \frac{1}{3} \right)+1}=0 \\ ; & \frac{1}{2}+\frac{3}{2}\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{3}{4\sqrt{3}}=0 \\ ; & \frac{3}{2}\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{1}{2}-\frac{3}{4\sqrt{3}} \\ ; & \therefore \frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{1}{3}-\frac{1}{2\sqrt{3}} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;

(i) $$\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{9-{{x}^{2}}}\equiv A+\frac{B}{3-x}+\frac{C}{3+x}$$;By long division,;;$$\begin{align};  & \frac{{{x}^{2}}}{9-{{x}^{2}}}=-1+\frac{9}{9-{{x}^{2}}}\Rightarrow A=-1 \\ ; & \therefore \frac{9}{9-{{x}^{2}}}\equiv \frac{9}{\left( 3-x \right)\left( 3+x \right)}\equiv \frac{B}{3-x}+\frac{C}{3+x} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;Cover-up rule:;$$\begin{align};  & x=3:B=\frac{9}{3+3}=\frac{3}{2} \\ ; & x=-3:C=\frac{9}{3-\left( -3 \right)}=\frac{3}{2} \\ ; & \therefore \frac{{{x}^{2}}}{9-{{x}^{2}}}\equiv -1+\frac{3}{2\left( 3-x \right)}+\frac{3}{2\left( 3+x \right)} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;(ii);$$\begin{align};  & \int_{0}^{2}{\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{9-{{x}^{2}}}dx} \\ ; & =\int_{0}^{2}{\left( -1+\frac{9}{{{3}^{2}}-{{x}^{2}}} \right)dx} \\ ; & =\left[ -x+\frac{9}{2\left( 3 \right)}\ln \left( \frac{3+x}{3-x} \right) \right]_{0}^{2} \\ ; & =\left[ \left( -2+\frac{3}{2}\ln 5 \right)-\left( 0+\frac{3}{2}\ln 1 \right) \right] \\ ; & =\frac{3}{2}\ln 5-2 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;(iii);$$\begin{align};  & \int_{0}^{2}{\ln \left( 9-{{x}^{2}} \right)dx} \\ ; & =\left[ \ln \left( 9-{{x}^{2}} \right)\left( x \right) \right]_{0}^{2}-\int_{0}^{2}{x\frac{\left( -2x \right)}{9-{{x}^{2}}}dx} \\ ; & =\left[ \ln \left( 9-{{2}^{2}} \right)\left( 2 \right)-0 \right]+2\int_{0}^{2}{\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{9-{{x}^{2}}}dx} \\ ; & =2\ln 5+2\left( \frac{3}{2}\ln 5-2 \right)=5\ln 5-4 \\ ;\end{align}$$;

(a) Let n = no, of observations = 50;Let $${\mu}_{0}$$ = assumed mean = 22;Let $$\sigma$$ = Var(X) = 36;Test $${H}_{0}$$ : $${\mu}$$ =  $${\mu}_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1}$$ : $${\mu}$$ < $${\mu}_{0}$$ ;a 1-tailed test for less;;The 1% critical value, $${z}_{0.01} = 2.326$$;Reject $${H}_{0}$$ if $$z < -{z}_{0.01}$$;Under $${H}_{0}$$ , the test statistic is ;$$z = \frac{\overline{x} - {\mu}_{0}}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} = \frac{20.2 - 22}{\sqrt{36 / 50}} = - 2.121$$;;Since $$z > - {z}_{0.01}$$, do not reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 1% level of significance there is no significant evidence that the mean $${\mu}$$ is less than 22.;;(b) Let p = proportion of the population who know the leader's name;Let $${n}_{1}$$ = sample size = 850;$$\hat{p} = \frac{124}{850} = \frac{62}{425}$$ ;$$\hat{q} = \frac{363}{425}$$ ;;$${z}_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p} \hat{q}}{{n}_{1}}} = 1.960\sqrt{\frac{( \frac{62}{425} ) ( \frac{363}{425} )}{850}} = 0.02373$$;;The 95% confidence interval for p is;$$[ \hat{p} - {z}_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p} \hat{q}}{{n}_{1}}} , \hat{p} + {z}_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p} \hat{q}}{{n}_{1}}} ]$$ ;$$ = [ \frac{62}{425} - 0.02373, \frac{62}{425}+ 0.02373 ]$$;$$ = [ 0.1222 , 0.1696 ]$$ ;$$ = [ 0.122, 0.170 ]$$ (ans);;Let $${n}_{2}$$ = sample size = 953;Let $${p}_{0}$$ = assumed p = 0.25;$$\hat{p} = \frac{263}{953}$$;Test $${H}_{0}$$ : $$p = {p}_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1}$$ : $$p > {p}_{0}$$;a 1-tailed test for more;The 5% critical value, $${z}_{0.05} = 1.645$$;Reject $${H}_{0}$$ if $$z > {z}_{0.05}$$;Under $${H}_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \frac{\hat{p} - {p}_{0}}{\sqrt{{p}_{0}{q}_{0} / {n}_{2}}} = \frac{\frac{263}{953} - 0.25}{\sqrt{( 0.25 ) ( 0.75 ) / 953}} = 1.852$$;;Since $$z > {z}_{0.05}$$, reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 5% level of significance, there is significant evidence that p > 0.25. Let B = a black die taken;Let R= a red ball taken;Let G = a green ball taken;;The probability tree is displayed:;img;;Probability of event M is happening given that event W was happened,;$$P( M|W ) = \frac{P(M \cap W)}{P(W)} = \frac{ P( WRG ) + P( WGR )}{P(W)}$$;$$ = \frac{\frac{3}{28} + \frac{3}{28}}{\frac{2}{5}} = \frac{15}{28}$$  (ans);;(i) $$P( M \cap W ) = P( WRG ) + P( WGR )$$;$$=\frac{3}{28} + \frac{3}{28} = \frac{3}{14}$$ (ans);;(ii) $$P( W|M ) = \frac{P( W \cap M)}{P(M)} = \frac{ P( WRG ) + P( WGR )}{P( WRG )+ P ( WGR ) + P( BRG ) + P( BGR ) }$$;$$ = \frac{\frac{3}{28} + \frac{3}{28}}{\frac{3}{28} + \frac{3}{28} + \frac{6}{35} + \frac{6}{35}} = \frac{15}{13}$$  (ans);;(iii) $$P( W \cup M )$$;$$ = P( W ) + P( BRG ) + P( BGR )$$;$$ = \frac{2}{5} + \frac{6}{35} + \frac{6}{35} = \frac{26}{35}$$ (ans);;In the container there are 20 objects comprising 2 white dice, 3 black dice, 9 red balls, and 6 green balls.;There are $$4!$$ ways to select the 4 objects.;$$\therefore$$ P( one object of each colour taken);$$= 4! \times \frac{2}{20} \times \frac{3}{20} \times \frac{9}{20} \times \frac{6}{20} = \frac{243}{5000}$$ (ans)

(a)$$\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x + 2x{y}^{2} = 2x ( 1 + y^2 )$$;$$\int \frac{dy}{1 + y^2 } = \int 2xdx$$;$${\tan }^{-1} y = {x}^{2} + c$$, c = constant;$$\therefore y = \tan (x^2 + c)$$;When $$x = 0$$ , $$y = 1$$;$$\Rightarrow 1 = \tan ( 0 + c )$$   $$\Rightarrow c = \frac{1}{4}\pi$$;$$\therefore y = \tan (x^2 + \frac{1}{4}\pi )$$ (ans);;(b) $$( 1 + x^2 )\frac{dy}{dx} + 4xy = \frac{4x}{( 1 + x^2  )^3}$$;$$\equiv \frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{4x}{( 1 + x^2 )}y = \frac{4x}{( 1 + x^2  )^4}$$;Let $$h(x) = \int \frac{4x}{( 1 + x^2 )}dx$$;             $$= 2 ln( 1 + x^2 ) = ln( 1 + x^2 )^2$$;$$\Rightarrow$$ integrating factor;$${e}^{h(x)} = {e}^{ln( 1 + x^2 )^2} = ( 1 + x^2 )^2$$ and;$${e}^{-h(x)} = {e}^{-ln( 1 + x^2 )^2} = \frac{1}{( 1 + x^2 )^2}$$;;$$\therefore$$ General solution is;$$y = {e}^{-h(x)}\left[\int {e}^{hx} \frac{4x}{(1 + x^2)^4}dx + c\right]$$, c = constant;   $$= \frac{1}{( 1 + x^2 )^2}\left[\int ( 1 + x^2 )^2 \frac{4x}{(1 + x^2)^4}dx + c\right]$$;   $$= \frac{1}{( 1 + x^2 )^2}\left[\int \frac{4x}{(1 + x^2)^2}dx + c\right]$$;   $$= \frac{1}{( 1 + x^2 )^2}\left[ - \frac{2}{(1 + x^2)} + c\right] = \frac{c(1 + x^2) - 2}{(1 + x^2)^3}$$;When $$x = 0$$ , $$y = 1$$;$$\Rightarrow 1 =  \frac{c(1 + 0^2) - 2}{(1 + 0^2)^3}$$  $$\Rightarrow c = 3$$;$$\therefore y = \frac{3(1 + x^2) - 2}{(1 + x^2)^3} = \frac{3{x}^{2} + 1}{(1 + x^2)^3}$$ (ans)

$$\sin 3\theta = \sin (2\theta + \theta)$$;$$= \sin 2\theta \cos \theta + \cos 2\theta \sin \theta$$;$$= 2\sin \theta \cos ^{2} \theta + (1 - 2\sin ^{2}\theta)\sin \theta$$;$$= 2\sin \theta(1 - \sin ^{2}\theta) + \sin \theta - 2\sin ^{3}\theta$$;$$=2\sin \ theta - 2\sin ^{3}\theta + \sin \theta - 2\sin ^{3}\theta$$;$$=3\sin \theta - 4\sin ^{3}\theta$$ (ans);;$$\sin 3\theta - \cos 2\theta$$;$$=(3 \sin \theta - 4\sin ^{3}\theta) - (1 - 2\sin ^{2}\theta)$$;$$=(3s - 4s^3) - ( 1 - 2s^2)$$;$$= - 1 + 3s + 2s^2 - 4s^3$$;$$=( 1 - s )(4s^2 + 2s - 1)$$ (ans);;With $$\theta = 18^0$$,;$$\sin 3\theta = \sin 3(18^0) = \sin 54^0 \equiv \cos (90^0 - 54^0)$$;$$=\cos 36^0 = cos2(18^0) \equiv \cos 2\theta$$;;$$\therefore \theta = 18^0$$ is an exact solution of $$\sin 3\theta  = \cos 2\theta$$. (ans);;$$\sin 3\theta = \cos 2\theta \equiv \sin 3\theta - \cos 2\theta = 0$$;$$\equiv ( 1 - s )(4s^2 + 2s - 1) = 0$$;where $$s = \sin \theta$$ and $$\sin 18^0$$ is a solution.;$$\Rightarrow s = 1$$ (NA, $$\theta = 90^0$$);or $$s = \frac{-2 \pm \sqrt{2^2 - 4(4)(-1)}}{2(4)} = \frac{-2 \pm \sqrt{20}}{8}$$;$$=\frac{1}{4}(-1 -\sqrt{5})$$ (NA, $$\sin 18^0 > 0$$ );or $$\frac{1}{4}(-1 + \sqrt{5})$$;$$\therefore \sin 18^0 = \frac{1}{4}(-1 + \sqrt{5})$$ (ans);;With $$\theta = 234^0$$,;$$\sin 3\theta = \sin 3(234^0) = \sin 702^0$$;$$=\sin (720^0 - 18^0) \equiv \sin -18^0$$;$$\equiv \cos (360^0 + 90^0 + 18^0) = \cos 468^0$$;$$=\cos 2(234^0) \equiv \cos 2\theta$$;$$\therefore \theta = 234^0$$ is another exact solution of $$\sin 3\theta = \cos 2\theta$$.;Since $$\sin 234^0 < 0$$, deduce that ;$$\sin 234^0 = \frac{1}{4}(-1 -\sqrt{5})$$ (ans)

(a)$$\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}\pi}\frac{7\cos x - 4\sin x}{\cos x + \sin x}dx$$;$$\equiv \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}\pi}\frac{\frac{3}{2}(\cos x + \sin x) + \frac{11}{2}(\cos x - \sin x)}{\cos x + \sin x}dx$$;$$= \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}\pi}\left[\frac{3}{2} + \frac{11}{2}\frac{\cos x - \sin x}{\cos x + \sin x}\right]dx$$;$$=\left[\frac{3}{2}x + \frac{11}{2}\ln (\cos x + \sin x)\right]_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}\pi}$$ ;$$=\left[\frac{3}{2}(\frac{1}{2}\pi) + \frac{11}{2}\ln (0 + 1)\right] - \left[\frac{3}{2}(0) + \frac{11}{2}\ln  (1 + 0)\right]$$;$$=\frac{3}{4}\pi$$ (ans);;(b)$$\int_{1}^{e}(\ln x)^2dx$$;$$=\left[x(\ln x)^2\right]_{1}^{e} - \int_{1}^{e}\left[x.2(\ln x)\frac{1}{x}\right]dx$$;$$=\left[e(\ln e)^2 - (1)(\ln 1)^2\right] - 2\int_{1}^{e}left[\ln x]dx$$;$$=\left[e - 0\right] - 2\left[x.(\ln x)\right]_{1}^{e} - 2\int_{1}^{e}\left[x.\frac{1}{x}\right]dx$$;$$=e - 2(\left[e.(\ln e) - (1)(\ln 1)\right] - \int_{1}^{e}dx)$$;$$=e - 2(\left[e - 0\right] -\left[e - 1\right]) = e - 2$$ (ans);;(c) With $$x = \frac{1}{y} \equiv y = \frac{1}{x}$$ , $$dx = -\frac{1}{y^2}dy$$;$$\int \frac{1}{x\sqrt{ x^2  - 1}}dx$$;$$\equiv \int \frac{1}{\frac{1}{y}\sqrt{(\frac{1}{y})^2 - 1}}( -\frac{1}{y^2})dy$$;$$= - \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1- y^2}}dy$$;$$= - \sin ^{-1}y + c$$, c = constant;$$= - \sin ^{-1}\frac{1}{x} + c$$ (ans)

Let $$O$$ = apex of pyramid;Let $$A$$,$$B$$,$$C$$,$$D$$ = corners of square base;Let $$P$$ = foot of perpendicular from O to base ABCD;Let $$M$$ = foot of perpendicular from O to edge AB;;img;;(i) Height of the pyramid is given by $$OP$$;$$OP = MP \tan \angle OMP = (\frac{1}{2}a)\tan 30^0$$;$$= (\frac{1}{2}a)(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}) = \frac{a}{2\sqrt{ 3}}$$ (ans);;(ii) Length of sloping edge is given by $$OA$$.;$$\Delta OPM$$:;$$OM = MP / \cos \angle OMP = (\frac{1}{2}a)/\cos 30^0$$;$$= (\frac{1}{2}a)/(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}a$$;$$\Delta OAM$$:;$$OA = \sqrt{AM^2 + OM^2} = \sqrt{(\frac{1}{2}a)^2 + (\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}a)^2 }$$;$$= \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}a^2 + \frac{1}{3}a^2} = a\sqrt {\frac{7}{12}}$$ (ans);;(iii) Let $$N$$ = foot of perpendicular from $$B$$ to edge $$OC$$;Angle between two adjacent triangular faces is given by $$\angle BND$$.;;$$\sin \angle NCB \equiv \sin \angle OAM = \frac{OM}{OA} = \frac{\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}a}{\sqrt{\frac{7}{12}}a} = \sqrt{\frac{4}{7}}$$;$$BN = BC\sin \angle NCB = \sqrt{\frac{4}{7}}a$$;$$DN \equiv BN = \sqrt{\frac{4}{7}}a$$;;$$\Delta BCD$$: $$BD^2 = BC^2 + CD^2 = a^2 + a^2 = 2a^2$$;Cosine rule on $$\Delta BND$$:;$$BD^2 = BN^2 + DN^2 - 2.BN.DN.\cos \angle BND$$;$$2a^2 = \frac{4}{7}a^2 + \frac{4}{7}a^2 - 2(\sqrt{\frac{4}{7}}a)(\sqrt{\frac{4}{7}}a)\cos \angle BND$$;$$\cos \angle BND = - \frac{3}{4}$$;$$\angle BND = 138.6^0 = 139^0$$ (ans)

(a) Let $$L$$ = length of cylinder = $$20x$$;When $$x = 5$$ , $$\frac{dx}{dt} = 0.025$$;;(i) Rate of increase of length of cylinder,;$$\frac{dL}{dt} = \frac{d}{dt}[20x] = 20\frac{dx}{dt}$$;$$= 20 (0.025) = 0.50 cms^{-1}$$;;(ii) Let $$V$$ = volume of cylinder = $$xL = 20x^2$$;Rate of increase of the volume of the cylinder,;$$\frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{d}{dt}[20x^2] = 40x\frac{dx}{dt}$$;$$= 40(5)(0.025) = 5.0 cm^{3}s^{-1}$$ (ans);;(iii) Let $$r$$ = radius of the cylinder = $$\sqrt{\frac{x}{\pi}}$$;Rate of increase of the radius of the cylinder,;$$\frac{dr}{dt} = \frac{d}{dt}[\sqrt{\frac{x}{\pi}}] = \frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi x}}\frac{dx}{dt}$$;$$=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\frac{1}{\pi (5)}}(0.025) = 0.04954$$;$$= 0.0495 cms^{-1}$$ (ans);;(b);img;;Volume formed when $$R$$ is rotated about the $$x-axis$$, $${V}_{x}$$;$$=\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{4}\pi}(\pi {y}_{2}^{2} - \pi {y}_{1}^{2})dx$$;$$=\pi \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{4}\pi}(\cos ^{2}x - \sin ^{2}x)dx$$;$$=\pi \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{4}\pi}\cos 2xdx$$;$$=\pi\left[\frac{1}{2}\sin 2x\right]_{0}^{\frac{1}{4}\pi}$$;$$=\pi \left[\frac{1}{2} - 0\right] = \frac{1}{2}\pi$$ (ans);;

$$F( x ) = \int_{- \infty}^{x} f( t )d t = \int^x_0 \frac{1}{a}dt$$  for $$0 \leq t \leq a$$;$$= \frac{1}{a}x$$;;\[ F(x) = \left\{ ;  \begin{array}{l l};    0 & \quad x < 0\\;    \frac{1}{a}x & \quad 0 \leq x \leq a\\;    1 & \quad x > a;  \end{array} \right.\];;(i) $$L < x$$ if and only if $${X}_{1} < x$$ and $${X}_{2} < x$$;$${F}_{L}( x ) = P ( L < x ) \equiv P ( {X}_{1} < x ) \times P ( {X}_{2} < x )$$ ;$$ = \frac{1}{a}x \times \frac{1}{a}x$$ ;$$ = \frac{1}{a^2} x^2$$;;Cumulative distribution function of L,;\[ {F}_{L}(x) = \left\{ ;  \begin{array}{l l};    0 & \quad x < 0\\;    \frac{1}{a^2}x^2 & \quad 0 \leq x \leq a\\;    1 & \quad x > a;  \end{array} \right.\];;(ii) ;$${f}_{L}( x ) = \frac{d}{dx} [ {F}_{L}( x ) ] = \frac{d}{d x}[ \frac{1}{a^2} x^2 ]$$ ;$$ = \frac{2x}{a^2}$$;;$$\therefore$$ Probability density function of $$L$$,;\[ {f}_{L}(x) = \left\{ ;  \begin{array}{l l};    \frac{2x}{a^2} & \quad 0 \leq x \leq a\\;    0 & \quad \text{otherwise};  \end{array} \right.\];;(iii) ;$$E( L ) = \int^\infty_{-\infty} x{f}_{L}( x )dx$$ ;$$ = \int^a_0 x ( \frac{2}{a^2}x )dx  = \frac{2}{a^2}\int^a_0 x^2 dx$$ ;$$ = \frac{2}{a^2}{[ \frac{1}{3}x^3 ]}^a_0 = \frac{2}{a^2}[ \frac{1}{3}a^3 ] = \frac{2}{3}a$$ (ans);;$$E( L^2 ) =  \int^\infty_{-\infty} x^2{f}_{L}( x )dx$$ ;$$ = \int^a_0 x^2 ( \frac{2}{a^2}x )dx  = \frac{2}{a^2}  \int^a_0 x^3dx$$ ;$$ = \frac{2}{a^2}{[ \frac{1}{4}x^4 ]}^a_0 = \frac{2}{a^2}[ \frac{1}{4}a^4 ] = \frac{1}{2}a^2$$; ;$$ Var( L ) = E( L^2 )- [ E ( L ) ]^2$$ ;$$ = \frac{1}{2}a^2 - [ \frac{2}{3}a ]^2 = \frac{1}{18}a^2$$ (ans);;(iv) ;Let $$m$$ = median of $$L$$;$$\Rightarrow P( L \leq m ) = \frac{1}{2} \equiv F( m ) = \frac{1}{2}$$ ;$$\Rightarrow \frac{1}{a^2}m^2 = \frac{1}{2}$$;$$\therefore m = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}a$$ (ans)

Let $$8\sin \theta  + 15\cos \theta$$;$$ = R\sin ( \theta  + \alpha  )$$;$$ = R\sin \theta\cos \alpha + R\cos \theta\sin \alpha$$;;Comparing coefficients:;$$\sin \theta: 8 = R\cos \alpha$$;$$\cos \theta: 15 = R\sin \alpha$$;$$\Rightarrow R = \sqrt{8^2 + {15}^2} = 17$$;$$\tan \alpha = \frac{15}{8} \Rightarrow \alpha = 61.92 = 61.9$$;;$$\therefore 8\sin \theta  + 15\cos \theta \equiv 17\sin (\theta + 61.9^0)$$ (ans);;(i) $$8\sin \theta  + 15\cos \theta \equiv 17\sin (\theta + 61.9^0)$$ has greatest value when $$\sin (\theta + 61.9^0) = 1$$,;i.e its greatest value = $$17(1) = 17$$ (ans);;(ii)$$\frac{1}{20 + 8\sin \theta  + 15\cos \theta} \equiv \frac{1}{20 + 17\sin (\theta + 61.9^0)}$$ has greatest value when $$\sin (\theta + 61.9^0) = -1$$;i.e its greatest value $$ = \frac{1}{20 + 17(-1)} = \frac{1}{3}$$ (ans);;(iii)$$\frac{1}{20 + ( 8\sin \theta  + 15\cos \theta  )^2 } \equiv \frac{1}{20 + (17\sin (\theta + 61.9^0))^2 }$$ has greatest value when $$\sin (\theta + 61.9^0) = 0$$, i.e its greatest value;$$ = \frac{1}{20 + (17(0))^2 } = \frac{1}{20}$$ (ans)

(i) $$P ( A \cap B ) = P ( B \lvert A ) \cdot P ( A ) = \frac{1}{8} \cdot \frac{1}{5} = \frac{1}{40}$$;(ii) $$P ( B ) = P ( B \lvert A ) \cdot P ( A ) + P ( B \lvert A \prime ) \cdot P ( A \prime )$$;$$  = \frac{1}{40}+ \frac{1}{10}\cdot \frac{4}{5}= \frac{21}{200}$$;(iii) $$P ( A \cup B ) = P ( A ) + P ( B ) - P ( A \cap B )$$; $$  = \frac{1}{5}+ \frac{21}{200}- \frac{1}{40}= \frac{7}{25}$$;(iv) $$P ( A \lvert B ) = \frac{P ( A \cap B )}{P ( B )} = \frac{( \frac{1}{40} )}{( \frac{21}{200} )} = \frac{5}{21}$$

Answer:;Let $$\mu$$ = E(X) = 1;Let $$\sigma^2$$ = Var(X) = 20;$$X ~ N(\mu,\sigma^2)$$;;(i) $$P ( X < a ) = 2P ( X > a )$$ ;$$ P(X < a) = 2 [ 1 - P(X < a) ] $$;$$ 3P ( X < a ) = 2$$ ;$$ P(X < a) = \frac{2}{3}$$;$$ P ( z < \frac{a - \mu}{\sigma} ) = \frac{2}{3} \equiv \Phi ( \frac{a - \mu}{\sigma} ) = \frac{2}{3}$$ ;$$ \frac{a - \mu}{\sigma}= \Phi^{- 1}(\frac{2}{3}) = 0.431$$ ;$$ a = \mu + 0.431\sigma = ( 1 ) + 0.431\sqrt{20}$$ ;$$ = 2.927 = 2.93$$ (ans);;(ii) Let  $$\overline{x}$$ = sample mean of n observations;$$\overline{x} \sim N ( \mu , \sigma^2 / n )$$ ;$$ P(\overline{x} > 1.5) \leq 0.01$$ ;$$ \equiv P ( \overline{x} < 1.5 ) > 1 - 0.01 = 0.99$$ ;;$$ \Rightarrow P(z < \frac{1.5 - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}) > 0.99 \equiv \Phi ( \frac{1.5 - \mu}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} ) > 0.99$$ ;$$ \frac{1.5 - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}> \Phi^{- 1}(0.99) = 2.326 $$;$$ \sqrt{n} = \frac{2.326\sigma}{1.5 - \mu} = \frac{2.326\sqrt{20}}{1.5 - 1} = 20.80 $$;$$ n >(20.80)^2 = 432.64$$;;$$\therefore P (\overline{x} > 1.5 ) \leq 0.01, n \geq 433$$ (ans)

Let $$X$$ = no. of sports cars served in 1 hr;$$X \sim Po(2)$$;Let Y = no. of motor-cycles served in 1 hr ;$$Y \sim Po(1)$$;Let $$Z$$ = no. of sports cars and motor-cycles served in a randomly chosen period of 2 hr ;$$     = {X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2}$$;where $${X}_{i}$$ = independent observations of X;     $${Y}_{i}$$ = independent observations of Y;Let $$\lambda = E(Z) = E({X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2})$$;$$      = 2E(X) + 2E(Y) = 2(2) + 2(1) = 6$$;;$$Z \sim P0(\lambda)$$;$$P ( Z \geq 4 )$$ ;$$ = 1 - P(Z \leq 3)$$ ;$$ = 1 - [ P ( Z = 0 ) + P ( Z = 1 ) + P ( Z = 2 ) + P ( Z = 3 ) ]$$ ;$$ = 1 - e^{- \lambda}[ \frac{\lambda^0}{0 !}+ \frac{\lambda^1}{1 !}+ \frac{\lambda^2}{2 !}+ \frac{\lambda^3}{3 !}] $$;$$ = 1 - e^{- 6} [ 1 + 6 + \frac{6^2}{2 !} + \frac{6^3}{3 !} ]$$;$$ = 0.8487 = 0.849$$ (ans);;Let $$C$$ = cost of petrol supplied to sport cars;$$C \sim U ( 10 , 100 )$$ ;$$ \Rightarrow E(C) = \frac{1}{2}(10 + 100) = 55 $$;$$ \Rightarrow Var ( C ) = \frac{1}{12} ( 100 - 10 )^2 = 675 $$;;Let $$D$$ = cost of petrol supplied to motor cycle;$$D \sim U ( 5 , 35 )$$ ;$$ \Rightarrow E(D) = \frac{1}{2}(5 + 35) = 20$$ ;$$ \Rightarrow Var ( D ) = \frac{1}{12} ( 35 - 5 )^2 = 75$$;Let $$T$$ = cost of petrol supplied to a random sample consisting of 4 cars and 2 motor cycles;$$ = {C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2}$$;where $${C}_{i}$$ = independent observations of C;     $${D}_{i}$$ = independent observations of D;;$$ E(T)  = E({C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2})$$ ;$$ = 4E ( C ) + 2E ( D )$$ ;$$ = 4(55) + 2(20) = 260$$ (ans); ;$$ Var ( T ) = Var ( {C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2} )$$ ;$$ = 4Var(C) + 2Var(D)$$ ;$$ = 4 ( 675 ) + 2 ( 75 ) = 2850$$ (ans)

Let $$n$$ = sample size = 80;Let $$\mu = E(x)$$;Let $$\sigma^2 = Var(x)$$;$$\hat{\mu} = \overline{x} = \frac{\sum x}{n} = \frac{79.53}{80} = 0.9941$$ ;$$ \hat{\sigma}^2 = \frac{1}{n - 1}[ \sum x^2 - \frac{1}{n}(\sum x)^2 ]$$ ;$$ = \frac{1}{79} [ 100.4621 - \frac{1}{80} ( 79.53 )^2 ] = 0.2709$$;;Let $$\mu_{0}$$ = required mean = 1.10kg;Test $${H}_{0}: \mu = \mu_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1} : \mu < \mu_{0}$$ a 1 tailed test for less;The 4% critical value, $${z}_{0.04} = 1.751$$ ;Reject $${H}_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_{0}}{\hat{\sigma} / \sqrt{n}} = \frac{0.9941 - 1.10}{\sqrt{0.2709 / 80}} = - 1.819$$;Since $$z < - {z}_{0.04}$$, reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that, at 4% level of significance, there is sufficient evidence that the mean mass of the contents is less than 1.10 kg.;;Alternative test is :;Test $${H}_{0}: \mu = \mu_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1} : \mu \neq \mu_{0}$$ a 2 tailed test for difference;At 4% significance level, critical value $${z}_{0.02} = 2.054$$;$${H}_{0}$$ is rejected if $$| z | > |{z}_{0.02}|$$;$$\lvert \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_0}{\hat{\sigma} / \sqrt{n}} \lvert > 2.054$$ ;$$ \lvert \overline{x} - \mu_0 \lvert > 2.054 \hat{\sigma}/\sqrt{n}$$;$$ \lvert 0.9941 - \mu_0 \lvert > 2.054\sqrt{0.2709 / 80} = 0.1195$$ ;$$ 0.9941 - \mu_0 < - 0.1195 $$ or $$ 0.9941 - \mu_0 > 0.1195$$ ;;$$ \mu_0 > 1.1136$$ or  $$\mu_0 < 0.8746$$ (ans)

$$f:x\mapsto \frac{6x}{x+3},x\ge 0$$;(i) Let y = f'(x);$$\begin{align};  & \Rightarrow f\left( y \right)=x \\ ; & \frac{6y}{y+3}=x \\ ; & 6y=x\left( y+3 \right) \\ ; & y\left( 6-x \right)=3x \\ ; & y=\frac{3x}{6-x} \\ ; & \therefore f'\left( x \right)=\frac{3x}{6-x} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;(ii) Range of f, $${{R}_{f}}=\left\{ x:0\le x\le 6 \right\}$$;;(iii) Sketch $$y=\frac{6x}{x+3},x\ge 0$$;At x = 0, y = 0;$$f\left( x \right)=\frac{6x}{x+3}\equiv 6-\frac{18}{x+3}$$;As $$x\to \infty ,f\left( x \right)\to 6-0=6$$;img;;Equation of its asymptote is y = 6;;(iv) Shade bounded region (above):;img;;Area of bounded region (shaded);$$\begin{align};  & =\int\limits_{0}^{6}{ydx}=\int\limits_{0}^{6}{\frac{6x}{x+3}dx} \\ ; & \equiv \int\limits_{0}^{3}{\left( 6-\frac{18}{x+3} \right)dx} \\ ; & =\left[ 6x \right]_{0}^{3}-18\left[ \ln \left( x+3 \right) \right]_{0}^{6} \\ ; & =36-18\ln 3 \\ ;\end{align}$$

Let $$\frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}\left( x+2 \right)}\equiv \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{B}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}}+\frac{C}{x+2}$$;Clearing the fractions:;$$\begin{align};  & 9{{x}^{2}}\equiv A\left( x-1 \right)\left( x+2 \right)+B\left( x+2 \right)+C{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}} \\ ; & =\left( A+C \right){{x}^{2}}+\left( A+B-2C \right)x+\left( -2A+2B+C \right) \\ ;\end{align}$$;Cover-up rule:;$$\begin{align};  & x=-2:C=4 \\ ; & x=1:B=3 \\ ;\end{align}$$;Comparing coefficients:;$$\begin{align};  & {{x}^{2}}:9=A+C \\ ; & \Rightarrow A=5 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;$$\therefore \frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}\left( x+2 \right)}\equiv \frac{5}{x-1}+\frac{3}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}}+\frac{4}{x+2}$$;;$$\begin{align};  & \therefore \int\limits_{2}^{3}{\frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}\left( x+2 \right)}dx}\equiv \int\limits_{2}^{3}{\left( \frac{5}{x-1}+\frac{3}{{{\left( x-1 \right)}^{2}}}+\frac{4}{x+2} \right)dx} \\ ; & =\left[ 5\ln \left( x-1 \right)-\frac{3}{x-1}+4\ln \left( x+2 \right) \right]_{2}^{3} \\ ; & =5\ln 2-\frac{3}{2}+4\ln 5-5\ln 1+3-4\ln 4 \\ ; & =\frac{3}{2}4\ln 5+5\ln 2-4\ln {{2}^{2}} \\ ; & =\frac{3}{2}4\ln 5-3\ln 2 \\ ;\end{align}$$;

$$\begin{align};  & y=\frac{{{x}^{3}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{2}}} \\ ; & \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{d}{dx}\left[ \frac{{{x}^{3}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{2}}} \right]=\frac{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{2}}\left( 2{{x}^{2}} \right)-\left( {{x}^{3}} \right)2\left( x+1 \right)}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{4}}} \\ ; & =\frac{2{{x}^{2}}\left( x+1 \right)\left( x+1-x \right)}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{4}}} \\ ; & =\frac{2{{x}^{2}}\left( x+1 \right)}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{4}}}=\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{3}}} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;At stationary pts, $$\frac{dy}{dx}=0$$;$$\begin{align};  & \Rightarrow \frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{3}}}=0 \\ ; & \Rightarrow x=0 \\ ;\end{align}$$;$$\begin{align};  & x={{0}^{-}},\frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{3}}}>0 \\ ; & x=0+,\frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\left( x+1 \right)}^{3}}}>0 \\ ;\end{align}$$;At x = 0, the stationary pt is a point of inflexion.;

$$\begin{align};  & \frac{dy}{dx}+y=x{{y}^{3}}\equiv \frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}=x} \\ ; & z=\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}},\frac{dz}{dx}=\frac{d}{dx}\left[ \frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}} \right]=-\frac{2}{{{y}^{3}}}\frac{dy}{dx} \\ ;\end{align}$$;Subst $$\frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\frac{dy}{dx}$$ and $$\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}$$ into $$\frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\frac{dy}{dx}+\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}=x$$:;$$\begin{align};  & -\frac{1}{2}\frac{dz}{dx}+z=x \\ ; & \therefore \frac{dz}{dx}-2z=-2x\\ ;\end{align}$$;;With $$z=\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}$$,;$$\frac{dy}{dx}+y=x{{y}^{3}}\equiv \frac{dz}{dx}-2z=-2x$$;Let $$h\left( x \right)=\int{\left( -2 \right)dx}=-2x$$ ;$$\Rightarrow$$ integrating factor = $${{e}^{h\left( x \right)}}={{e}^{-2x}}$$ and $${{e}^{-h\left( x \right)}}={{e}^{2x}}$$;;General solution is:;$$\begin{align};  & z={{e}^{-h\left( x \right)}}\left[ \int{{{e}^{h\left( x \right)}}\left( -2x \right)dx}+c \right] \\ ; & ={{e}^{2x}}\left[ {{e}^{-2x}}x-\int{{{e}^{-2x}}dx}+c \right] \\ ; & ={{e}^{2x}}\left[ {{e}^{-2x}}x+\frac{1}{2}{{e}^{-2x}}+c \right] \\ ; & =x+\frac{1}{2}+c{{e}^{2x}} \\ ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};  & \equiv \frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}=\frac{1}{2}+x+c{{e}^{2x}} \\ ; & i.e. \\ ; & \left( \frac{1}{2}+x+c{{e}^{2x}} \right){{y}^{2}}=1 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;At x = 0, $$y=\sqrt{2}$$;$$\begin{align};  & \Rightarrow \left( \frac{1}{2}+0+c{{e}^{0}} \right)\left( 2 \right)=1 \\ ; & \Rightarrow 1+2c=1\Rightarrow c=0 \\ ;\end{align}$$;Particular solution is ;$$\begin{align};  & \left( \frac{1}{2}+x \right){{y}^{2}}=1 \\ ; & \Rightarrow y=\sqrt{\frac{2}{1+2x}} \\ ;\end{align}$$

Let $$\angle$$PXQ = $$\theta$$;Sine rule on $$\Delta$$PQX:;$$\frac{x}{\sin{\alpha}} = \frac{\lambda}{\sin{\theta}} \Rightarrow x = \frac{\lambda \sin{\alpha}}{\sin{\theta}}$$;Sine rule on $$\Delta$$PXR:;$$\frac{y}{\sin{\alpha}} = \frac{\mu}{\sin{(\pi-\theta)}} \equiv \frac{\mu}{\sin{\theta}}\Rightarrow y = \frac{\mu\sin{\alpha}}{\sin{\theta}}$$;$$\therefore \frac{\left(\frac{\lambda \sin{\alpha}}{\sin{\theta}}\right)}{\left(\frac{\mu\sin{\alpha}}{\sin{\theta}}\right)} = \frac{a}{b} = \frac{\lambda}{\mu}$$

Let a = $$1^{st}$$ term of G.P.;Let r = common ratio of G.P.;Let $$T_i$$ = $$i^{th}$$ term of G.P. (= $$ar^{i-1}$$);;Population at end of 1995 ($$T_1$$) = 46650;$$\Rightarrow a = 46650$$;;Population at end of 2000 ($$T_6$$) = 54200;$$\Rightarrow ar^{5}$$ = 54200;;$$\begin{align};i.e. \\;&(46650)r^{5} = 54200 \\;& r^{5} = 1.1618 \\;&\therefore r = 1.030;\end{align}$$;;(i) Population at end of 2006,;$$T_{12} = ar^{11} = (46650)(1.030)^{11} = 64574 = 64570(4 sf)$$;;(ii) Let n = year in which the population reaches 100000;$$\begin{align};& T_n = ar^{n-1} > 100000 \\;& \Rightarrow (46650)(1.030)^{n-1} > 100000\\;& (1.030)^{n-1} > 2.143\\;& n-1 > \frac{\ln{2.143}}{\ln{1.030}} = 25.78\\;& n > 26.78\\;&\therefore n=27 ;\end{align}$$

No. of ways to place 10 canisters on 10 bases;= $$^{10}\textrm{P}_{10}$$ = 10! = 3 628 800;;(i) No. of ways to place 2 particular canisters on remaining 6 bases (not A, E, F or J);= $$^{6}\textrm{P}_{2} = \frac{6!}{(6-2)!}$$ = 30;No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases;= $$^{8}\textrm{P}_{8}$$ = 8! = 40 320;$$\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters ;= 30 x 40 320 = 1 209 600;;(ii) ;Case 1:;1st particular canisters is placed in one of 4 corner bases (A, E, F or J),;2nd particular canisters can be placed in any of 8 bases (not next to the 1st on the same side);No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases = 40 320;$$\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters; = 4 x 8 x 40 320 = 1 290 240;;Case 2:;1st particular canisters is placed in one of 6 non-corner bases (not A, E, F or J),;2nd particular canisters can be placed in any of 7 bases (not next to the 1st on the same side);No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases = 40 320;$$\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters; = 6 x 7 x 40 320 = 1 693 440;;$$\therefore$$ Total no. of ways to place the canisters; = 1 290 240 + 1 693 440; = 2 983 680

a) $$f(\theta) = \sin^{2}{\theta} - 6 \sin{\theta} + 4 \equiv (\sin{\theta} - 3)^{2} - 5$$;Deduce that $$f(\theta)$$ is greatest when $$ \sin{\theta = -1} \equiv (\sin{\theta} -3) = -4$$;i.e. $$f(\theta)_{greatest} = (-4)^{2} -5 = 11$$;Deduce that $$f(\theta)$$ is least when $$\sin{\theta} = 1 \equiv (\sin{\theta} -3) = -2$$;i.e. $$f(\theta)_{least} = (-2)^{2} -5 = -1$$;;b) ;$$\begin{align} &\sin{(A+B)} = 2 \cos{(A-B)}\\;& \Rightarrow \sin{A} \cos{B} + \cos{A}\sin{B} = 2(\cos{A}\cos{B} + \sin{A}\sin{B}) \\;&\equiv \frac{\sin{A} \cos{B}}{\cos{A}\cos{B} } + \frac{\cos{A}\sin{B} }{\cos{A}\cos{B} } = 2\left(1+\frac{ \sin{A}\sin{B}}{\cos{A}\cos{B}}\right)\\;& \tan{A} + \tan{B} = 2 + 2 \tan{A}\tan{B}\\;& \frac{1}{3} + \tan{B} = 2 + \frac{2}{3} \tan{B}\\;& \left(1-\frac{2}{3}\right)\tan{B} = 2 - \frac{1}{3}\\;&\therefore \tan{B} = 5;\end{align}$$

Given $$P(A \cup B)$$ = 0.9, $$P(A \cap B)$$ = 0.2, and P(A|B) = 0.8.;;$$\begin{align};& P(A \cap B) = P(A | B).P(B) \\;& i.e. 0.2 = 0.8 P(B) \\;& \Rightarrow P(B) = 0.25 \\;& P ( A \cup B ) = P ( A ) + P ( B ) - P ( A \cap B ) \\;& i.e. 0.9 = P(A) + 0.25 - 0.2 \\;& \therefore P ( A ) = 0.85 \\;& P(B \prime) = 1 - P(B) = 1 - 0.25 = 0.75\\;\end{align}$$

Let X = mass of an apple of variety A;Let Y = mass of an apple of variety B;X ~ N(0.125,0.022), Y ~ N(0.100,0.032);Let C = $$(X_{1}+ X_{2}+ X_{3}) + (Y_{1}+ Y_{2}+ Y_{3}+ Y_{4})$$;where $$X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{3}$$ are masses of 3 randomly chosen apples of variety A, and $$Y_{1}, Y_{2}, Y_{3}, Y_{4}$$ are masses of 4 randomly chosen apples of variety B.;$$\begin{align};&Let \mu_c = E (C) \\ ;&= E((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\ ;&= 3E ( X ) - 4E ( Y ) \\ ;&= 3(0.125) - 4(0.100) = - 0.025 \\ ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};&Let \sigma_c^2 = Var ( C ) \\ ;&= Var((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\ ;&= 3Var ( X ) + 4Var ( Y ) \\ ;&= 3({0.02}^2) + 4({0.03}^2) = 0.0048 \\;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};&C \sim N ( \mu_c , \sigma_c^2 ) \\ ;&P((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) >(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\ ;&\equiv P ( ( X_1 + X_2 + X_3 ) - ( Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4 ) > 0 ) \\ ;&\equiv P(C > 0) \\ ;&\equiv P ( Z > \frac{0 - \mu_c}{\sigma_c} ) = P ( Z > \frac{0 - ( - 0.025 )}{\sqrt{0.0048}} ) \\ ;&= P(Z > 0.3608) \equiv 1 - \Phi(0.3608) \\ ;&= 1 - 0.6410 = 0.3590 = 0.359 (3sf);\end{align}$$

Let $$p_{9} = 9^{th}$$ percentile of X;$$\begin{align};& F( p_9 ) = 0.09 \\;& \frac{1}{81}(p_9)^2 = 0.09 \\;& \therefore p_9 = 2.7 ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};& f(x) = \frac{d}{dx} F(x) \\;& =  \frac{d}{dx}[\frac{1}{81} x^2 ] \\;&= \frac{2}{81}x, for 0 \leq x \leq 9 \\;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};& E (\sqrt{X}) = \int^\infty_{-\infty} \sqrt{x}f (x)dx \\;& =   \int^9_0 \sqrt{x} \left( \frac{2}{81}x \right)dx, for 0 \leq x \leq 9 \\;& =   \int^9_0 \frac{2}{81} x^{3 / 2}dx \\;& = {\left[ \frac{4}{405} x^{5 / 2}\right]}^9_0   = \frac{12}{5}\\;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};& E ( X ) = \int^\infty_{- \infty}x.f(x) dx \\;& = \int^9_0 x(\frac{2}{81}x) dx \\;& = \int^9_0 \frac{2}{81}x^2 dx \\;& = {[ \frac{2}{243} x^3 ]}^9_0 = 6 \\;\end{align}$$;$$\begin{align};& Var(\sqrt{X}) = E(X) - [ E(\sqrt{X}) ]^2 \\;& = 6 - ( \frac{12}{5} )^2 = 0.24 \\;\end{align}$$

A suitable model for the distribution of Y is uniform (or rectangular) distribution.;;Let M = total mass of batch = $$\sum \left(x_{i} + \frac{y_{i}}{1000}\right)$$;$$\begin{align};& E(M) = E\left[\sum \left(x_{i} + \frac{y_{i}}{1000}\right)\right] \\;& =\left(\sum x_{i}\right) + \frac{E(\sum y_{i})}{1000} \\;& =\left(\sum x_{i}\right) + \frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align};& Y \sim U (0,1000) \\;& \Rightarrow E(Y) = \frac{1}{2}(0, 1000) = 500 \\;& \therefore E(M) = (\sum x_{i} ) + \frac{60(500)}{1000} = (\sum x_{i} ) + 30;\end{align}$$;;Given Var(Y) = $$\frac{10^{6}}{12}$$;$$P(\left(\sum x_{i}\right)+30$$ within $$\pm$$ 5kg of $$\sum \left(x_{i} + \frac{y_{i}}{1000}\right))$$;$$\equiv$$ P(30 within $$\pm$$ 5kg of $$\frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000}$$);$$\equiv P\left(25 < \frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35\right)$$;;$$\begin{align};& Let S = \frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000} \\;& E(S) = E\left(\frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000}\right) \\;& = \frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\;& = \frac{60(500)}{1000} = 30 \\;& Var(S) = Var\left(\frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000}\right) \\;& = \frac{60 Var(Y)}{{1000}^2} \\;& = \frac{60\left(\frac{{10}^6}{12}\right)}{{10}^6}= 5 \\;\end{align}$$;;Since batch size (=60) is large, S ~ N(30,5) approximately. ;$$\begin{align};& P ( 25 < \frac{\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35 ) \\;& \equiv P(25 < S < 35) \\;& \equiv P\left(\frac{25 - 30}{\sqrt{5}} < Z < \frac{35 - 30}{\sqrt{5}}\right) \\;& = P(- \sqrt{5}< Z < \sqrt{5}) \equiv 2 \Phi(\sqrt{5}) - 1 \\;& = 2\Phi ( 2.236 ) - 1 = 2 ( 0.9873 ) - 1 \\;& = 0.9746 = 0.975 (3sf)\\;\end{align}$$

A condition is that the moths are caught at randomly scattered intervals.;;Let M = no. of moths caught in an evening ;Let $$\lambda$$=E(M)=3.5;M ~ Po($$\lambda$$);P(5 or more moths caught in an evening);P ( M $$\geq$$ 5 ) ;$$\equiv$$ 1 - P(M $$\leq$$ 4) ;= 1 - [P(M=0) + P(M=1) + P(M=2) + P(M = 3) + P(M = 4)] ;= 1 - $$e^{- \lambda} \left[ \frac{\lambda^0}{0 !} + \frac{\lambda^1}{1 !} + \frac{\lambda^2}{2 !} + \frac{\lambda^3}{3 !} + \frac{\lambda^4}{4 !}\right]$$ ;= 1 - $$e^{- 3.5} \left[ 1 + 3.5 + \frac{(3.5)^2}{2}+ \frac{(3.5)^3}{6}+ \frac{(3.5)^4}{24} \right]$$ ;= 0.2746 = 0.275 (3sf);;Let B = $$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$ where $$M_1, M_2, M_3, M_4$$ are no. of moths caught in 4 randomly chosen evenings. ;Let $$\mu$$=E(B)=E($$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$) = 4E(M) = 4(3.5) = 14.0;B ~ Po($$\mu$$);Since $$\mu$$(=14) $$\geq$$ 10;B ~ N($$\mu$$,$$\mu$$) approximately;P( 18 or more caught in 4 evenings) ;P ( B $$\geq$$ 18 ) ;$$\equiv$$ P(B > 17.5) ;$$\equiv$$ P$$\left(Z > \frac{17.5 - \lambda}{\sqrt{\lambda}}\right)$$;= P$$\left(Z > \frac{17.5 - 14}{\sqrt{14}}\right)$$;= P$$(Z > 0.9354) \equiv 1 - \Phi (0.935)$$;= 1 - 0.8251 = 0.175 (3sf)

a) The procedure does not gives a random sample because the children do not have equal chances of being selected.;;b) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$p_0$$ = assume p = 0.8 and $$q_0$$ = 1 - $$p_0$$ = 0.2;Let $$p_s$$ = sample p = $$\frac{34}{50}$$ = 0.68 and $$q_s$$ = 1- $$p_s$$ = 0.32;;Test $$H_0: p = p_0$$ against $$H_1: p < p_0$$ a 1 tailed test for less;The 5% critical value, $$z_{0.05}$$ = 1.645 ;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$z < -z_{0.05}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \frac{p_s - p_0}{\sqrt{p_0 q_0 / n}} = \frac{0.68 - 0.8}{\sqrt{( 0.8 ) ( 0.2 ) / 50}} = - 2.12$$;Since $$z < -z_{0.05}$$, reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that at the 5% level of significance, there is significant evidence that the proportion of children at the school with access to a computer at home is less than 0.8.;;$$z_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} = 1.960\sqrt{\frac{( 0.68 ) ( 0.32 )}{50}} = 0.1293$$;A symmetric 95% confidence interval;$$p_s - z_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} , p_s + z_{0.025} \sqrt{\frac{p_s q_s}{n}}$$  ;= [ 0.68 - 0.1293, 0.68 + 0.1293 ] ;= [ 0.5507 , 0.8093 ] ;= [ 0.551, 0.809 ] (3sf)

(i) Tabulate all possible products:;img;Tabulate frequency / probability distribution:;img;;$$E(X) = \sum_{all x_{i}} x_{i}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (2)\left(\frac{12}{36}\right) + (3)\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (4)\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (6)\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) $$;$$= 3$$;;$$E(X^{2}) = \sum_{all x_{i}} {x_{i}}^{2}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)^{2}\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (2)^{2}\left(\frac{12}{36}\right) + (3)^{2}\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (4)^{2}\left(\frac{6}{36}\right) + (6)^{2}\left(\frac{6}{36}\right)$$;$$= \frac{35}{3}$$;;$$\therefore Var(X) = E(X^{2}) - [E(X)]^{2}$$;$$ = \left(\frac{35}{3}\right) - (3)^{2} = \frac{8}{3}$$;;(ii) ;Let n = sample size = 100;Let p = P(X = 2) = $$\frac{12}{36}$$ = $$\frac{1}{3}$$ and q = 1 - p = $$\frac{2}{3}$$;T ~ B(n,p);Since n(= 100) is large and np$$\left(= \frac{100}{3}\right)$$ > 5 and nq$$\left(= \frac{200}{3}\right)$$ > 5;X ~ N(np, npq) = N $$\left(\frac{100}{3}, \frac{200}{9}\right)$$ approximately ;P(T $$\geq$$ 40);$$\equiv$$ P(T > 39.5) $$\leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\equiv$$ P$$\left(Z > \frac{39.5 - np}{\sqrt{npq}}\right)$$ = P $$\left(Z > \frac{39.5-\frac{100}{3}}{\sqrt{\frac{200}{9}}} \right)$$;= P(Z > 1.3081) = 1 - $$\Phi$$(1.308);= 1 - 0.9045 = 0.0955(3sf)

(i) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$\mu_{0}$$ = assume $$\mu$$ = 9.5;Let $$\sigma^{2}$$ = Var(X) = 15;;$$\hat{\mu} = \overline{x} = \frac{\sum x}{n} = \frac{527.1}{50} = 10.542$$;Test $$H_{0}: \mu = \mu_{0}$$ against $$H_{1}: \mu \neq \mu_{0}$$ a 2-tailed test for difference;At 5% significance level, critical value $$z_{0.025}$$ = 1.960;Reject $$H_{0}$$ if $$\left| z \right| > \left| z_{0.025} \right|$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \left( \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_{0}}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} \right) = \frac{10.542 - 9.5}{\sqrt{15/50}} = 1.902$$;;Since $$\left| z \right| < \left| z_{0.025} \right|$$, do not reject $$H_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 5% significance level, there is insufficient evidence that $$\mu \neq 9.5$$;;(ii);Let $$\mu_{1}$$ = alternative assume $$\mu = 11.5$$;With $$\hat{\mu}(= 10.542) < \mu_{1}(= 11.5)$$, in a 1-tailed test with $$H_{0}: \mu < \mu_{1}$$;$$\hat{\sigma}^{2} = \frac{1}{n-1}\left[\sum x^{2} - \frac{1}{n}\left(\sum x\right)^{2}\right]$$;= $$\frac{1}{49}\left[6172.31 - \frac{1}{50}\left(527.1\right)^{2}\right]$$ = 12.56;For a 1-tailed test, the $$\alpha$$% critical value is $$z_{\alpha}$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \left( \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_{1}}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} \right) = \frac{10.542 - 11.5}{\sqrt{12.56/50}} = -1.911$$;$$H_{0}$$ is accepted if $$z > - z_{\alpha}$$;;i.e. -1.911 > -$$z_{\alpha}$$;$$z_{\alpha}$$ > 1.911;$$\equiv \Phi(z_{\alpha}) > \Phi(1.911)$$ ;$$\equiv 1 - \alpha > 0.9720$$;$$\therefore \alpha < 0.028$$;$$\equiv$$ Significance level of test < 2.8%

At the points of intersection between ;y = x - 3 and $$y^{2} + y = 2x^{2} - x + 1$$;$$\begin{align};& \left ( x - 3 \right )^2 + \left ( x -3 \right ) = 2x^{2}- x + 1\\;& \Rightarrow x^{2} - 6x + 9 + x - 3 - 2x^{2} - x +1\\;& x^{2} + 4x - 5  = 0\\;\end{align}$$;$$\therefore x = -5$$ or $$x = 1$$;$$\Rightarrow y = x - 3 = -2$$ or $$-8$$;$$\therefore$$ There are 2 points of intersection: (1,-2) and (-5,-8);$$\begin{align};& y^{2} + y = 2x^{2} - x +1\\;& \Rightarrow \frac{d}{dx}[y^2 + y] = \frac{d}{dx}[2x^{2} - x +1]\\;& 2y\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{dy}{dx} = 4x -1\\;& (2y+1)\frac{dy}{dx} = 4x -1\\;& \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{4x-1}{2y+1}\\;\end{align}$$;;Gradient $$m_1$$ of line y = (1)x - 3 is 1.;Gradient $$m_2$$ of curve is given by $$\frac{dy}{dx}$$;At (1, -2), $$m_2 = \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{4(1)-1}{2(-2)+1} = -1$$;Since $$m_2 = \frac{1}{m_1}$$, line y = x - 3 is normal to the curve at this point.;At (-5,-8), $$m_2 = \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{4(-5)-1}{2(-8)+1} = 1.4$$;Since $$m_2 \neq \frac{1}{m_1}$$, line y = x - 3 is not normal to the curve at this point.;;$$\therefore$$ The line is normal to the cruve at exactly one (1,-2) of the two points of intersection

(i) Deduce that f(x) is symmetrical about x =1 $$\Rightarrow$$Mode = 1;;(ii) f(x)$$\geq$$0 for 0$$\leq$$x$$\leq$$2 - by definition $$\Rightarrow$$ f(0)$$\geq$$0;$$\begin{align}  ;i.e. & a - b ( 0 - 1 )^2 \geq 0 \\;&a - b \geq 0 \\;&\therefore a \geq b\\;\end{align}$$;;(iii) ;$$\begin{align} ;& \int^\infty_{- \infty} f ( x ) dx = 1 \\;& \Rightarrow \int^2_0 [ a - b(x - 1)^2 ] dx = 1 \\;& {[ ax - \frac{1}{3}b ( x - 1 )^3 ]}^2_0 = 1 \\;& 2a - \frac{2}{3}b = 1 \\;& 3a - b = \frac{3}{2}\\;\end{align}$$;;(iv) $$ b = \frac{3}{8} \Rightarrow 3a - \frac{3}{8} = \frac{3}{2} \Rightarrow a = \frac{5}{8}$$;If q is upper quartile of X, $$ \int^q_{- \infty} f ( x )d x = \frac{3}{4}$$;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ \int^{\sqrt{2}}_0 f(x)dx;\\ \int^{\sqrt{2}}_0 \left[ \frac{5}{8}- \frac{3}{8}(x-1)^2 \right] dx ;\\ = {\left[ \frac{5}{8}- \frac{1}{8}(x-1)^3 \right]}^{\sqrt{2}}_0 ;\\ = \left[ \frac{5}{8}(\sqrt{2})- \frac{1}{8}(\sqrt{2}-1)^3 \right]-\left[ 0- \frac{1}{8}(-1)^3 \right] ;\\ = \frac{1}{8}\left[ 5 \sqrt{2}-(2 \sqrt{2}-6 + 3 \sqrt{2}-1)-(1) \right] ;\\ = \frac{6}{8}= \frac{3}{4};\end{align}$$;$$\Rightarrow \sqrt(2)$$ is upper quartile of X.

Let X = no. of flaws in 200m of ribbon;Let $$\lambda = E(X) = 2$$;$$\begin{align} ;X \sim P_0 ( \lambda ) ;\\ P(X \geq 3) ;\\ \equiv 1 - P ( X = 0 ) - P ( X = 1 ) - P ( X = 2 ) ;\\ = 1 - e^{- \lambda}[ 1 + \lambda + \frac{\lambda^2}{2 !}] ;\\ = 1 - e^{- 2} [ 1 + 2 + \frac{2^2}{2 !} ] ;\\ = 0.3233 = 0.323(3dp);\end{align}$$;;Let L = required length of ribbon;Let Y = no. of flaws in length L of ribbon;Deduce that E(Y) = L / 100 and $$Y ~ P_o(L / 100)$$;$$\begin{align}  ;i.e. & P(Y=0) = 0.001\\;& \Rightarrow e^{- L / 100} = 0.001 \\;& - L/100 = \ln  (0.001) = - 6.908 \\;& \therefore L = 690.8 = 691m(3sf) \\;\end{align}$$;;Let R = no. of flaws in 2000 m of ribbon;Let $$\mu=E(R)=20$$;$$R \sim P_o(\mu)$$;Since $$\mu(=20) > 10$$,;$$R ~ N(\mu,\mu)$$ approximately;P ( R < 12 ) ;$$ \equiv P(R < 11.5) \leftarrow$$  continuity correction;$$ \equiv P \left( Z < \frac{11.5 - \mu}{\sqrt{\mu}} \right) = P ( Z < \frac{11.5 - 20}{\sqrt{20}} ) $$;$$ = P(Z < - 1.9007) \equiv 1 - \Phi(1.901) $$;$$ = 1 - 0.9714 = 0.0286 = 0.029(3dp)$$

For a uniform (rectangular) distribution with $$ l - 0.03 \leq x \leq l + 0.03$$,;$$\begin{align} ;&f(x) &= 1/0.06, &l - 0.03 \leq x \leq l+0.03\\;& &=0, & otherwise\\; \end{align}$$;;Let $$\mu$$=E(X);Let $$\sigma^2$$=Var(X);Deduce that f(x) is symmetrical about $$x = l$$ ;$$\mu = E ( X ) = l $$;$$\begin{align}  ;{\sigma^2 = \int}^\infty_{- \infty}(x- \mu)^2. f(x)dx ;\\ {\equiv \int}^{l + 0.03}_{l-0.03}(x-l)^2.(1/0.06) dx ;\\ = {\left[ \frac{1}{3}(x-l)^3(1/0.06) \right]}^{l + 0.03}_{l-0.03};\\ = ( 1 / 0.18 ) [ ( 0.03 )^3 - ( - 0.03 )^3 ] ;\\ = 0.0003;\end{align}$$;;$$T = \sum^{50}_{r = 1} X$$;$$E ( T ) = E ( \sum^{50}_{r = 1} X ) = 50E ( X ) = 50l $$;$$Var ( T ) = Var ( \sum^{50}_{r = 1} X ) = 50Var ( X )$$;$$= 50 ( 0.0003 ) = 0.015$$;Since sample size (=50) is large, Central Limit Theorem;T ~ N(50l,0.015) approximately;;Deduce that 5 observations of T is equal to (5 x 50 =) 250 observations of X;Let n = sample size = 250;$$\begin{align} \hat{l} \equiv \hat{\mu} = \overline{x} = \frac{\Sigma t}{n} = \frac{499.53}{250} = 1.99812\end{align}$$;Let $$l_0$$ = assumed $$l$$ (or $$\mu$$) =2;Test $$H_0: l = l_0$$ against $$H_1: l < l_0$$ a 1-tailed test for less;The 1% critical value, $$z_{0.01} = 2.326$$;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$z < -z_{0.01}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$\begin{align} z = \frac{\overline{x} - l_0}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}} = \frac{1.99812 - 2}{\sqrt{0.0003 / 250}} = - 1.7162 \end{align}$$;Since $$z > -z_{0.01}$$, do not reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that, at the 1% level of significance, there is insufficient evidence that $$l$$<2.

A symmetric 90% cofidence interval is o.6567 < p < 0.8100;$$ \Rightarrow p_s$$ = (0.6567 + 0.8100)/2 = 0.73335 and $$q_s$$ = 1 - $$p_s$$ = 0.26665;$$\begin{align} \Rightarrow p_s + z_{0.05} \sqrt{\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} = 0.8100 \end{align}$$;$$\begin{align}  ;i.e. 0.73335 + 1.645\sqrt{\frac{(0.73335)(0.26665)}{n}} = 0.8100;\\ \therefore n = \frac{(1.645)^2(0.73335)(0.26665)}{(0.8100-0.73335)^2} = 90.07 = 90;\end{align}$$;;Let $$p_0$$ = assumed value of $$p=\frac{2}{3}$$;Test $$ H_0 p=p_0 $$ against $$p > p_0$$ a 1-tailed test for greater value;The 10% critical value, $$z_{0.10} = 1.282$$;Reject $$ H_0 $$if $$ z > z_{0.10}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$\begin{align} z = \frac{p_s-p_0}{\sqrt{p_0 q_0/n}} = \frac{0.73335 - 0.66667}{\sqrt{(0.73335)(0.26665)/90}} = 1.342 \end{align}$$;Since $$z > z_{0.10}$$, reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that, at the 10% level of significance, there is significant evidence that the probability p of a dropped drawing pin landing 'point-up' is greater than $$\frac{2}{3}$$;;To take p = 0.7( and q = 1- p = 0.3);No. of 'point-ups' obtained in $$1^{st}$$ trial = $$n p_s$$ = (90)(0.73335) = 66;Let X = no. of 'point-ups' obtained in $$2^{nd}$$ trial ;$$X\sim B(n,p)$$;Since n(=90) is larege, ;$$X \sim N(np, npq)$$approximately;$$ P(X = 66)$$;$$ = P(65.5 < X < 66.5) \leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\begin{align} ;\equiv P\left(\frac{65.5 - np}{\sqrt{npq}} < Z < \frac{66.5 - (90)(0.7)}{\sqrt{(70)(0.7)(0.3)}}\right);\\ = P(0.57505 < Z < 0.80508);\\ \equiv \Phi (0.805) - \Phi(0.575);\\ = 0.7896 - 0.7174;\\ = 0.0722 = 0.072 (3dp); \end{align}$$
