Assume that $$ z^4 - 2z^3 + 6z^2 - 8z + 8 = 0 $$ has a root of the form $$ ki $$;$$\begin{align}  ;\Rightarrow (ki)^4 - 2(ki)^3 + 6(ki)^2 - 8(ki) + 8 = 0;\\ (ki)^4 - 2k^3i + 6k^2 - 8ki + 8 = 0;\\ (k^4 - 6k^2 + 8) + (2k^2-8)ki = 0;\end{align}$$;;Equating Im parts:;$$ (2k^2 -8)k = 0 \Rightarrow k =0 (NA) or K = \pm 2$$ ;Equating Re parts:;$$ k^4 - 6k^2 + 8 = 0 $$;Subst $$ k = \pm 2$$ into eqn:;LHS = $$(\pm 2)^4 - 6(\pm 2)^2 + 8 = 0$$ = LHS;$$ \therefore z^4-2z^3+6z^2-8z+8=0 $$ has roots $$\pm2i$$;;$$\pm2i$$ are roots;$$ \Rightarrow (z-2i)(z+2i) = (z^2 + 4) $$ is a factor;By long division:;$$ z^4 - 2z^3 + 6z^2 - 8z + 8 = 0$$;$$ \equiv (z^2+4)(z^2 - 2z + 2) =0 $$;$$  z^2 -2z +2 =0$$;$$ \Rightarrow z = \frac{-(-2)\pm\sqrt{(-2)^2-4(1)(2)}}{2(1)} = 1\pm i$$;$$ \therefore z^4-2z^3+6z^2-8z + 8 =0 $$;$$ \Rightarrow$$ z = i, -i, 1+i or 1-i

Let h = depth of liquid;Let r = radius of liquid surface;Let V = volume of liquid;;$$ \frac{dV}{dt} = 2 cm^3s^-1$$;r = h $$ \tan^{-1}{45^{\circ}} $$ = h;;$$\begin{align}  ;\Rightarrow V = \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h = \frac{1}{3}\pi h^3 \Rightarrow h = \left(\frac{3V}{\pi}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}};\\ \Rightarrow \frac{dh}{dt} = \frac{d}{dV} \left(\frac{3V}{\pi}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} x \frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{3V}{\pi}\right)^{-\frac{2}{3}}\frac{dV}{dt};\end{align}$$;;After 3 minutes, volume of remaining liquid, V = (initial volume) - (3min x run out rate) = 390 - 3 x 60 x 2 = 30 $$cm^3$$;$$ \therefore $$ Rate at which depth is decreasing,;$$\begin{align}  ;\frac{dh}{dt} = \frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{3V}{\pi}\right)^{-\frac{2}{3}}\frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{1}{\pi}\left(\frac{3(30)}{\pi}\right)^{-\frac{2}{3}}(2);\\ = 0.067996 = 0.0680 cms^{-1} (3sf) \end{align}$$

$$\begin{align}  ;3x^2 + xy + y^2 = 33;\\ \Rightarrow \frac{d}{dx} [3x^2 + xy + y^2\ = \frac{d}{dx}[33];\\ 6x + y + x \frac{dy}{dx} + 2y\frac{dy}{dx} = 0;\\ \frac{dy}{dx}(x+2y) = -(6x+y);\\ \therefore \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{6x + y}{x+2y} \end{align}$$;;At points where tangent is parallel to x-axis,;$$\begin{align} \frac{dy}{dx} = 0 \end{align}$$, i.e. $$\begin{align} -\frac{6x+y}{x+2y} = 0 \Rightarrow y = -6x \end{align}$$;At $$ y =-6x $$,;$$\begin{align} 3x^2 + x(-6x) +(-6x)^2 = 33 ;\\ 3x^2 - 6x^2 + 36x^2 = 33 ;\\ x^2 = 1;\Rightarrow x \pm 1 \Rightarrow y=-6(\pm1) = \mp 6\end{align}$$;$$ \therefore $$ Coordinates of the points are (1, -6) and (-1,6).

(i);$$\begin{align}  ;\frac{d}{d\theta}[\sec\theta] ;\\ \equiv \frac{d}{d\theta}\left[\frac{1}{\cos\theta}\right] ;\\ = \frac{-(-\sin\theta)}{\cos^{2}{\theta}};\\ = \frac{1}{\cos{\theta}}\frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta} ;\\ \equiv \sec\theta \tan\theta \end{align}$$;;(ii) With $$ x = \sec\theta -1, $$ dx = $$ \sec\theta \tan\theta d\theta$$;At $$ x = \sqrt{2} - 1, \theta = \frac{1}{4} \pi; $$ at $$ x = 1, \theta = \frac{1}{3}\pi $$;$$\begin{align} (x+1)\sqrt{x^2 + 2x} ;\\ \equiv (\sec\theta -1 +1)\sqrt{(\sec\theta-1)^2 + 2(\sec\theta-1)};\\ = \sec\theta \sqrt{\sec^{2}\theta - 2\sec\theta +1 +2\sec\theta - 2};\\ = \sec\theta \sqrt{\sec^{2}\theta - 1} ;\\ = \sec\theta \sqrt{\tan^2\theta} ;\\ \therefore \int^{1}_{\sqrt{2}-1} \frac{1}{(x+1)\sqrt{x^2+2x}}dx;\\ = \int^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{\frac{1}{4}\pi} \frac{1}{\sec\theta\tan\theta}\sec\theta\tan\theta d\theta;\\ = \int^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{\frac{1}{4}\pi} d\theta;\\ = [\theta]^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{\frac{1}{4}\pi};\\ = \frac{1}{3}\pi - \frac{1}{4}\pi = \frac{1}{12}\pi \end{align}$$

$$\begin{align} \sin {3\theta} = \sin{(2\theta+\theta)};\\ = \sin{2\theta}\cos{\theta} + \cos{2\theta}\sin{\theta} ;\\ = (2\sin{\theta}\cos{\theta})\cos{\theta} + (1-2\sin^{2}{\theta})\sin{\theta};\\ = 2\sin{\theta}\cos^{2}{\theta} + (1-2\sin^{2}{\theta})\sin{\theta};\\ = 2\sin{\theta}(1-\sin^{2}{\theta})+\sin{\theta}-2\sin^{3}{\theta};\\ = 2\sin{\theta} - 2\sin^{3}{\theta} + \sin{\theta} - 2\sin^{3}{\theta};\\ = 3\sin{\theta} - 4 \sin^{3}{\theta} \end{align}$$;;(i);$$\begin{align} 8\sin^{3}{\theta} - 6\sin{\theta} = 1.5;\\ \equiv -2(3\sin{\theta}-4\sin^{3}{\theta}) = 1.5;\\ \equiv -2 \sin{3\theta} = 1.5 ;\\ \sin{3\theta} = -\frac{3}{4};\\ 3\theta = n\pi + (-1)^n (-0.8481), n \in \mathbb{Z};\\ \therefore \theta = \frac{1}{3}n\pi + (-1)^n (-0.2827);\\ = \frac{1}{3}n\pi + (-1)^n (-0.283) rad (3sf)\end{align}$$;;(ii);$$\begin{align} \sin{3\theta} = 3\sin{\theta} - 4\sin^{3}{\theta};\\ \Rightarrow \sin^{3}{\theta} = \frac{3}{4}\sin{\theta}-\frac{1}{4}\sin{3\theta};\\ \therefore \int^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{0} \sin^{3}{\theta} d\theta;\\ \equiv \int^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{0} \left(\frac{3}{4}\sin{\theta} - \frac{1}{4}\sin{3\theta}\right) d\theta;\\ = \left[-\frac{3}{4}\cos{\theta} + \frac{1}{12} \cos{3\theta}\right]^{\frac{1}{3}\pi}_{0};\\ = \left[-\frac{3}{4}\cos{\frac{1}{3}\pi} + \frac{1}{12} \cos{\pi}\right]-\left[-\frac{3}{4}\cos{0} + \frac{1}{12} \cos{0}\right];\\ = -\frac{3}{4}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) + \frac{1}{12}(-1) + \frac{3}{4}(1) - \frac{1}{12}(1);\\ = \frac{3}{8} - \frac{2}{12} = \frac{5}{24} \end{align}$$

Let $$\begin{align} f(x) = \frac{1+x-2x^2}{(2-x)(1+x^2)} \equiv \frac{A}{2-x} + \frac{Bx+C}{1+x^2} \end{align}$$;;Clearing the fractions:;$$\begin{align} 1+x-2x^2;\\ \equiv A(1+x^2) + (Bx + c)(2-x);\\= (A - B)x^2 +(2B-C)x + (A + 2C) \end{align}$$;;Cover-up rule:;$$\begin{align} x = 2: A = \frac{1+(2)-2(2)^2}{1+(2)^2} = -1 \end{align}$$;;Comparing coefficients:;$$\begin{align} x^2: -2 = A-B;\\ \Rightarrow -2 =(-1)-B \Rightarrow B = 1;\\ x^1: 1 = 2B-C ;\\ \Rightarrow 1 = 2(1) -C \Rightarrow C = 1 ;\\ \therefore f(x) = -\frac{1}{2-x} + \frac{x+1}{1+x^2} \end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  f(x) \equiv -\frac{1}{2} \left(1-\frac{1}{2}x\right)^{-1} + (1+x)(1+x^2)^{-1};\\ = -\frac{1}{2} \left[1+(-1)\left(-\frac{1}{2}x\right) + \frac{(-1)(-2)}{2!}\left(-\frac{1}{2}x\right)^2 +...\right]+(1+x)\left[1+(-1)(x^2)+...\right];\\ = \left[-\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{4}x -\frac{1}{8}x^2+...\right] + (1+x)[1-x^2+...];\\ = \left[-\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{4}x -\frac{1}{8}x^2+...\right] + [1+x-x^2+...];\\ = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{3}{4}x - \frac{9}{8}x^2\end{align}$$;;The expansion is valid for;$$ \left| \frac{1}{2}x \right| < 1$$ and $$ \left| x^2 \right| < 1 $$;$$ \equiv$$ | x | < 1 or -1< x <1

(i);$$\begin{align} (1-x)\frac{dy}{dx} - xy - 1 = 0, |x| < 1 ;\\ = \frac{dy}{dx} - \frac{x}{1-x^2}y = \frac{1}{1-x^2}\end{align}$$;;Let $$ h(x) = \int\frac{-x}{1-x^2}dx$$;$$= \frac{1}{2} \ln {|1-x^2|}$$;$$= \ln{\sqrt{1-x^2}}  $$ (for | x | <  1);$$ \Rightarrow $$ integrating factor,;$$ e^{h(x)} = e^{\ln{\sqrt{1-x^2}}} = \sqrt{1=x^2}$$ and;$$ e^{-h(x)} =  e^{-\ln{\sqrt{1-x^2}}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1=x^2}}$$;$$ \therefore $$ General Solution is;$$\begin{align} y = e^{-h(x)}\left[\int e^{h(x)} \frac{1}{1-x^2} dx\right] ;\\ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\left[\int\sqrt{1-x^2}\frac{1}{1-x^2} dx \right] ;\\ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\left[\int\sqrt{1-x^2}dx \right] ;\\ = \frac{\sin^{-1}{x} + c}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} \end{align}$$;;(ii) $$ y = \frac{1}{2}\pi $$ when x = 0;$$\begin{align} \Rightarrow \frac{1}{2}\pi = \frac{\sin^{-1}{0}+c}{\sqrt{1-(0)^2}} \Rightarrow c = \frac{1}{2}\pi \end{align}$$;When $$ x = \frac{1}{2} $$;$$\begin{align} y = \frac{\sin^{-1}{\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)} + \frac{1}{2}\pi}{\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2}};\\= \frac{\frac{1}{6}\pi+ \frac{1}{2}\pi}{\sqrt{1-\frac{1}{4}}} ;\\ = \frac{4}{3\sqrt{3}}\pi\end{align}$$;;(iii) For | x | > 1,;$$\begin{align} h(x) = \frac{1}{2}\ln{|1 - x^2| \equiv \sqrt{x^2-1}};\\ \Rightarrow y = e^{-h(x)} \left[\int e^{h(x)} \frac{1}{1-x^2} dx \right] ;\\ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}\left[\int \sqrt{x^2-1}\frac{1}{1-x^2} dx\right];\\ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}}\left[- \int \sqrt{x^2-1}\frac{1}{x^2-1} dx\right] ;\\ \therefore y\sqrt{x^2-1} = - \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-1}} dx \end{align}$$

(i) ;Gradient of QR, ;$$\begin{align}  m_{QR} = \frac{y_R - y_Q}{x_R - X_Q} = \frac{\frac{c}{r} - \frac{c}{q}}{cr-cq};\\ = \frac{q-r}{qr(r-q)};\\ = -\frac{1}{qr} \end{align}$$;;(ii) Deduce from part(i) that  gradient of PV, $$ m_{PV} = - \frac{1}{pv}$$;PV is perpendicular to QR $$ \Rightarrow m_{PV} = - \frac{1}{m_{QR}} = qr $$;i.e. $$\begin{align} -\frac{1}{pv} = qr \Rightarrow v = -\frac{1}{prq} \end{align}$$;;(iii);$$\begin{align} \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{dy}{dt} / \frac{dx}{dt} ;\\ = \frac{d}{dt}\left[\frac{c}{t}\right] / \frac{d}{dt}[ct];\\ = - \frac{c}{t^2}/c = -\frac{1}{t^2}\end{align}$$;Gradient of normal, $$ m' = -1/\frac{dy}{dx} = t^2$$;Gradient of normal at $$ P(t=p), m_P' = p^2$$;;(iv) ;Normal at P meets curve at $$ S(t=s) \Rightarrow $$ gradient of PS, $$ m_{PS} = m_{P}' = p^2$$;Deduce from part(i) that $$ m_{PS} = - \frac{1}{ps}$$;i.e. $$\begin{align} - \frac{1}{ps} = p^2 \Rightarrow s = -\frac{1}{p^3} \end{align}$$;;(v) $$ \angle$$QPR is 90$$^{\circ}$$;i.e. PQ is perpendicular to PR ;$$\Rightarrow$$ gradient of PQ, $$ m_{PQ} = -1/(m_{PR}) = -1/(-\frac{1}{pr}) = pr $$;Deduce from par (i) that $$ m_{PQ} = - \frac{1}{pq}$$;i.e. $$\begin{align} -\frac{1}{pq} = pr \Rightarrow -\frac{1}{qr} = p^2 \equiv m_{QR} = m_P'\end{align}$$;i.e. gradient of QR = gradient of normal at P.;$$\therefore$$ QR is parallel to the normal at P.

$$\begin{align}  \frac{x-9}{x^2-9} \leq 1;\\ \Rightarrow \frac{x-9}{x^2-9} -1 \leq 0;\\ \frac{(x-9)-(x^2-9)}{x^2-9} \leq 0;\\ \frac{x-x^2}{x^2-9} \leq 0;\\ \frac{x(1-x)}{(x-3)(x+3)} \leq 0, [x\neq\pm3]] \end{align}$$;;Critical values are -3, 0, 1, 3;Let $$ f(x) = \frac{x(1-x)}{(x-3)(x+3)} $$;;$$\begin{align}  ;& Range & Test Value & Sign of f(x) \\;& x < -3 & -4 & - \\;& -3 < x \leq 0 & -1 & + \\;& 0 \leq x \leq 1 & \frac{1}{2} & - \\ ;& 1\leq x \leq 3 & 2 & + \\;& x > 3 & 4 & - \\ ;\end{align}$$;;$$ \therefore $$ Solution is x < -3, 0 $$ \leq $$ x $$ \leq $$1, x > 3

Let x = $$ log_b a $$;$$\begin{align}  \Rightarrow b^x = a;\\ log_a b^x = log_a a = 1;\\ x.log_a b = 1 ;\\ \therefore x(=log_b a) = \frac{1}{log_a b}\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  2log_9 x + 1 = 2log_x 3 = log_x 3^2 = log_x 9 = \frac{1}{log_9 x};\\ \Rightarrow 2(log_9x)^2 + (log_9 x) - 1 = 0;\\ \Rightarrow (log_9 x) = \frac{-(1)\pm\sqrt{(1)^2-4(2)(-1)}}{2(2)};\\ = \frac{1}{2} or -1(NA);\\ \therefore x = 9^\frac{1}{2} = 3 \end{align}$$

(i) Using the cosine formula, ;$$\begin{align} \Delta ABC: \cos{\angle ABC} = \frac{a^2+b^2-x^2}{2ab};\\ \Delta ADC: \cos{\angle ADC} = \frac{c^2+d^2-x^2}{2cd} ;\\ \angle ABC + \angle adc = 180^{\circ};\\ \Rightarrow \cos{\angle ABC} = \cos{(180^{\circ} - \angle ADC)};\\ = - cos{\angle ADC};\\ \frac{a^2+b^2-x^2}{2ab} = - \frac{c^2+d^2-x^2}{2cd} ;\\ a^2cd+b^2cd-cdx^2 = -abc^2-abd^2+abx^2;\\ \therefore (ab+cd)x^2 = a^2cd+abc^2+abd^2+b^2cd;\\ = ac(ad+bc) + bd(ad+bc);\\ = (ac+bd)(ad+bc) \end{align}$$;;(ii) BD = y:;img;$$\begin{align} \Delta ABD: \cos{\angle BAD} = \frac{a^2+d^2-y^2}{2ad} ;\\ \Delta BCD: \cos{\angle BCD} = \frac{b^2+c^2-y^2}{2bc} ;\\ \angle ABC + \angle ADC = 180^{\circ};\\ \Rightarrow \cos{\angle BAD} + \cos{\angle BCD} = 180^{\circ};\\ \Rightarrow \cos{\angle BAD} = \cos{(180^{\circ} - \angle BCD)} ;\\ = -\cos{\angle BCD};\\ \Rightarrow \frac{a^2+d^2-y^2}{2ad} = -\frac{b^2+c^2-y^2}{2bc} ;\\ (a^2+d^2-y^2)(bc) = - (b^2+c^2-y^2)(ad);\\ a^2bc -bcd^2-bcy^2 = -ab^2d -ac^2d + ady^2;\\ \therefore (ad+bc)y^2 = a^2bc + ab^2d+ac^2d+bcd^2 ;\\ = ab(ac+bd) + cd(ac+bd);\\ = (ab+cd)(ac+bd) ;\\ \Rightarrow y^2 = \frac{(ab+cd)(ac+bd)}{(ad+bc)}\end{align}$$;From part(i), $$\begin{align} x^2 = \frac{(ac+bd)(ad+bc)}{(ab+cd)} \end{align}$$;i.e.;$$\begin{align} x^2y^2 = \frac{(ac+bd)(ad+bc)}{(ab+cd)} \frac{(ab+cd)(ac+bd)}{(ad+bc)};\\ = (ac+bd)^2 \end{align}$$;$$ \therefore xy = ac+bd  $$

Let n = no. of electors in sample = 800;Let p = percentage of electorate that support George Berry as Presidential candidate;;$$\begin{align}  ;\hat{p} = \frac{417}{800} ;\\ \hat{q} = 1 - \hat{p} = \frac{383}{800};\\ z_{0.005} \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p} \hat{q}}{n}} = 2.576\sqrt{\frac{\left( \frac{417}{800} \right) \left( \frac{383}{800} \right)}{800}} = 0.045497;\end{align}$$;;The 99% confidence interval for p is;$$\begin{align}  ;[ \hat{p} - z_{0.005} \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p} \hat{q}}{n}} , \hat{p} + z_{0.005} \sqrt{\frac{{}\hat{p} \hat{q}}{n}} ] ;\\ = \left[ \frac{417}{800}- 0.045497, \frac{417}{800} + 0.045497 \right] ;\\ = [ 0.47575 , 0.56675 ] ;\\ = [ 0.476, 0.567 ] (3dp);\end{align}$$;;An assumption that need to be made is that the electors were randomly selected.

Let $$G_i = i^{th}$$ pupil in sample is a girl;Let $$B_i = i^{th}$$ pupil in sample is a boy;;$$\begin{align}  ;P ( X = - 3 ) = P ( B_1 , B_2 , B_3 );\\ = \frac{4}{10}\cdot \frac{3}{9}\cdot \frac{2}{8}= \frac{1}{30};\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ P(X = - 1) = P(G_1, B_2, B_3) +P(B_1, G_2, B_3) +(B_1, B_2, G_3) ;\\ = \frac{6}{10} \cdot \frac{4}{9} \cdot \frac{3}{8} +\frac{4}{10} \cdot \frac{6}{9} \cdot \frac{3}{8} +\frac{4}{10} \cdot \frac{3}{9} \cdot \frac{6}{8} ;\\ = \frac{9}{30}= \frac{3}{10};\end{align}$$ ;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ P(X = 1) = P(G_1, G_2, B_3) +P(G_1, B_2, G_3) +(B_1, G_2, G_3) ;\\ = \frac{6}{10} \cdot \frac{5}{9} \cdot \frac{4}{8} +\frac{6}{10} \cdot \frac{4}{9} \cdot \frac{5}{8} +\frac{4}{10} \cdot \frac{6}{9} \cdot \frac{5}{8} ;\\= \frac{15}{30}= \frac{1}{2};\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ P(X = 3) = P(G_1, G_2, G_3) ;\\ = \frac{6}{10}\cdot \frac{5}{9}\cdot \frac{4}{8};\\ = \frac{5}{30} = \frac{1}{6};\end{align}$$;;$$ \therefore $$Probability distribution of X is:;   img;;$$\begin{align}  ;E ( \lvert X \lvert ) ;\\ = \sum_{all  x} \lvert x \lvert P ( X = x ) ;\\ = 1 \cdot(\frac{9}{30}+\frac{15}{30}) +3 \cdot(\frac{1}{30}+\frac{5}{30}) ;\\ = 1.4 ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ E(\lvert X \lvert^2) ;\\ = {\sum_{all  x}\lvert x \lvert}^2 P(X = x) ;\\ = 1^2 \cdot ( \frac{9}{30} +\frac{15}{30} ) +3^2 \cdot ( \frac{1}{30} +\frac{5}{30} ) ;\\ = 2.6 ;\end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ Var ( \lvert X \lvert ) ;\\ = E ( \lvert X \lvert^2 ) - [ E ( \lvert X \lvert ) ]^2 ;\\ = 2.6 -(1.4)^2 ;\\ = 0.64;\end{align}$$

Let n = no. of bags in sample = 80;Let $$\mu=E(x)$$;Let $$\sigma^2=Var(x)$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;\hat{\mu} = \overline{x} = \frac{\Sigma ( x - c )}{n} +c = \frac{- 2510}{80} +10000 ;\\ = 9968.625 ;\end{align}$$;$$\begin{align} ;\\ \hat{\sigma}^2 = \frac{1}{n - 1}\left[ \Sigma(x - c)^2 - \frac{(\Sigma(x - c))^2}{n}\right] ;\\ = \frac{1}{79} \left( 2010203 - \frac{( - 2510 )^2}{80} \right) ;\\ = 24448.76 (2dp); \end{align}$$;;Let $$\mu_0$$ = required mean = 10 kg = 10000 g;Test $$H_0 : \mu=\mu_0$$ against $$H_1: \mu<\mu_0$$a 1-tailed test for less ;The 5% critical value, $$ z_{0.05} = 1.645 $$;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$ z < -z_{0.05}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$\begin{align}  z = \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_0}{\hat{\sigma} / \sqrt{n}} = \frac{9968.625 - 100000}{\sqrt{24448.76 / 80}} = - 1.794 \end{align}$$;Since $$z < -z_{0.05}$$, reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that, at the 5% level of significance, there is sufficient evidence that the mean mass of the contents of a bag is less than 10 kg.;;The '5%significance level' refers to the probability that, by chance alone, the null hypothesis is rejected incorrectly, i.e. the null hypothesis is rejected although the sample is taken from a population in which the mean mass of the contents of a bag is 10 kg.

X~U(0,1) or R(0,1);i.e. X has the density function ;$$\begin{align}  ;& f(x) &= 1 &0 < x < 1  ;\\&  &= 0 &otherwise. ;\end{align}$$;;Let $$\mu = E ( X ) = \frac{1}{2} ( 0 + 1 ) = \frac{1}{2} $$;$$\begin{align} ;Var(X) =   \int^{\infty}_{- \infty}(x- \mu)^2 \cdot f(x) dx ;\\ =   \int^1_0(x- \frac{1}{2})^2 \cdot(1) dx ;\\ = {\left[ \frac{1}{3}\left(x- \frac{1}{2}\right)^3 \right]}^1_0 ;\\ = \frac{1}{3} \left[ \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^3 - \left( - \frac{1}{2} \right)^3 \right] = \frac{1}{12}; \end{align}$$;;$$Y\sim U(-1,2)$$ and $$Y \equiv 3X - 1$$;$$\begin{align}  \;E ( Y ) \equiv E ( 3X - 1 ) ;\\ = 3E(X) - 1 ;\\ = 3 \left( \frac{1}{2} \right) - 1 = \frac{1}{2} ;\end{align}$$;$$\begin{align};\\ Var ( Y ) \equiv Var ( 3X - 1 ) ;\\ = 3^2 Var(X) +0 ;\\ = 9 \left( \frac{1}{12} \right) = \frac{3}{4};\end{align}$$;;;$$ T = \lambda X + ( 1 - \lambda ) Y $$;$$\begin{align}  ;\\ \Rightarrow E(T) = E [ \lambda X +(1 - \lambda) Y ] ;\\ = \lambda E ( X ) +( 1 - \lambda ) E ( Y ) ;\\ = \lambda\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) + (1 - \lambda)\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) ;\end{align}$$;$$  = \frac{1}{2} \leftarrow$$ independent of $$\lambda$$;;$$\begin{align}  ;Var ( T ) = Var [ \lambda X +( 1 - \lambda ) Y ] ;\\ = \lambda^2 Var  (X) +(1 - \lambda)^2 Var(Y) ;\\ = \frac{1}{12} \lambda^2 +\frac{3}{4} ( 1 - \lambda )^2 ;\\ = \frac{1}{12}[ \lambda^2 +9(1 - 2 \lambda +\lambda^2)]  ;\\ = \frac{1}{12} [ 10 \lambda^2 - 18\lambda +9 ] ;\\ = \frac{10}{12}\left[ \lambda^2 - \frac{18}{10}\lambda +\frac{9}{10}\right] ;\\ = \frac{5}{6} \left[ \left( \lambda - \frac{9}{10} \right)^2 - \left( \frac{9}{10} \right)^2 +\frac{9}{10} \right];\end{align}$$;;Deduce that Var(T) is smallest when ;$$\begin{align} \lambda-\frac{9}{10} = 0,\end{align}$$  $$\begin{align}i.e. \lambda = \frac{9}{10} \end{align}$$

Let X= speed of a car;Let $$\mu=E(X)$$;Let $$\sigma^2=Var(X)$$;;$$\begin{align};X \sim N ( \mu , \sigma^2 ) ;\\ P(X > 125) = 1/80 = 0.0125 ;\\ \equiv P ( Z > \frac{125 - \mu}{\sigma} ) = 0.0125 ;\\ \equiv P\left(Z < \frac{125 - \mu}{\sigma}\right) = 1 - 0.0125 = 0.9875 ;\\ \Phi ( \frac{125 - \mu}{\sigma} ) = 0.9875 ;\\ \frac{125 - \mu}{\sigma}= \Phi^{- 1}(0.9875) = 2.240 ;\\ \mu +2.240\sigma = 125 ----(1); \end{align}$$;;$$\begin{align} ;P ( X < 40 ) = 1 / 10 = 0.1 ;\\ \equiv P(Z < \frac{40 - \mu}{\sigma}) = 0.1 ;\\ \equiv P ( Z < \frac{\mu - 40}{\sigma} ) = 1 - 0.1 = 0.9 ;\\ \Phi(\frac{\mu - 40}{\sigma}) = 0.9 ;\\ \frac{\mu - 40}{\sigma} = \Phi^{- 1} ( 0.9 ) = 1.282 ;\\ \mu - 1.282 \sigma = 40 ----(2); \end{align}$$;;Eqn(1) - (2):;$$ 3.522\sigma = 85$$;$$ \Rightarrow \sigma =24.134 = 24.1 km h^{-1} (3sf)$$;Subst $$\sigma = 24.134$$ into eqn(2):;$$ \mu - 1.282(24.134) = 40 $$;$$ \Rightarrow \mu =70.94 = 70.9 km h^{-1}$$;;(i) Let n = no. of cars in sample = 10;Let p = P(X<40) = 0.1 and q = 1- p = 0.9;Let Y = no. of cars out of n with X < 40;;Y ~ B(n,p);P(at least 7 cars with X > 40);$$\equiv$$ P(at most 3 cars with X < 40);$$=P ( Y \leq 3 ) $$;$$= P(Y = 0) +P(Y = 1) +P(Y = 2) +P(Y = 3) $$;$$= q^n +^n{C_1} p^1 q^{n - 1} +^n{C_2} p^2 q^{n - 2} +^n{C_3} p^3 q^{n - 3} $$;$$=(0.9)^{10}+ ^{10}{C_1}{(0.1)}^1 {(0.9)}^9 + ^{10}{C_2} {( 0.1 )}^2 {( 0.9 )}^8 + ^{10}{C_3} {( 0.1 )}^3 {( 0.9 )}^7 $$;$$ = 0.9872 = 0.987(3sf)$$;;(ii) Let m = no. of cars in $$2^{nd}$$ sample = 100;Let S= no. of cars out of m with X < 40;;S ~ B(m, p);Since m(=100) is large, mp = (100)(0.1) = 10 >5 and mq = (100)(0.9) = 90 >5,;S~N(mp,npq) approximately;P(at most 8 cars with X < 40);= P(S $$\leq$$8);$$\equiv$$ P(S<8.5)$$\leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\begin{align} \equiv P\left(Z < \frac{8.5-mp}{\sqrt{mpq}}\right);\\ = P\left(Z < \frac{8.5-100(0.1)}{\sqrt{100(0.1)(0.9)}}\right);\\ = P(Z < -0.5000);\\ = 1 - \Phi(0.5000);\\ = 1 - 0.6915 ;\\ = 0.3085 = 0.309(3sf)\end{align}$$

It meant that there is a 95% confidence level that the interval (3.52, 414) encloses the true value of $$\mu$$.;It is not necessary to make any assumptions because the Central Limit Theorem suggests that the sample mean of a large sample is approximately normally distributed.;;Let X = time per week a teenager spend playing computer games;Let $$\sigma^{2}$$ = Var(X);(3.52,4.14) is a 95% confidence interval;$$\begin{align}  \Rightarrow (3.52, 4.14) = \left[\overline{x} - z_{0.025} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}}, \overline{x} + z_{0.025} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}}\right];\\ \Rightarrow \overline{x} = \frac{1}{2} (3.52+4.14) = 3.83;\\ z_{0.025} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}} = \frac{1}{2}(4.14-3.52) = 0.31;\\ \therefore  \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}} = 0.31/z_{0.025} = 0.31/1.960 = 0.15816;\\ z_{0.025} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}} = (2.576)(0.15816) = 0.4074\end{align}$$;A symmetric 99% confidence interval for $$\mu$$;$$\begin{align}  = \left[\overline{x} - z_{0.005} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}}, \overline{x} + z_{0.005} \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{n}}\right];\\ = [3.83-0.407, 3.83+0.407];\\ = [3.423, 4.237] = [3.42,4.24](3sf)\end{align}$$;;(i) Since $${I_1}^'$$ encloses $$I_1$$,;P(both $$I_1$$ and $${I_1}^'$$ to contain $$\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\mu$$) = 95%;;(ii) Since $${I_1}^'$$ encloses $$I_1$$,;P(exactly one of $$I_1$$ and $${I_1}^'$$ to contain $$\mu$$);= P($${I_1}^'$$ contains $$\mu$$) - P($$I_1$$ contains $$\mu$$);=0.99 - 0.95 = 0.04 $$\equiv$$ 4%;;(iii) P(both $$I_1$$ and $$I_2$$ to contain $$\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\mu$$) $$\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ contains $$\mu$$);=(0.95)(0.95) = 0.9025 $$\equiv$$ 90.25%;;(iv) P(exactly one of $$I_1$$ and $$I_2$$ to contain $$\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\mu$$) $$\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ doesn't contains $$\mu$$) + P($$I_1$$ doesn't contains $$\mu$$) $$\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ contains $$\mu$$);= (0.95)(1-0.95)+(1-0.95)(0.95);= 0.095 $$\equiv$$ 9.5%

A sequence $$u_{1}, u_{2}, u_{3}, ...$$ is such that;$$u_{1} = 1$$ and;$$u_{n+1} = u_{n} - \frac{2n + 1}{n^2 (n + 1)^2}$$ ------- (1) for all $$n \ge 1$$;;(i) $$\therefore$$ Let $$P_{n}$$ be;$$u_{n} = \frac{1}{n^2}$$ ------ (2) where $$n \in Z^{+}$$;When $$n = 1$$,;$$P_{1} = U_{1}$$;LHS of $$P_{1} = 1$$ (given);RHS of $$P_{1} = \frac{1}{1^2} = 1 = $$ LHS of $$P_{1}$$;$$\therefore P_{1}$$ is true.;;Assume $$P_{k}$$ is true for some $$k \in Z^{+}$$, $$k \le n$$:;$$u_{k} = \frac{1}{k^2}$$;When $$n = k + 1$$,;RHS of $$P_{k+1} = \frac{1}{(k + 1)^2}$$;LHS of $$P_{k+1} = u_{k+1} = u_{k} - \frac{2k + 1}{k^2 (k + 1)^2}$$;$$ = \frac{1}{k^2} - \frac{2k + 1}{k^2 (k + 1)^2} = \frac{(k + 1)^2 - (2k + 1)}{k^2 (k + 1)^2}$$;$$ = \frac{k^2 + 2k + 1 - 2k - 1}{k^2 (k + 1)^2} = \frac{k^2}{k^2 (k + 1)^2}$$;$$ = \frac{1}{(k + 1)^2}$$;= RHS of $$P_{k+1}$$;$$\therefore P_{k+1}$$ is true when $$P_{k}$$ is true.;$$\therefore$$ By mathematical induction, $$P_{n}$$ is true for all $$n \in Z^{+}$$. ;;(ii) Hence,;$$\therefore \sum_{n = 1}^{N} \frac{2n + 1}{n^2 (n + 1)^2}$$;$$ = \sum_{n=1}^{N}(u_{n} - u_{n+1})$$;$$ = u_{1} - u_{2} + u_{2} - u_{3} + .... + u_{N-1} - u_{N} + u_{N} - u_{N+1}$$;$$ = u_{1} - u_{N+1}$$ (Method of difference);$$ = 1 - \frac{1}{(N + 1)^2}$$ (ans);;(iii) $$\therefore$$ The reason that the series in part (ii) is convergent is;as $$N \to + \infty$$, $$\frac{1}{(N + 1)^2} \to 0$$;$$\Rightarrow \sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{2n + 1}{n^2 (n + 1)^2} = 1 - \frac{1}{(\infty + 1)^2} = 1 - 0 = 1$$;$$\therefore$$ the series is convergent.;$$\therefore$$ The sum to infinity is 1. (ans);;(iv) Using the answer from part (ii),;$$\therefore \sum_{n=2}^{N} \frac{2n - 1}{n^2 (n - 1)^2}$$;$$ = \sum_{n=1}^{N-1} \frac{2(n + 1) - 1}{(n + 1)^2 (n + 1 - 1)^2}$$ (replace n with n + 1);$$ = \sum_{n=1}^{N-1} \frac{2n + 1}{n^2 (n + 1)^2}$$;$$ = 1 - \frac{1}{N^2}$$ (ans)

(i) The function is defined by;$$y = (1 + x)^n$$ ------ (1);$$\therefore$$ To find its Maclaurin's series, (1) is differentiated successively wrt x:;;$$\frac{dy}{dx} = n(1 + x)^{n -1}$$;$$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = n(n-1)(1 + x)^{n-2}$$;$$\frac{d^3y}{dx^3} = n(n -1)(n - 2)(1 + x)^{n - 3}$$;;When $$x = 0$$,;$$y = 1$$;$$\frac{dy}{dx} = n$$;$$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = n(n - 1)$$;$$\frac{d^3y}{dx^3} = n(n - 1)(n - 2)$$;;$$\therefore$$ The Maclaurin's series for $$(1 + x)^n$$ up to and including $$x^3$$:;$$y \approx 1 + nx + \frac{n(n - 1)}{2!}x^2 + \frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}x^3$$ (ans);;(ii) $$\therefore$$ Expansion of $$(4 - x)^{\frac{3}{2}}(1 + 2x^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}$$ up to and including $$x^3$$;$$ = 4^{\frac{3}{2}}(1 - \frac{x}{4})^{\frac{3}{2}}(1 + 2x^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}$$;$$\approx 8 \left[1 + (\frac{3}{2})(- \frac{x}{4}) + \frac{(\frac{3}{2})(\frac{1}{2})}{2!}(- \frac{x}{4})^{2} + \frac{(\frac{3}{2})(\frac{1}{2})(-\frac{1}{2})}{3!}(-\frac{x}{4})^3)\right]\left[1 + 3x^2\right]$$;$$ = 8 (1 - \frac{3x}{8} + \frac{3x^2}{128} + \frac{x^3}{1024})(1 + 3x^2)$$;$$ = (8 - 3x + \frac{3x^2}{16} + \frac{x^3}{128})(1 + 3x^2)$$;$$ = 8 - 3x + (\frac{3}{16} + 24)x^2 + (\frac{1}{128} - 9)x^3$$;$$ = 8 - 3x + \frac{387}{16}x^2 - \frac{1153}{128}x^3$$ (ans);;(iii) $$\therefore$$ For the expansion in part (ii) to be valid,;$$|\frac{x}{4}| < 1$$ and $$| 2x^2 | < 1$$;$$|\frac{x}{4}| < 1 \Rightarrow -4  < x < 4$$;$$| 2x^2 | < 1 \Rightarrow 2x^2 - 1< 0$$;$$x^2 - \frac{1}{2} < 0 \Rightarrow (x - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})(x + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}) < 0$$;$$\Rightarrow - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$$;$$\therefore$$ The set of values of $$x$$;$$ = \left(x \in R : - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)$$ (ans) ;

(i) $$\therefore$$ The exact value of $$\int_{0}^{\frac{2}{3} \pi} \sin^2 x dx$$;$$ = \int_{0}^{\frac{2}{3} \pi} \frac{1 - \cos 2x}{2} dx$$ (Use $$\cos 2x = 1 - 2 \sin^2 x$$);$$ = \left[\frac{x}{2} - \frac{\sin 2x}{4} \right]_{0}^{\frac{5}{3} \pi} = \frac{5 \pi}{6} - \frac{\sin \frac{10 \pi}{3}}{4}$$;$$ = \frac{5}{6} \pi + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}$$ (ans);;$$\therefore$$ The exact value of $$ \int^{\frac{5}{3}\pi}_{0} \cos^{2}{x} dx$$;$$ = \int^{\frac{5}{3}\pi}_{0} (1 - \sin^{2}{x}) dx$$;$$ = [x]_{0}^{\frac{5}{3} \pi} - \frac{5 \pi}{6} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}$$  (Using $$ \int^{\frac{5}{3}\pi}_{0} \sin^{2}{x} dx = \frac{5 \pi}{6} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}$$);$$ = \frac{5 \pi }{3} - \frac{5 \pi}{6} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}$$;$$ = \frac{5 \pi}{6} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{8}$$ (ans);;(ii) The shaded region $$R$$ is bounded by the curve $$y = x^2 \sin x$$, the line $$x = \frac{1}{2} \pi$$ and the part of the x - axis between 0 and $$\frac{1}{2} \pi $$ as shown.;;img;;(a) $$\therefore$$ The exact area of $$R$$;$$ = \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} x^2 \sin x dx$$;$$ = [(- \cos x) x^2]_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} - \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} (- \cos x) (2x) dx$$;$$ = 0 + [(\sin x)(2x)]_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} - \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} 2\sin x dx$$;$$ = \pi + [2 \cos x]_{0}^{\frac{1}{2} \pi} = \pi + ( 0 - 2)$$;$$ = \pi - 2$$ unit$$s^{2}$$ (ans);;(b) The bounded region $$R$$ is made to rotate completely about the x - axis.;$$\therefore$$ The numerical value of volume of revolution;$$ = \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \pi y^2 dx = \int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \pi (x^4 \sin^2 x) dx$$;$$ = 5.391$$ unit$$s^3$$ (From GC) (ans)

(i) $$\therefore$$ Real life example of a situation in which quota sampling could be used:;Quota sampling could be used by a market researcher to conduct a survey about how frequently shoppers at a particular mall visit the mall. A sample of 100 shoppers, subdivided according to age group or gender.;;Quota sampling is appropriate in this situation because it is quick and convenient to carry out, since the tasks of listing the whole population, randomly selecting the sample and following-up on non-respondents can be omitted from the process.;;Disadvantages of quota sampling:;Quota sampling is a non-random sampling method selection that is biased as those selected will be those who are most willing to cooperate.;The issue of the sample not representative of the general population leading to faulty conclusions remains a difficult problem.;;;(ii)$$\therefore$$ Based on the situation described in part (i), stratified sampling cannot be used because the sampling frame is not accessible.

In a large population, it is found that 24% have a particular gene $$A$$, while only 0.3% have another gene $$B$$.;;$$\therefore$$ Let $$X$$ represent the number of people who have gene $$A$$ out of a random sample of 10.;$$X \sim B(10, 0.24)$$;$$\therefore$$ The probability that out of 10, at most 4 have gene $$A$$;$$ = P(X \le 4)$$;$$ = P(X = 0) + P(X = 1) + P(X = 2) + P(X = 3) + P(X = 4)$$;$$ = \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} (0.24)^0(0.76)^10 + \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} (0.24)^1(0.76)^9 + \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} (0.24)^2(0.76)^8 + \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} (0.24)^3(0.76)^7 + \begin{pmatrix} 10 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} (0.24)^4(0.76)^6$$;$$ = 0.06428 + 0.20301 + 0.288849 + 0.24294 + 0.13425 + 0.93297$$;$$ = 0.933$$ (ans);;Another random sample of 1000 from the population is taken;Using the appropriate approximations,;(i) $$\therefore$$ Let $$Y$$ represent the no. of people who have gene $$A$$ out of a random sample of 1000.;$$Y \sim B(1000, 0.24)$$;Since $$n = 1000$$ is large, $$np = 240 > 5$$ and $$n(1 - p) = 760 > 5$$,;$$Y \sim N(240, 182.4)$$ approximately;;$$\therefore$$ The probability that between 230 and 260, inclusive have gene $$A$$;$$ = P(230 \le Y \le 260)$$;$$ = P(229.5 \le Y \le 260.5)$$ (continuity correction);$$ = P(\frac{229.5 - 240}{\sqrt{182.4}} \le Z \le \frac{260.5 - 240}{\sqrt{182.4}})$$;$$ = P(-0.7775 \le Z \le 1.5.179)$$;$$ = \phi(1.518) - [1 - \phi(0.778)]$$;$$ = 0.9355 - [1 - 0.7817]$$;$$ = 0.7172 = 0.717$$ (ans);;(ii) $$\therefore$$ Let $$U$$ represent the number of people who have gene $$B$$ out of a random sample of 1000.;Since $$n = 1000$$ is large and $$np = 3< 10$$, ;$$U \sim Po(3)$$ approximately;$$\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 but fewer than 5 have gene $$B$$;$$ = P(2 \le U < 5)$$;$$ = P(U = 2 ) + P(U = 3 ) + P(U = 4 )$$;$$ = e^{-3} \left[\frac{(3)^2}{2!} + \frac{(3)^3}{3!} + \frac{(3)^4}{4!}\right]$$;$$ = 0.616$$ (ans)

A large number of school students were tasked to complete a project. Time taken by a student to complete is $$x$$ hours, out of a random sample of 150 students. The results are summarized by:;$$ \sum x = 4626, \sum x^2 = 147691$$;$$\therefore$$ Let $$X$$ represent the time in hours taken by a student to complete a project, with population mean $$\mu$$.;$$\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of mean, $$\mu$$;$$ = \overline{x} = \frac{\sum x}{n} = \frac{4626}{150} = 30.84$$ (ans);;$$\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of population variance, $$s^2$$;$$ = \frac{1}{150 - 1}[147691 - \frac{4626^2}{150}] = \frac{5025.16}{149}$$;$$ = 33.7$$ (ans);;$$\therefore$$ To test if the population mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours at 5% significance level,;Test $$H_{0}$$: $$\mu = 30$$ against $$H_{1}$$ : $$\mu > 30$$;One - tail test at 5% significance level, $$\alpha = 0.05$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, since $$n = 150$$ is large by Central Limit Theorem,;$$\overline{X} \sim N(30, \frac{33.7}{150})$$ approximately, where $$\overline{X}$$ is the sample mean.;Perform Z- test with: $$\mu_{0} = 30$$, $$s = \sqrt{33.7259}$$, $$\overline{x} = 30.84$$ and $$n = 150$$;From GC, $$p$$-value $$= 00382$$;Since $$p$$-value $$= 0.0382 < 0.05$$, we reject $$H_{0}$$ and conclude that there is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level that the mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours. (ans);;$$\therefore$$ No assumption is needed in order for the test to be valid since the sample size is large, by Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed. (ans)

In a market, chicken and turkeys are sold by weight. 2.2}{0.5}) = P (Z > 0.2667)$$;$$ = 1 - \phi(0.267)$$;$$ = 0.3947 = 0.395$$ (ans);;(ii) $$\therefore$$ To find the probability that the total selling price of a randomly chosen chicken has a selling price exceeding $7 and a randomly chosen turkey is more than $55:;The probability that a random chosen turkey costs more than $55;$$ = P(5T > 55)$$;$$ = P (T > \frac{55}{5}) = P(Z > \frac{11 - 10.5}{2.1})$$;$$ = P(Z > 0.2381) = 1 - \phi(0.238)$$;$$ = 0.4059$$;$$\therefore$$ Probability that both a random chicken costs more than $7 and a random turkey costs more than $55;$$ =  P(C > \frac{7}{3}) \times P(T > 11)$$;$$ = 0.3947 \times 0.4059$$;$$ = 0.1602 = 0.160$$ (ans);;(iii) $$\therefore$$ To find the probability that the total selling price of a randomly chosen chicken a randomly chosen turkey is more than $62:;Let $$Y$$ be the cost of 3 chickens and 5 turkeys;$$Y = 3C + 5T$$;$$ Y \sim N(3(2.2) + 5(10.5), 3^2 (0.5^2) + 5^2 (2.1^2))$$;$$\Rightarrow Y \sim N(59.1, 112.5)$$;$$\therefore$$ The probability that the total selling price of a randomly chosen chicken and a randomly chosen turkey is more than $62;$$ = P(Y > 62)$$;$$ = P(Z > \frac{62 - 59.1}{\sqrt{112.5}})$$;$$ = P(Z > 0.2734) = 1 - \phi (0.273)$$;$$ = 0.3924 = 0.392$$ (ans);;(iv) $$\therefore$$ The reason why the answer to part (iii) is greater than the answer to part (ii) is because the condition for the total selling price of a chicken and turkey exceeds $62 [part (iii)] is less restrictive than the condition for the selling price of chicken is greater then $7 and at the same time, the selling price of turkey is greater than $55 [part(ii)]. (ans)

A group of 12 people is made up of 6 married couples.;(i) The group stands in a line.;(a) $$\therefore$$ The number of different possible arrangements;$$ = 12!$$;$$ = 479001600$$ (ans);;(b)$$\therefore$$ The number of different possible orders in which each man stands next to his wife;$$ = 6! \times (2^6)$$;$$ = 46080$$ (ans);(6 couples bundled together can be arranged in 6! ways and within each couple husband and wife can switch positions.;;(ii) The group stands in a circle.;(a) $$\therefore$$ The number of different possible arrangements;$$ = (12 - 1)!$$;$$ = 11!$$;$$ = 39916800$$ (ans);;(b) $$\therefore$$ The number of different possible arrangements if men and women alternate;$$ = 5! \times 6!$$;$$ = 86400$$ (ans) ;(6 women first arranged in 5! ways, then men arranged in between them in 6! ways);;(c) $$\therefore$$ The number of different possible arrangements if each man stands next to his wife and men and women alternate;$$ = (6 - 1)! \times 2!$$;$$ = 240$$ (ans);(6 couples arranged in 5! ways; all wives sit to the right of the husband or the other way round)

An archer shoots 3 darts at a target. The probability that he is successful in hitting the target with his $$1^{st}$$ shot is $$\frac{1}{8}$$. For each of his $$2^{nd}$$ and $$3^{rd}$$ shots, the probability of success is:;- twice probability of success on preceding shot if that shot was successful;- same as probability of success on preceding shot if the shot was unsuccessful.;;$$\therefore$$ The probability tree showing the above information is shown;;img;;$$\therefore$$ Let $$S$$ denote a successful shot and $$F$$ denote a unsuccessful shot;(i) $$\therefore$$ The probability that all three shots were successful;$$ = P(SSS) = \frac{1}{8} \times \frac{2}{8} \times \frac{4}{8} = \frac{1}{64}$$;;(ii) $$\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 shots were successful;$$ = P(SSS) + P(FSS) + P(SFS) + P(SSF)$$;$$ = \frac{1}{64} + (\frac{7}{8} \times \frac{1}{8} \times \frac{2}{8}) + (\frac{1}{8} \times \frac{6}{8} \times \frac{2}{8}) + (\frac{1}{8} \times \frac{2}{8} \times \frac{4}{8})$$;$$ = \frac{1}{64} + \frac{14}{512} + \frac{12}{512} + \frac{8}{512}$$;$$ = \frac{21}{256}$$ (ans);;(iii) $$\therefore$$ The probability that the $$3^{rd}$$ shot is successful given that exactly 2 shots of the three shots are successful;$$ = \frac{P(FSS) + P(SFS)}{P(FSS) + P(SFS) + P(SSF)}$$;$$ = \frac{\frac{14}{512} + \frac{12}{512}}{\frac{14}{512} + \frac{12}{512} + \frac{8}{512}}$$;$$ = \frac{26}{34} = \frac{13}{17}$$ (ans)

The experiment is about how the concentration of a drug in the bloodstream varies with team, measured from when the drug is given. Observations at successive times are:;;img;;The value of product moment correlation coefficient for this data is -0.912, correct to 3 decimal places. Scatter plot for the data:;;img;;$$\therefore$$ To find the equation of regression line of $$x$$ on $$t$$:;Let $$n$$ be the sample size = 9;$$\sum x  = 82 + 65 + 43 + 37 + 22 + 19 + 12 + 6 + 2$$;$$ = 288$$;$$\sum x^2  = 82^2 + 65^2 + 43^2 + 37^2 + 22^2 + 19^2 + 12^2 + 6^2 + 2^2$$;$$ = 15196$$;$$\sum t = 15 + 30 + 60 + 90 + 120 +150 +180 + 240 +300$$;$$ = 1185$$;$$\sum t^2 = 15^2 + 30^2 + 60^2 + 90^2 + 120^2 +150^2 +180^2 + 240^2 +300^2$$;$$ = 229725$$;;$$\sum xt = (82)(15) + (65)(30) + (43)(60) + (37)(90) + (22)(120) + (19)(150) + (12)(180) + (6)(240) + (2)(300)$$;$$ = 18780$$;;$$\overline{x} = \frac{\sum n}{n} = \frac{288}{9} = 32$$;$$\overline{t} = \frac{\sum t}{n} = \frac{1185}{9} = 131.67$$;;Regression coefficient of $$x$$ and $$t$$:;$$\beta_{x} = \frac{\sum xt - \frac{\sum x \sum t}{n}}{\sum t^2 - \frac{(\sum t)^2}{n}}$$;$$ = \frac{18780 - \frac{288 \times 1185}{9}}{229725 - \frac{1185^2}{9}} = -0.2597$$;;$$\therefore$$ Equation of regression line of $$x$$ on $$t$$:;$$x - \overline{x} = \beta_{x} (t - \overline{t})$$;$$\Rightarrow x - 32 = - 0.2597(t - 131.67)$$;$$\Rightarrow x = - 0.2597t + 66.19$$;$$\Rightarrow x = - 0.260t + 66.2$$ (from GC) (ans);;$$\therefore$$ The corresponding estimated value of $$x$$ when $$t = 300$$;$$x_{300} = 66.1940 - 0.2597(300)$$;$$ = - 11.72 = - 11.7$$ (ans);;$$\therefore$$ Comment on the suitability of the model:;The estimated value of $$x$$ is impossible because the concentration of the drug in the bloodstream cannot be negative. Besides the curved nature of the graph suggests that a straight line is not a good model. (ans);;The variable $$y$$ is defined by $$y = \ln x$$;(i) For the variables $$y$$ and $$t$$,;$$\therefore$$ Let $$n$$ be the sample size = 9;;$$\sum y = \ln 82 + \ln 65 + \ln 43 + \ln 37 + \ln 22 + \ln 19 + \ln 12 + \ln 6 + \ln 2$$;$$ = 26.959$$;$$\sum y^2 = (\ln 82)^2 + (\ln 65)^2 + (\ln 43)^2 + (\ln 37)^2 + (\ln 22)^2 + (\ln 19)^2 + (\ln 12)^2 + (\ln 6)^2 + (\ln 2)^2$$;$$ = 92.120$$;$$\sum t = 15 + 30 + 60 + 90 + 120 +150 +180 + 240 +300$$;$$ = 1185$$;$$\sum yt = (\ln 82)(15) + (\ln 65)(30) + (\ln 43)(60) + (\ln 37)(90) + (\ln 22)(120) + (\ln 19)(150) + (\ln 12)(180) + (\ln 6)(240) + (\ln 2)(300)$$;$$ = 2639.8$$;;$$\therefore$$ The product moment correlation coefficient;$$r = \frac{\sum yt - \frac{\sum y \sum t}{n}}{\sqrt{(\sum t^2 - \frac{(\sum t)^2}{n})(\sum y^2 - \frac{(\sum y)^2}{n})}}$$;$$ = \frac{2639.8 - \frac{26.959 \times 1185}{9}}{\sqrt{(229725 - \frac{(1185)^2}{9})(92.12 - \frac{(26.959)^2}{9})}}$$;$$ = - 0.9941 = - 0.994$$ (ans);;$$\therefore$$ Comment on the value:;The product moment correlation coefficient of the linear model,;$$r = \frac{\sum xt - \frac{\sum x \sum t}{n}}{\sqrt{(\sum t^2 - \frac{(\sum t)^2}{n})(\sum x^2 - \frac{(\sum x)^2}{n})}}$$;$$ = \frac{18780 - \frac{288 \times 1185}{9}}{\sqrt{(229725 - \frac{(1185)^2}{9})(15196 - \frac{(288)^2}{9})}}$$;$$ = - 0.9117 = -0.912$$;;This indicates a stronger correlation is between $$y$$ and $$t$$ ($$| r | = 0.994$$) and this | value | is closer to 1 than the value obtained from the linear model ($$| r | = 0.912$$). (ans);;(ii) $$\therefore$$ Regression coefficient of $$y$$ and $$t$$:; $$\beta_{y} = \frac{\sum yt - \frac{\sum y \sum t}{n}}{\sum t^2 - \frac{(\sum t)^2}{n}}$$;$$ = \frac{2639.8 - \frac{26.959 \times 1185}{9}}{229725 - \frac{1185^2}{9}} = -0.01234$$;;$$\overline{y} = \frac{\sum y}{n} = \frac{26.959}{9} = 2.995$$;;$$\therefore$$ Equation of regression line of $$y$$ on $$t$$:;$$y - \overline{y} = \beta_{y} (t - \overline{t})$$;$$\Rightarrow y - 2.995 = - 0.01234 (t - 131.67)$$;$$\Rightarrow y = - 0.01234t + 4.621$$;$$\Rightarrow y = - 0.0123t + 4.62$$ (from GC) (ans);;When the drug concentration $$(x)$$ is 15 micrograms per litre,;$$\Rightarrow y = \ln 15$$;$$\Rightarrow \ln 15 = 4.62 - 0.0123t$$;$$\Rightarrow t = 155.02$$;;$$\therefore$$ The best estimate of time when drug concentration is 15 mg$$l^{-1}$$:;$$ t = 155$$ min (ans)

fields.content: Graphical Form: $$ax + by = c$$ or Gradient-Intercept Form: $$y= mx + c$$ or Double Intercept Form: $$\frac{x}{a} + \frac{y}{b} = 1$$
fields.title: Linear Function

fields.content: $$y = \sin x$$ or $$y = \cos x$$ or $$y = \tan x$$
fields.title: Trigonometrical Functions

fields.content: (a) Even Power Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{ 2, 4, 6, ...\}$$  ;(b) Odd Power Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{ 3, 5, 7, ...\}$$
fields.title: Power Functions

fields.content: (a) Even Reciprocal Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{ .... , -6 ,-4 , -2\}$$  ;(b) Odd Reciprocal Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{ ...., -7, -5, -3\}$$
fields.title: Power Functions - Reciprocal

fields.content: (a) Even Root Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{4}, ...\}$$  ;(b) Odd Root Function: $$y = {x}^{n}$$ where $$n \in \{\frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{5} ...\}$$
fields.title: Power Functions - Root

fields.content: (a) Circle: $$x^2 + y^2 = r^2$$ Centre at (0,0) and Radius r    ;(b) Ellipse: $$\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1$$ Centre at (0,0) and Radii a and b
fields.title: Conics

fields.content: Hyperbola: $$\frac{x^2}{a^2} - \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1$$ Centre at (0,0) and Vertices at (-a,0) and (a,0)  or  $$\frac{y^2}{b^2} - \frac{x^2}{a^2} = 1$$ Centre at (0,0) and Vertices at (0,-b) and (0,b)
fields.title: Conics - Hyperbola

fields.content: Given the graph of a function $$y = f(x)$$: if the variable $$x$$ is replaces by a function of $$x$$, or if the variable $$y$$ is replaced by a function of $$y$$, then graphically, this will correspond to a Transformation of the graph $$y = f(x)$$
fields.title: Transformations

fields.content: Horizontal Translation of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$y = f(x + a)$$
fields.title: Horizontal Translation

fields.content: Vertical Translation of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$y + a = f(x)$$
fields.title: Vertical Translation

fields.content: The general equation of a circle with centre at $$(p,q)$$ and radius $$r$$ is $$(x - p)^2 + (y - q)^2 = r^2$$ with axes of symmetry $$x = p$$ and $$y = q$$ and point of symmetry $$(p,q)$$
fields.title: General Equation of Circle

fields.content: The general equation of a ellipse with centre at $$(p,q)$$ and radii $$a$$ and $$b$$ is $$\frac{(x - p)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y - q)^2}{b^2} = 1$$ with axes of symmetry $$x = p$$ and $$y = q$$ and point of symmetry $$(p,q)$$
fields.title: General Equation of Ellipse

fields.content: The general equation of a hyperbola with centre at $$(p,q)$$ and oblique asymptotes $$(y - q) = \pm \frac{b}{a}(x - p)$$ is $$\frac{(x - p)^2}{a^2} - \frac{(y - q)^2}{b^2} = 1$$ or $$\frac{(y - q)^2}{b^2} - \frac{(x - p)^2}{a^2} = 1$$with axes of symmetry $$x = p$$ and $$y = q$$ and point of symmetry $$(p,q)$$
fields.title: General Equation of Hyperbola

fields.content: Horizontal Scaling of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$y = f(ax)$$
fields.title: Horizontal Scaling

fields.content: Vertical Scaling of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$ay = f(x)$$
fields.title: Vertical Scaling

fields.content: Horizontal Reflection of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$y = f(- x)$$
fields.title: Horizontal Reflection

fields.content: Vertical Reflection of graph $$y = f(x)$$: $$- y = f(x)$$
fields.title: Vertical Reflection

fields.content: Given the graph of a function $$y = f(x)$$: the graphs of functions $$y = f(ax + b)$$ and $$(ay + b) = f(x)$$ are obtained by performing a Sequence of Composite Transformations on the graph of $$y = f(x)$$
fields.title: Composite Transformations

fields.content: Given a function $$y = f(x)$$: ;(a) Vertical Asymptote: as $$x \to k$$ , $$y \to \infty$$  or  as $$x \to k$$ , $$y \to -\infty$$  ;(b) Horizontal Asymptote: as $$x \to \infty$$ , $$y \to h$$  or  as $$x \to -\infty$$ , $$y \to h$$  ;(c) Slant Asymptote: as $$x \to \infty$$ , $$y \to mx + c$$  or  as $$x \to -\infty$$ , $$y \to mx + c$$
fields.title: General Curve - Asymptotes

fields.content: For Rational Function $$y = \frac{N(x)}{D(x)}$$ where $$N(x)$$ and $$D(x)$$ are polynomial functions: ;(a) Vertical Asymptotes: Solve $$D(x) = 0$$  ;(b) Horizontal Asymptotes: ;If degree of $$N(x)$$ < degree of $$D(x)$$, then y = 0 else If degree of $$N(x)$$ = degree of $$D(x)$$, divide out to get $$\frac{N(x)}{D(x)} = h + \frac{n(x)}{D(x)}$$ and $$y = h$$ is the horizontal asymptote  ;If degree of $$N(x)$$ > degree of $$D(x)$$, divide out to get $$\frac{N(x)}{D(x)} = p(x) + \frac{n(x)}{D(x)}$$ and if $$p(x) = mx + c$$ is linear function then $$y = mx + c$$ is the horizontal asymptote
fields.title: Rational Functions - Asymptotes

fields.content: Representations such as $$x = g(t)$$ and $$y = h(t)$$ are known as Parametric Equations and $$t$$ is the Parameter
fields.title: Parametric Equations

fields.content: The graphs of $$y = |f(x)|$$ and $$y = f(|x|)$$ are transformations of the graph  $$y = f(x)$$
fields.title: Special Graphs - Type 1

fields.content: Graph $$y^2 = f(x)$$ is a transformation of the graph $$y = f(x)$$ as follows: $$y^2 = f(x) \implies y = \sqrt{f(x)}$$ or $$y = -\sqrt{f(x)}$$
fields.title: Special Graphs - Type 2

fields.content: Graph $$y = \frac{1}{f(x)}$$ is a transformation of the graph $$y = f(x)$$
fields.title: Special Graphs - Type 3

fields.content: Given a function $$f : x \mapsto f(x), x  \in X$$: $$f$$ is a one-one function $$\iff$$ the rule $$x \mapsto f(x)$$ of the function $$f$$ is a One-one Relation for all $$x \in X$$
fields.title: One - One Function

fields.content: Given a function $$f : x \mapsto f(x), x  \in X$$ which is not one-one, the domain $${D}_{f} = X$$ can be restricted in such a way that its restriction $${f}_{R}$$ : $$x \mapsto f(x), x \in {X}_{R}$$ is one-one
fields.title: Restriction to One-one Function

fields.content: Given a function $$f : x \mapsto f(x), x  \in X$$ with $${D}_{f} = X$$ and $${R}_{f} = Y$$, its Inverse Function is $${f}^{-1}$$ : $$y \mapsto x, y \in Y$$ with $${D}_{f^{-1}} = Y$$ and $${R}_{f^{-1}} = X$$ exists $$\iff$$ $$f$$ is one-one
fields.title: Inverse Function

fields.content: Given two functions: $$f$$ : $$x \mapsto f(x), x \in {X}_{f}$$ and $$g$$ : $$x \mapsto g(x), x \in {X}_{g}$$, the composite function $$g \circ f$$ : $$x \mapsto g(f(x)), x \in {X}_{f}$$
fields.title: Composite Function

fields.content: Given an inequality: $$g(x) > h(x)$$ ;(i) Rearrange $$g(x) > h(x)$$ into its Homogenous Form: $$f(x) > 0$$ or $$f(x) < 0$$ ;(ii) Factorise $$f(x)$$ completely into Linear Factors : $$(ax + b)(cx + d)... > 0$$ ;(iii) For each Linear Factor, find Critical Value: $$ ax + b = 0 \implies x = -\frac{b}{a}$$ ;(iv) Mark all critical values on a Number Line ;(v) Complete a Sign Diagram by doing a Sign Test on each interval ;(vi) Determine Solution Set
fields.title: Polynomial Inequality

fields.content: (a) Factorisable Quadratics: ;Given a quadratic $$ax^2 + bx + c$$ with $$b^2 - 4ac > 0$$: ;$$ax^2 + bx + c = a(x - \frac{- b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a})(x - \frac{- b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a})$$; ;(b) Non-Factorisable Quadratics:  ;Given a quadratic $$ax^2 + bx + c$$ with $$b^2 - 4ac < 0$$: $$b^2 - 4ac < 0$$ and $$a > 0$$:;(i) $$ax^2 + bx = c > 0 \implies x \in R$$ ;(ii) $$ax^2 + bx = c < 0 \implies x \in \{\}$$
fields.title: Quadratic Inequalities

fields.content: For inequalities involving rational functions, the solution set must exclude all the Zero's of its Denominator.
fields.title: Inequalities - Rational Functions

fields.content: Used to solve inequality of the form: $$f(x) > 0$$ or $$f(x) < 0$$ or of the form $$g(x) > h(x)$$
fields.title: Solutions of Inequalities - Graphical Method

fields.content: Given any real number $$k > 0$$: ;(i) $$| x | < k \implies -k < x < k$$ ;(ii)$$| f(x) | < k \implies -k < f(x) < k$$
fields.title: Inequalities - Modulus Functions

fields.content: Using a graphical calculator, we can solve simultaneously for all unknowns using an Augmented Matrix. Any system of simultaneous linear equations will have one of the following: ;(i) Unique solution ;(ii) Infinitely many solutions ;(iii) No solution.
fields.title: System of Linear Equations

fields.content: For any $$n \in {Z}^{+}$$ : $$(a + b)^n = a^n  + na^{n-1}b + \binom{n}{2}a^{n-2}b^2 + ..... + \binom{n}{n-2}a^2b^{n-2} + \binom{n}{n-1}ab^{n-1} + b^n$$ where $$\binom{n}{r}a^{n-r}b^r$$ is called General Term of Expansion.
fields.title: Binomial Theorem

fields.content: For any $$n \in Q$$ : $$(1 + x)^n = 1 + nx + \frac{n(n-1)}{2!}x^2 + \frac{n(n-1)(n-2}{3!}x^3 + ... + \frac{n(n-1)(n-2)...(n-r+1)}{r!}x^r + ...$$  ;If $$n \in {Z}^{+}$$, then expansion is valid for all $$x \in R$$ and has finite number of $$n + 1$$ terms.   ;If $$n \in Q$$ but $$n \in {Z}^{+}$$, then expansion is valid only for $$| x | < 1: -1 < x < 1$$ and has infinite number of terms.
fields.title: Binomial Series

fields.content: $$(a + bx)^n = (a(1 + \frac{bx}{a}))^n = a^n(1 + \frac{bx}{a})^n = a^n(1 + n(\frac{bx}{a}) + \frac{n(n-1)}{2!}(\frac{bx}{a})^2 + \frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}(\frac{bx}{a})^3 + ... )$$. This expansion is valid for $$|\frac{bx}{a}| < 1 \implies | x | < \frac{a}{b} \implies -\frac{a}{b} < x < \frac{a}{b}$$
fields.title: Expansion in Ascending Powers of x

fields.content: $$(a + bx)^n = (bx(\frac{a}{bx} + 1))^n = (bx)^n(1 + \frac{a}{bx})^n = (bx)^n(1 + n(\frac{a}{bx}) + \frac{n(n-1)}{2!}(\frac{a}{bx})^2 + \frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}(\frac{a}{bx})^3 + .... )$$. This expansion is valid for $$|\frac{a}{bx}| < 1 \implies | x | > \frac{a}{b} \implies x < -\frac{a}{b}$$ or $$x > \frac{a}{b}$$
fields.title: Expansion in Descending Powers of x

fields.content: In using the binomial series for numerical approximations, the value of $$x$$ must fall within the interval of convergence. ;If the expansion is in ascending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ must be as close to zero as possible: $$| x | < k $$, so that higher powers of $$x$$ are negligible. ;If the expansion is in descending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ should be as far away from zero as possible: $$| x | > k$$ so that higher powers of $$(\frac{1}{x})$$ are negligible.
fields.title: Binomial Series in Numerical Approximations

fields.content: (i) General Form: $$a, a+d, a +2d, ... , a + (n-1)d , ...$$    ;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = a + (n - 1)d$$    ;(iii) Common difference $$d$$: $$d = {T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1}$$    ;(iv) Arithmetic Mean: $$\frac{{T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1}}{2} = {T}_{n} \implies  {T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1} = 2{T}_{n}$$    ;(v) Sum of the first $$n$$ terms $${S}_{n}$$: $${S}_{n} = \frac{n}{2}(2a + (n - 1)d)$$ or $${S}_{n} = \frac{n}{2}(a + l)$$ where $$l = {T}_{n} = a + (n-1)d$$
fields.title: Arithmetic Progression

fields.content: (i) General Form: $$a, ar, ar^2, ar^3, ... ,ar^{n-1}, ...$$  ;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = ar^{n-1}$$  ;(iii) Common Ratio $$r$$ : $$r = \frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}}$$  ;(iv) Geometric Mean: $$\sqrt{{T}_{n-1} \times {T}_{n+1}} = {T}_{n} \implies {T}_{n-1} \times {T}_{n+1} = {{T}_{n}}^2$$  ;(v) Geometric Series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+ ... + ar^{n-1} + ... $$  ;(vi) Sum of the first n terms $${S}_{n}$$ : $${S}_{n} = \frac{a(1-r^n)}{1-r}$$ or $$\frac{a(r^n-1)}{r-1}$$
fields.title: Geometric Progression

fields.content: $${S}_{\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\infty} = \frac{a}{1 - r}$$
fields.title: Convergent Infinite Geometric Series

fields.content: Given a general infinite geometric series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+...$$ ;(i) $$| r | < 1 \implies {S}_{\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\infty} = \frac{a}{1-r}$$. We say that the series is Convergent.   ;(ii)$$| r | > 1 \implies {S}_{\infty}$$ does not exist. We say that the series is Divergent.
fields.title: General Infinite Geometric Series

fields.content: (i) If $${T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is an AP with common difference $$d = k$$. ;(ii) If $$\frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is a GP with common ratio $$r = k$$. ;(iii) If neither of the above occur, then the sequence is neither an AP or GP.
fields.title: AP or GP Determination

fields.content: $$\sum_{r=1}^{n} a = a + a + a + ... + a = na$$ where $$a$$ is a constant.
fields.title: Rules of Summation - Rule 1

fields.content: $$\sum_{r=m}^{n} a = (n - m + 1)a$$ where $$a$$ is a constant.
fields.title: Rules of Summation - Rule 2

fields.content: $$\sum_{r =1}^{n} a^r = a + a^2 + a^3 + ... + a^n = \frac{a(1-a^n)}{1 - a}$$ or $$\frac{a(a^n - 1)}{a - 1}$$ where $$a$$ is a constant. $$\sum_{r = 1}^{\infty} a^r = a + a^2 + a^3 + ... = \frac{a}{1 - a}$$ where $$| a | < 1$$.
fields.title: Rules of Summation - Rule 6

fields.content: $$\sum_{r=1}^{n} \lambda {T}_{r} = \lambda \sum_{r=1}^{n} {T}_{r}$$ where $$\lambda$$ is a constant.
fields.title: General Rules of Summation 1

fields.content: $$\sum_{r=1}^{n} (\lambda {T}_{r} \pm \mu {U}_{r}) = \lambda \sum_{r=1}^{n} {T}_{r} \pm \mu \sum_{r=1}^{n} {U}_{r}$$ where $$\lambda , \mu$$ are constants.
fields.title: General Rules of Summation 2

fields.content: Given a series: $${u}_{1} + {u}_{2} + {u}_{3} + ... + {u}_{n} = \sum_{r=1}^{n} {u}_{r}$$, if the general term $${u}_{r}$$ can be represented as a difference of two expressions: $${u}_{r} \equiv f(r) - f(r+1)$$ where $$f$$ is an integer function of $$r \in Z$$; then $$\sum_{r=1}^{n} {u}_{r} = \sum_{r=1}^{n} (f(r) - f(r+1)) = f(1) - f(n+1)$$
fields.title: Summation by Method of Difference

fields.content: $$\sum_{r=1}^{\infty} {u}_{r} = \lim_{n \to \infty} (\sum_{r=1}^{n} {u}_{r})$$
fields.title: Summation of General Infinite Series

fields.content: Steps involved: ;(i) Definition: Define $${P}_{n}$$  ;(ii) Initial or Starting Value : Show that $${P}_{1}$$ is true  ;(iii) Induction Hypothesis: Assumption that $${P}_{k}$$ is true.  ;(iv) Induction: Show that $${P}_{k}$$ is true $$\implies {P}_{k+1}$$ is true.  ;(v) Conclusion: $${P}_{n}$$ is true for all $$n \in {Z}^{+}$$
fields.title: Principle of Mathematical Induction

fields.content: (i) $$\frac{d}{dx}({x}^{n}) = n{x}^{n-1}$$  ;(ii)$$\frac{d}{dx}({x}) = 1$$  ;(iii)$$\frac{d}{dx}(c) = 0$$  (c is a constant)
fields.title: Standard Derivatives - Power Differentiation

fields.content: (i)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\sin x) = \cos x$$  ;(ii)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\cos x) = - \sin x$$  ;(iii)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\tan x) = {\sec}^{2} x$$  ;(iv)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\csc x) = - \csc x \cot x$$  ;(v)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\sec x) = \sec x \tan x$$  ;(vi)$$\frac{d}{dx}(\cot x) = - {\csc}^2 x$$
fields.title: Standard Derivatives - Trigonometrical Differentiation

fields.content: (i)$$\frac{d}{dx}(e^x) = e^x$$  ;(ii)$$\frac{d}{dx}(a^x) = a^x \ln a$$
fields.title: Standard Derivatives - Exponential Differentiation

fields.content: (i) $$\frac{d}{dx}(\ln x) = \frac{1}{x}$$  ;(ii) $$\frac{d}{dx}\log_{a} x = \frac{1}{x \ln a}$$
fields.title: Standard Derivatives - Logarithmic Differentiation

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(af(x)) = a \frac{d}{dx}(f(x))$$ ( a is constant)
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Constant Multiple Rule

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(f(x) \pm g(x)) = \frac{d}{dx}(f(x)) \pm \frac{d}{dx}(g(x))$$
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Sum and Difference Rule

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(f(g(x))) = f^'(g(x)) \times g^'(x)$$
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Composite/Chain Rule

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(uv) = v \frac{d}{dx}(u) + u \frac{d}{dx}(v)$$
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Product Rule

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(\frac{u}{v}) = \frac{v \frac{du}{dx} - u \frac{dv}{dx}}{v^2}$$
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Quotient Rule

fields.content: $$\frac{dx}{dy} = \frac{1}{\frac{dy}{dx}}$$
fields.title: Rules of Differentiation - Reciprocal Rule

fields.content: (i)$$\frac{d}{dx}\sin^{-1} x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$$  ;(ii)$$\frac{d}{dx}\cos^{-1} x = - \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$$  ;(iii)$$\frac{d}{dx}\tan^{-1} x = \frac{1}{1 + x^2}$$
fields.title: Inverse Trigonometrical Differentiation

fields.content: $$\frac{d}{dx}(f(y)) = \frac{d(f(y))}{dy} \frac{dy}{dx} = f^'(y)\frac{dy}{dx}$$
fields.title: Implicit Differentiation

fields.content: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{dy}{dt} \times \frac{dt}{dx} = \frac{dy/dt}{dx/dt} = \frac{k^'(t)}{h^'(t)}$$
fields.title: Parametric Differentiation

fields.content: (i) First Derivative: $$\frac{d}{dx}y = \frac{dy}{dx} = f'(x)$$  ;(ii) Second Derivative: $$\frac{d}{dx}\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = f''(x)$$  ;(iii) Third Derivative: $$\frac{d}{dx}\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \frac{d^3y}{dx^3} = f'''(x)$$ ;(iv)nth Derivative: $$\frac{d}{dx}\frac{d^{n-1}y}{dx^{n-1}} = \frac{d^ny}{dx^n} = f'^{(n)}(x)$$
fields.title: Higher Derivatives

fields.content: Equation of the Tangent to the curve $$y = f(x)$$ at the point $$P(x_{1}, y_{1})$$ is given by $$\frac{y_{1} - y}{x_{1} - x} = m$$ or $$y - {y}_{1} = m(x -x_{1})$$ where $$m = \frac{dy}{dx}$$
fields.title: Equation of Tangent

fields.content: Equation of the Normal to the curve $$y = f(x)$$ at the point $$P(x_{1}, y_{1})$$ is given by $$\frac{y_{1} - y}{x_{1} - x} = - \frac{1}{m}$$ or $$y - {y}_{1} = -\frac{1}{m}(x -x_{1})$$ where $$m = \frac{dy}{dx}$$
fields.title: Equation of Normal

fields.content: Test the signs of the gradient $$\frac{dy}{dx}$$ just to the Left and Right of $$x = x_{1}$$  ;(i)Maximum point if $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{-})$$ is + and  $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{+})$$ is - .   ;(ii)Minimum Point if point if $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{-})$$ is - and  $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{+})$$ is + .  ;(iii)Stationary point of inflexion if $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{-})$$ and  $$\frac{dy}{dx}(x_{1}^{+})$$ are of the same sign.
fields.title: Nature of Stationary Points -  Method 1

fields.content: The curvature of a graph $$y = f(x)$$ can be obtained by the following: ;(i) $$\frac{dy}{dx} \ge 0 \iff f$$ is increasing function over [a,b].  ;(ii) $$\frac{dy}{dx} \le 0 \iff f$$ is decreasing function over [a,b].  ;(iii) $$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} \ge 0 \iff f$$ is Concave Upward over [a,b].  ;(iv) $$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} \le 0 \iff f$$ is Concave Downward over [a,b].
fields.title: Graphical Interpretation of First and Second Derivatives

fields.content: Steps: ;(1) Obtain an expression for the quantity $$y$$ which is to be maximized or minimized in terms of one or more related variables. ;(2) Express the quantity $$y$$ in terms of only one variable $$x : y=f(x)$$ using the conditions given. ;(3)Differentiate the expression to find $$dy/dx$$  ;(4)Set the derivative to 0 and solve for the unknown $$x$$. ;(5)Test the nature of the stationary values, if necessary.  ;(6) Determine the required maximum or minimum value of the quantity $$y$$.
fields.title: Maximization and Minimization

fields.content: Steps: ;(1)Denote the changing quantities by the variables $$x$$ and $$y$$;(2)Obtain an equation relating $$x$$ and $$y : y = f(x)$$;(3)Differentiate the equation $$y = f(x)$$ to obtain $$\frac{dy}{dx}$$;(4)Obtain the rate of change of $$x : \frac{dx}{dt}$$;(5)Find the rate of change of $$y : \frac{dy}{dt}$$, using the chain rule $$\frac{dy}{dt} = \frac{dy}{dx} \times \frac{dx}{dt}$$
fields.title: Rates of Change

fields.content: (1) Graph of $$y = f(x)$$ increasing over $$x \in [x_{1},x_{2}]$$ gives graph of $$y = f'(x)$$ above the x axis for $$x \in [x_{1},x_{2}]$$  ;(2) Graph of $$y = f(x)$$ decreasing over $$x \in [x_{1},x_{2}]$$ gives graph of $$y = f'(x)$$ below the x axis for $$x \in [x_{1},x_{2}]$$  ;(3) Stationary Point at $$(a,b)$$, x-intercept at $$x=a$$  ;(4) Vertical Asymptote $$x=k$$ ;(5) Horizontal Asymptote $$y=h$$ and graph of $$y = f'(x)$$ gives horizontal asymptote at $$y=0$$  ;(6)Slant Asymptote $$y=mx + c$$ and graph of $$y=f'(x)$$ gives horizontal asymptote at $$y=m$$
fields.title: Graphical Relation between y = f(x) and y = f'(x)

fields.content: (i) $$\int x^n dx = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C$$  ;(ii)$$\int x^{-1} dx = \ln |x| + C$$  ;(iii)$$\int k dx = kx + C$$  ;(iv)$$\int 0 dx = C$$
fields.title: Standard Integrals - Power Integration

fields.content: (i)$$\int e^x dx = e^x + c$$  ;(ii)$$\int a^x dx = \frac{a^x}{\ln a} + c$$
fields.title: Standard Integrals - Exponential Integration

fields.content: (i)$$\int \sin x dx = - \cos x + c$$  ;(ii)$$\int \cos x dx =  \sin x + c$$  ;(iii)$$\int \sec^2 x dx =  \tan x + c$$  ;(iv) $$\int \csc^2 x dx = - \cot x + c$$  ;(v)$$\int \sec x \tan x dx =  \sec x + c$$  ;(vi)$$\int \csc x \cot x dx = - \csc x + c$$
fields.title: Standard Integrals - Trigonometrical Integration

fields.content: $$\int k f(x) dx = k \int f(x) dx$$, $$k$$ is a constant
fields.title: Rules of Integration - Constant Multiple Rule

fields.content: $$\int f(x) \pm g(x) dx = \int f(x) dx \pm \int g(x) dx$$
fields.title: Rules of Integration - Sum and Difference Rule

fields.content: If $$\int f(x) dx = F(x) + c$$ Then $$\int f(ax + b) dx = \frac{F(ax +b)}{a} + c$$
fields.title: Rules of Integration - Linear Composite Rule

fields.content: If $$\int f(x) dx = F(x) + c$$ Then $$\int g'(x) f(g(x)) dx = F(g(x)) + c$$
fields.title: Rules of Integration - Reverse Composite Rule

fields.content: (i)$$\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2}} dx = \sin^{-1} x + c$$ and $$\int \frac{1}{1+ x^2}dx = \tan^{-1} x + c$$  ;(ii)$$\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - (ax + b)^2}} dx = \frac{\sin^{-1} (ax + b)}{a} + c$$ and $$\int \frac{1}{1+ (ax +b)^2}dx = \frac{\tan^{-1} (ax +b)}{a} + c$$  ;(iii)$$\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{a^2 - x^2}} dx = \sin^{-1} \frac{x}{a} + c$$ and $$\int \frac{1}{a^2+ x^2}dx = \tan^{-1} \frac{x}{a} + c$$ ;(iv)$$\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{k^2 - (ax+b)^2}} dx = \frac{1}{a} \sin^{-1} (\frac{ax + b}{k}) + c$$ and $$\int \frac{1}{k^2+ (ax +b)^2}dx = \frac{1}{a} \tan^{-1} (\frac{ax + b}{k}) + c$$  ;(v)$$\int \frac{g'(x)}{\sqrt{1 - (g(x))^2}} dx = \sin^{-1} (g(x)) + c$$ and $$\int \frac{g'(x)}{1+ (g(x))^2}dx = \tan^{-1} (g(x)) + c$$  ;(vi)$$\int \frac{g'(x)}{\sqrt{a^2 - (g(x))^2}} dx = \sin^{-1} (\frac{g(x)}{a}) + c$$ and $$\int \frac{g'(x)}{a^2+ (g(x))^2}dx = \frac{1}{a} \tan^{-1} (\frac{g(x)}{a}) + c$$
fields.title: integration Results from Inverse Trigonometrical Differentiation

fields.content: (a) Integrals of the form: $$\int \sin^n x dx, \int \cos^n x dx, \int \tan^n x dx, \int \cot^n x dx$$ where n = 2,3  ;(b) Integrals of the form: $$\int \sin^m x \cos^n x dx$$ where m = 3 or n = 3  ;(c) Integrals of the form: $$\int \sin ax \cos bx dx, \int \cos ax \sin bx dx, \int \cos ax \cos bx dx, \int \sin ax \sin bx dx$$
fields.title: Trigonometrical Integration

fields.content: For Integrals of Rational Functions: $$\int \frac{N(x)}{D(x)}dx$$ where $$D(x)$$ can be factorized into Linear Factors: $$ax + b$$ and for Repeated Linear Factors: $$(ax +b)^2$$ and for Irreducible Quadratic Factors :$$ax^2 + bx +c$$. We can express the integral $$\frac{N(x)}{D(x)}$$ into sums of partial fractions: $$\frac{A}{ax + b} + \frac{A}{(ax + b)^2} = \frac{Ax + B}{ax^2 + bx + c}$$
fields.title: Integration using Partial Fractions

fields.content: (i) $$\int \frac{1}{x^2 - a^2}dx = \frac{1}{2a}\ln |\frac{x - a}{x + a}| + c$$  ;(ii)$$\int \frac{1}{(bx + d)^2 - a^2}dx = \frac{1}{2ab}\ln |\frac{(bx + d) - a}{(bx + d) + a}| + c$$  ;(iii)$$\int \frac{g'(x)}{(g(x))^2 - a^2}dx = \frac{1}{2a}\ln |\frac{g(x) - a}{g(x) + a}| + c$$
fields.title: Integration Results From Partial Fractions

fields.content: Given a function $$f(x)$$ : $$\int f(x)dx = F(x)$$. Suppose $$x$$ is also a function of $$u$$: $$\int g'(u)f(g(u))du = F(g(u))$$. SInce $$F(x) = F(g(u))$$: $$\int f(x)dx = \int g'(u)f(g(u))du = \int \frac{du}{dx}f(g(u))du$$. Hence $$\int f(x)dx = \int f(g(u))\frac{dx}{du}du$$ where $$x = g(u)$$ and $$\frac{dx}{du} = g'(u)$$ and $$x = g(u)$$ is known as Substitution.
fields.title: Integration by Substitution

fields.content: $$\int u\frac{dv}{dx}dx = uv - \int v\frac{du}{dx}dx$$
fields.title: Integration by Parts

fields.content: Given that $$f(x)$$ and $$g(x)$$ are Continuous Functions in the interval [a,b]: ;(1)$$\int_{a}^{b}kf(x)dx = k \int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx$$ ;(2)$$\int_{a}^{b}(f(x) \pm g(x))dx = \int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx \pm \int_{a}^{b}g(x)dx$$  ;(3)$$\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx = 0$$  ;(4)$$\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx = - \int_{b}^{a}f(x)dx$$  ;(5)$$\int_{a}^{m} f(x)dx + \int_{m}^{b} f(x)dx = \int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx$$
fields.title: Properties of Definite Integrals

fields.content: $$\int_{a}^{b}u\frac{dv}{dx}dx = [uv]_{a}^{b} - \int_{a}^{b}v\frac{du}{dx}dx$$
fields.title: Definite Integral - Integration by Parts

fields.content: $$\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx = \int_{u=g^{-1}(a)}^{u=g^{-1}(b)}f(g(u))\frac{dx}{du}du$$
fields.title: Definite Integral - Substitution

fields.content: (1) As the Area under the curve $$y = f(x)$$ from $$x = a$$ to $$x = b$$  ;(2) As a Limit of Sum: $$\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx = \lim_{x \to \infty}\sum_{i=1}^{n}f(x_{i})\delta x$$  ;(3)As the Reverse Process of Differentiation:$$\int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx = F(b) - F(a)$$
fields.title: Interpretation of Definite Integral

fields.content: (1) Area between a Curve and x-axis: $$A = \int_{a}^{b}ydx = \int_{a}^{b}f(x)dx$$  ;(2) Area between a Curve and the Y-axis: $$A = \int_{a}^{b}xdy = \int_{a}^{b}g(y)dy$$  ;(3) Area between Two Curves: $$A = \int_{a}^{b}(y_{1} - y_{2})dx = \int_{a}^{b}(f_{1}(x) - f_{2}(x))dx$$  ;(4) Area between a Parametric Curve and the x - axis: $$x = h(t) \implies \frac{dx}{dt} = h'(t) \implies dx = h'(t)dt$$ and $$A = \int_{x=a}^{x=b}ydx = \int_{t=\alpha}^{t=\beta}k(t)h'(t)dt$$  ;(5)Area between a Parametric Curve and the y - axis: $$y = k(t) \implies \frac{dy}{dt} = k'(t) \implies dy = k'(t)dt$$ and $$A = \int_{y=c}^{y=d}xdy = \int_{t=\alpha}^{t=\beta}h(t)k'(t)dt$$
fields.title: Application of Integration - Area

fields.content: First order differential equations of the form: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)$$ can be solved by Direct Integration: $$y = \int f(x)dx + A$$ where A is called an Arbitrary Constant of Integration and $$y = \int f(x)dx + A$$ is called the General Solution.
fields.title: First Order Differential Equations - Direct Integration

fields.content: First order differential equations of the form: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = g(y)$$ or $$\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)$$ or $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{f(x)}{g(y)}$$ or $$f(x)\frac{dy}{dx} = g(y)$$ is said to be Variable Separable. Such differential equations can be solved by the following: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = g(y) \equiv \frac{1}{g(y)}dy = 1dx \equiv \int \frac{1}{g(y)}dy = \int 1dx$$ or $$\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y) \equiv \frac{1}{g(y)}dy = f(x)dx \equiv \int \frac{1}{g(y)}dy = \int f(x)dx$$
fields.title: First Order Differential Equations - Variable Separable

fields.content: Differential equations such as $$x\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y$$ and $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \cos (x - y)$$ cannot be solved by direct integration and they are not variable separable. By using a suitable Substitution: $$y = f(x,u)$$: a given differential equation in x and y may be reduced into a simpler differential equation in x and u. This simpler differential equation can then be solved by direct integration or variable separable.
fields.title: First Order Differential Equations - Substitution

fields.content: Second order differential equations of the form :$$\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = f(x)$$ can be solved by applying Direct Integration twice: $$\frac{dy}{dx} = \int f(x)dx + A$$ and $$y = \int (\int f(x)dx)dx + Ax + B$$ where A and B are Arbitrary Constants of Integration and $$y = \int (\int f(x)dx)dx + Ax + B$$ is called the General Solution.
fields.title: Second Order Differential Equations

fields.content: (1) Volume of Revolution about the x - axis: $$V_{r} = \int_{a}^{b}\pi y^2dx$$ or $$\pi \int_{a}^{b}(f(x))^2dx$$  ;(2) Volume of Revolution about the y - axis: $$V_{y} = \int_{c}^{d} \pi x^2dy$$ or $$\pi \int_{c}^{d}(g(y))^2dy$$ ;(3) Volume generated by Area Between Two Curves: $$V = \int_{a}^{b}(\pi y_{1}^2 - \pi y_{2}^2)dx$$ or $$\pi \int_{a}^{b}(f_{1}(x))^2 - (f_{2}(x))^2)dx$$  ;(4) Volume of Revolution about the Horizontal Line y = h: $$V = \int_{a}^{b} \pi(y - h)^2dx$$ or $$\pi \int_{a}^{b}(f(x) - h)^2dx$$  ;(5) Volume of Revolution about the Vertical Line x = k: $$V = \int_{c}^{d} \pi (x - k)^2dy$$ or $$\pi \int_{c}^{d} (g(y) - k)^2dy$$
fields.title: Application of Integration - Volume

fields.content: Given a differential equation $$\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)$$, its general solution $$y = \int f(x)dx + A$$ is geometrically represented by a family of solution curves. ;When sketching the family of solution curves of a differential equation, unless otherwise stated, it is a usual practice to sketch: ;(i) one particular solution curve for $$A=0$$  ;(ii) one or two particular solution curves for $$A > 0$$  ;(iii) one or two particular solution curves for $$A < 0$$
fields.title: Applications of Differential Equations - Family of Solution Curves

fields.content: If a physical quantity $$y$$ varies continuously with time $$t : y = f(t)$$. Hence, the rate of change of $$y : \frac{dy}{dt}$$ is not constant. ;But $$\frac{dy}{dt}$$ varies with $$y$$ itself : $$\frac{dy}{dt} = g(y)$$. Such a rate of change is known as Rate of Growth or Rate of Decay. Solving this differential equation $$\frac{dy}{dt} = g(y)$$ will give the function $$ y = f(t)$$
fields.title: Applications of Differential Equations - Formulation of Differential Equations

fields.content: (1) Vector Addition: The vector sum $$a + b$$ is obtained by the Polygon Law of Vector Addition.  ;(2) Vector Subtraction: Vector Difference $$a - b$$ is defined as the vector sum $$a + ( - b )$$  ;(3) Scalar Multiplication of Vectors: ;(i) If $$k > 0$$: $$ka$$ is in the same direction as $$a$$ ;(ii) If $$k < 0$$: $$ka$$ is in the opposite direction to $$a$$ ;(iii) If $$k = 0$$: $$ka = 0$$
fields.title: Vector Algebra

fields.content: (1) Commutative Law: $$a + b = b + a$$  ;(2) Associative Law: $$a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c$$  ;(3) Commutative Law of Scalar Multiplication: $$\lambda a = a \lambda$$  ;(4) Associative Law of Scalar Multiplication: $$\lambda (\mu a) = (\lambda \mu)a$$  ;(5) Distributive Law of Scalar Multiplication: ;(i) $$(\lambda + \mu)a = \lambda a + \mu a$$  ;(ii)$$\lambda (a + b) = \lambda a + \lambda b$$
fields.title: Laws of Vector Algebra

fields.content: Given two points A and B on the plane with position vectors a and b: The mid point M of AB with position vector m is given by: $$m = \frac{a + b}{2}$$
fields.title: Vector Theorems - Mid Point Theorem

fields.content: Given two points A and B on the plane with position vectors a and b: the point M with position vector m which divides AB internally in the ratio $$\lambda : \mu$$ is given by $$m = \frac{\mu a + \lambda b}{\lambda + \mu}$$
fields.title: Vector Theorems - Ratio Theorem

fields.content: Given two points $$A(a_{1},a_{2})$$ and $$B(b_{1},b_{2})$$; distance between A and B is given by : $$AB = |\overrightarrow{AB}| = \sqrt{(b_{1} - a_{1})^2 + (b_{2} - a_{2})^2}$$
fields.title: Distance between Two Points in a Two - Dimensional Plane

fields.content: Given two points $$A(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3})$$ and $$B(b_{1},b_{2},b_{3})$$; distance between A and B is given by : $$AB = |\overrightarrow{AB}| = \sqrt{(b_{1} - a_{1})^2 + (b_{2} - a_{2})^2 + (b_{3} - a_{3})^2}$$
fields.title: Distance between Two Points in a Three - Dimensional Plane

fields.content: The Scalar Product or Dot Product or Inner Product of a and b, denoted by $$a \bullet b$$ is defined by $$a \bullet b = |a||b|\cos \theta$$ where $$\theta$$ is the angle between a and b
fields.title: Scalar Product of Two Vectors

fields.content: (1) $$a \bullet b$$ is a scalar, and not a vector.  ;(2) If either a = 0 or b = 0, then $$a \bullet b = 0$$  ;(3) Commutative Law: $$a \bullet b = b \bullet a$$  ;(4) Distributive Law: $$a \bullet (b + c) = (a \bullet b) + ( a \bullet c)$$  ;(5) $$\lambda (a \bullet b) = (\lambda a) \bullet b = a \bullet (\lambda b)$$ and $$\alpha a \bullet \beta b = (\alpha \times \beta)a \bullet b$$  ;(6)$$a \bullet b > 0 \iff 0^{o} < \theta < 90^{o}$$ and $$a \bullet b < 0 \iff 90^{o} < \theta < 180^{o}$$
fields.title: Properties of Scalar Product

fields.content: (a) Parallel Vectors: $$a // b$$ and in the same direction $$\iff a \bullet b = |a||b| = ab$$  ;(b) Perpendicular Vectors: $$a \bot b \iff a \bullet b = 0$$
fields.title: Scalar Product of Parallel and Perpendicular Vectors

fields.content: $$a \bullet b = |a||b| \cos \theta \Rightarrow \cos \theta = \frac{a \bullet b}{|a||b|} = \hat{a} \bullet \hat{b} \Rightarrow \theta = \cos^{-1} (\hat{a} \bullet \hat{b})$$
fields.title: Applications of Scalar Product - Angle Between Two Vectors

fields.content: $$ p = |\frac{a \bullet b}{b}|$$ or $$|a \bullet \hat{b}|$$
fields.title: Applications of Scalar Product - Projection

fields.content: $$a \times b = |a||b|\sin \theta \hat{n}$$ or $$ab \sin \theta \hat{n}$$ where $$\theta$$ is the angle between a and b and $$\hat{n}$$ is the unit vector perpendicular to both a and b
fields.title: Vector Product of Two Vectors

fields.content: (i) $$a \times b$$ is a vector, which is normal to the plane containing both a and b.  ;(ii) If either $$a = 0$$ or $$b = 0$$, then $$a \times b = 0$$  ;(iii) Vector Product is not commutative: $$a \times b \neq b \times a$$  ;(iv) Distributive Law of Vector Product: $$a \times ( b + c) = (a \times b) + (a \times c)$$  ;(v) $$\lambda (a \times b) = (\lambda a) \times b = a \times ( \lambda b)$$ and $$(\alpha a) \times (\beta b) = \alpha \beta (a \times b)$$
fields.title: Properties of Vector Product

fields.content: (a) Parallel Vectors: $$a // b \iff a \times b$$ and $$|a \times b| = 0$$  ;(b) Perpendicular Vectors: $$a \bot b \iff a \times b = |a||b| \hat{n} = ab \hat{n}$$ and $$ |a \times b| = |a||b| = ab$$
fields.title: Vector Product of Parallel and Perpendicular Vectors

fields.content: (i) $$OP$$ is the Length of Projection of a onto b: $$OP = |a|\cos \theta = \frac{|a \bullet b|}{|b|}$$ and $$\overrightarrow{OP} = (a \bullet \hat{b}) \hat{b}$$  ;(ii) $$P$$ is the Foot of the Perpendicular from $$A$$ to $$OB$$ and $$AP$$ is the Perpendicular Distance from $$A$$ to $$OB$$  ;$$AP = |a|\sin \theta = \frac{|a \times b|}{|b|}$$ and $$\overrightarrow{AP} = \overrightarrow{OP} - \overrightarrow{OA} = (a \bullet \hat{b}) \hat{b} - a$$
fields.title: Geometric Relation between Scalar and Vector Products

fields.content: Area of parallelogram $$OACB = |a \times b|$$
fields.title: Area of a Parallelogram

fields.content: Area of triangle $$OAB = \frac{1}{2}|a \times b|$$
fields.title: Area of a Triangle

fields.content: (a) Given a Known Fixed Point and a Specified Direction: Given that a Line $$l$$ passes through a Fixed Point $$A$$ with Position Vector $$a = a_{1}i + a_{2}j + a_{3}k$$ and that line $$l$$ is parallel to a Specified Direction given by a Direction Vector $$b = b_{1}i + b_{2}j + b_{3}k$$ then a Vector Equation of the Line $$l$$ is given by: $$r = a + \lambda b$$, $$\lambda \in R$$  ;;(b) Given that a Line $$l$$ passes through Two Fixed Points $$A$$ and $$B$$ with position vectors $$a$$ and $$b$$ respectively, then a direction vector of the line $$l$$ is given by $$\overrightarrow{AB} = b - a$$ or $$\overrightarrow{BA} = a- b$$, thus the Vector Equation of the Line $$l$$ is given by: $$r = a + \lambda (b - a)$$ or $$r = a + \lambda (a - b)$$ or $$r = b + \lambda (b - a)$$ or $$r = b + \lambda (a - b)$$ where $$\lambda \in R$$
fields.title: Vector Equation of a Straight Line
Cartesian Equation of a Straight Line

fields.content: Given that a Plane $$\pi$$ passes through a Fixed Point $$A$$ with a position vector $$a = a_{1}i + a_{2}j + a_{3}k$$, and that $$\pi$$ is parallel to 2 non-parallel Direction Vectors $$b = b_{1}i + b_{2}j + b_{3}k$$ and $$c = c_{1}i + c_{2}j + c_{3}k$$, then a Vector Equation of the Plane $$\pi$$ in Parametric Form is given by: $$r = a + \lambda b + \mu c$$, where $$ \lambda , \mu \in R$$
fields.title: Vector Equation of a Plane - Parametric Form

fields.content: Given that a Plane $$\pi$$ passes through a Fixed Point $$A$$ with a position vector $$a = a_{1}i + a_{2}j + a_{3}k$$, and that $$\pi$$ is perpendicular to a Normal Vector $$n = n_{1}i + n_{2}j + n_{3}k$$, then a Vector Equation of the Plane $$\pi$$ in Scalar Product Form is given by: $$r \bullet n = a \bullet n = p$$ or $$r \bullet \hat{n} = a \bullet \hat{n} = d$$
fields.title: Vector Equation of a Plane - Scalar Product Form

fields.content: Given that a plane $$\pi$$ passes through a Fixed Point $$A$$ with position vector $$a = a_{1}i + a_{2}j + a_{3}k$$, and that $$\pi$$ is perpendicular to a Normal Vector $$n = n_{1}i + n_{2}j + n_{3}k$$:;$$r \bullet n = a \bullet n$$;$$ax + by + cz = p$$
fields.title: Vector Equation of a Plane - Cartesian

fields.content: (i) Plane $$\pi$$ passes through $$A(a_{1}, a_{2}, a_{3})$$ and parallel to the xy - plane: $$z = a_{3}$$;(ii) Plane $$\pi$$ passes through $$A(a_{1}, a_{2}, a_{3})$$ and parallel to the xz - plane: $$y = a_{2}$$;(iii) Plane $$\pi$$ passes through $$A(a_{1}, a_{2}, a_{3})$$ and parallel to the yz - plane: $$x = a_{1}$$
fields.title: Vector Equation of a Plane - Planes Parallel to the Co-ordinate Planes

fields.content: (a) A Point Lying on A Line:;;(i) Given a Point $$P(p_{1}, p_{2}, p_{3})$$ and a line $$l : \frac{x - a_{1}}{b_{1}} = \frac{y - a_{2}}{b_{2}} = \frac{z - a_{3}}{b_{3}}$$:;P lies on $$l \iff \frac{p_{1} - a_{1}}{b_{1}} = \frac{p_{2} - a_{2}}{b_{2}} = \frac{p_{3} - a_{3}}{b_{3}}$$;Otherwise P does not lie on $$l$$.;(ii) Given a Point $$P$$ with position vector $$p = p_{1}i + p_{2}j + p_{3}k$$ and a line $$l: r = a + \lambda b$$;P lies on $$l \iff p = a + \lambda b$$ gives a Unique Solution for $$\lambda$$;Otherwise P does not lie on $$l$$.;;(b) Foot of the Perpendicular from a Point to a Line:;(i) Since $$F$$ lies on $$l$$ : $$\overrightarrow{OF} = a + \lambda b$$;(ii) $$\overrightarrow{PF} = \overrightarrow{OF} - \overrightarrow{OP} = a + \lambda b - p$$;(iii) Since $$\overrightarrow{PR} \bot l$$: $$\overrightarrow{PF} \bullet b = 0$$ Solve for $$\lambda$$;(iv) Substitute $$\lambda$$ into $$\overrightarrow{OF}$$ : $$\overrightarrow{OF} = a + \lambda b$$;;(c) Perpendicular Distance from a Point to a Line;(i) Since $$F$$ lies on $$l$$ : $$\overrightarrow{OF} = a + \lambda b$$;(ii) $$\overrightarrow{PF} = \overrightarrow{OF} - \overrightarrow{OP} = a + \lambda b - p$$;(iii) Since $$\overrightarrow{PR} \bot l$$: $$\overrightarrow{PF} \bullet b = 0$$ Solve for $$\lambda$$;(iv) Substitute $$\lambda$$ into $$\overrightarrow{PF}$$ : $$\overrightarrow{PF} = a + \lambda b - p$$;(v) $$PF = |\overrightarrow{PF}| = |a + \lambda b - p|$$;
fields.title: Three Dimensional Vector Geometry - A Point and A Line

fields.content: (a) Parallel, Intersecting and Skew Lines:;(i) Parallel Lines: $$l_{1} // l_{2} \iff b_{1} // b_{2} \iff b_{1} = k b_{2}$$;(ii) Intersecting Lines: $$b_{1} \neq k b_{2}$$ and $$r_{1} = r_{2} \implies a_{1} + \lambda b_{1} = a_{2} + \mu b_{2}$$ gives a unique pair of solution for $$\lambda$$ and $$\mu$$;(iii) Skew Lines: $$b_{1} \neq k b_{2}$$ and $$r_{1} = r_{2} \implies a_{1} + \lambda b_{1} = a_{2} + \mu b_{2}$$ has no unique pair of solution for $$\lambda$$ and $$\mu$$;;(b) Angle Between a Pair of Lines;Given a pair of intersecting or a pair of skew lines:;$$l_{1} : r_{1} = a_{1} + \lambda b_{1}$$;$$l_{2} : r_{2} = a_{2} + \mu b_{2}$$;$$\theta  = \cos^{-1} \frac{|b_{1} \bullet b_{2}|}{|b_{1}||b_{2}|}$$ or $$\cos^{-1}| \hat{b_{1}} \bullet \hat{b_{2}}|$$;;(c) Distance Between a Pair of Parallel Lines;Given a pair of parallel lines:;$$l_{1} : r_{1} = a_{1} + \lambda b_{1}$$;$$l_{2} : r_{2} = a_{2} + \mu b_{2}$$;Perpendicular distance $$d = |(a_{1} - a_{2}) \times \hat{b}|$$
fields.title: Three Dimensional Vector Geometry - A Pair of Lines

fields.content: (a) Three cases;(i) Line lies on Plane: Substituting $$r = a + \lambda b$$ into $$r \bullet n = p$$ : $$(a + \lambda b) \bullet n = p$$ satisfied for all $$\lambda \in R$$;(ii) Line is parallel to but does not lie on Plane: Substituting $$r = a + \lambda b$$ into $$r \bullet n = p$$ : $$(a + \lambda b) \bullet n = p$$ not satisfied for any $$\lambda \in R$$;(iii) Line is not parallel to Plane: Substituting $$r = a + \lambda b$$ into $$r \bullet n = p$$ : $$(a + \lambda b) \bullet n = p$$ satisfied for a value of $$\lambda$$;;(b) Angle Between a Line and a Plane;Given a line $$l: r = a + \lambda b$$ and a plane $$\pi : r \bullet n = p$$;The Angle $$\theta$$ between the line and the plane $$\pi$$ is given by: ;$$\theta = \sin^{-1} \frac{|b \bullet n|}{|b||n|}$$ or $$\theta = \sin^{-1} |\hat{b} \bullet \hat{n}|$$;;(c) Projection of a Vector Onto a Plane;Given a vector $$v$$ and a plane $$\pi: r \bullet n = p$$:;Length of Projection $$q = |v \times \hat{n}|$$;;(d) Distance Between a Plane and a Parallel Line;(i) $$\pi$$': $$r \bullet n = a \bullet n = p'$$;(ii) $$ r  = \frac{|p - p'|}{|n|}$$;Thus $$ r =  \frac{|p - a \bullet n|}{|n|}$$
fields.title: Three Dimensional Vector Geometry - A Line and A Plane
